<title>Jun_1993: Re: Post-institutionalism</title>
<h1>Re: Post-institutionalism</h1>
Bill Nickless (<i>nickless@mcs.anl.gov</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 27 Jun 1993 00:57:25 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#275">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#275">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#275">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#275">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0276.html">Steven Timm: "L'Establishment, c'est moi"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0274.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Self-supporting institutions"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0209.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Post-institutionalism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This is the fourth start of this note.  Usually I try to make my messages<br>
clear, structured, and coherent.  But I have a strong emotional reaction to<br>
the question of Adventist education that's difficult to completely spell out<br>
in a concise, rational framework.<br>
<p>
Personal history: I started grade school in the Glen Park Seventh-day<br>
Adventist Church School in Gary/Hobart Indiana.  Grades 2-4 were spent there.<br>
In fourth grade my family moved to Dillingham, Alaska, where my father (hi,<br>
Dad! [he's here on the net too]) took on the role of mission pilot/pastor in<br>
Dillingham and for believers in a, what, 200 mile radius?  I spent fourth<br>
through eighth grade in the Dillingham Seventh-day Adventist Church School.<br>
Grade 9 was from Home Study International, with one class a day (Advanced<br>
Computer Literacy) in the Dillingham High School (well financed and equipped<br>
from Prudhoe Bay oil revenues--this was the '82-'83 school year.)  In 1983 my<br>
family moved to Ketchikan, Alaska, and I moved to Spangle, Washington--Upper<br>
Columbia Academy.  When I graduated in 1986 from UCA, my parents were in<br>
Michigan, so I attended Andrews University from 1987 to 1991 (except for<br>
Winter and Spring quarters 1990 which were spent at Argonne National<br>
Laboratory near Chicago, my current employer) graduating with a Bachelor of<br>
Science in Computer Science.<br>
<p>
Stream of consciousness follows:<br>
<p>
Gary/Hobart: first real experience dealing with kids my own age on a<br>
day-to-day basis.  Learned to take responsibility feeding the fish.  :)<br>
<p>
Dillingham grade school: Totally new environment and set of people to know.<br>
Not particularly pleasant.  Lets just say that I was not a typical Alaskan at<br>
the time, with weird interests in science, computers, and electricity.  In<br>
eighth grade, however, a new teacher came to town: Jim Beirle.  He enjoyed<br>
math and science and knew what a computer was, and really encouraged me that<br>
I was O.K.  8th grade was great.<br>
<p>
9th grade &amp; high school: Mostly boring.  Home study takes time, and its hard<br>
to self-motivate.  I much preferred the computer lab over in the high school,<br>
and had a lot of fun playing with the Apple IIs.  (One of the Apples was<br>
serial number 634.)  Gained the respect of the wrestling team captain and the<br>
senior class valedictorian, both of which happened to be taking the class with<br>
me.  For my part, I learned that non-Adventists could be nice, honest people<br>
too.<br>
<p>
Upper Columbia Academy: Totally new environment and set of people to know.<br>
This (as opposed to Dillingham) was much better.  I was able to make friends<br>
and carve out a social niche for myself.  For you Broadview, Wisconsin,<br>
Adelphian, Indiana, and other Midwest school alumini: they let the boys walk<br>
and girls alternate days to walk to town, alone, unescorted.  I had problems<br>
with the rules there too, but until nearly the end of my senior year didn't<br>
have any real run-ins with the disciplinary side of the administration.  (I<br>
really did deserve any discipline I received for that incident--and this note<br>
doesn't say what it was.)<br>
<p>
Andrews: Excellent education.  Because the department was small, classes were<br>
generally taught by professors.  I worked for teachers.  I got to know them.<br>
They treated me like a person, able to take responsibility and to have<br>
credible ideas.  I like to think that I, as a student, was given the<br>
opportunity to help shape their existing computing infrastructure--internal<br>
and external networking, etc.  This is the kind of education you simply don't<br>
get at public universities until the graduate level or later.  Kudos to the<br>
Computer Science Department at Andrews.  Way To Go.  Keep It Up!<br>
<p>
I brought up the "walk to town" bit above for a reason.  While at Andrews, an<br>
acquaintance went to Thunderbird Academy in Arizona to act as an assistant<br>
dean.  He came back, literally shaking his head at the insolence, disrespect,<br>
and worldliness of the students there.  Saving his point best point to last,<br>
he told his (shocked, nearly disbelieving) friends who had also attended<br>
Midwest academies "they even let the students WALK TO TOWN ALONE!"<br>
<p>
Except for my (now) wife and I sitting at the table, he convinced everyone.<br>
At UCA, TracyAnne and I regularly (on separate days) walked into town to buy<br>
corn chips and soda pop, and sometimes play video games in the little mom &amp;<br>
pop store.  Fun times.  I had a checking account at the Bank of Fairfield in<br>
Spangle.  For a while I even had a post office box at the US Post Office.<br>
Never did get up the nerve to order Playboy, though.  :) :) :) But isn't that<br>
sort of the point?<br>
<p>
I remember clearly a wise observation I overheard my father share.  In<br>
Dillingham, Alaska, 13, 14, 15, 16 year old kids run million-dollar fishing<br>
boats while the other crewmembers sleep.  They are paid and learn to<br>
handle/mishandle thousands of dollars of their own money.  (No exagguration: I<br>
worked three days on a fishing boat my 7-8th grade summer.  I made $1,247.33.<br>
After paying the $800 or so for my 8th grade school year, I still had $300 or<br>
so to spend.  And remember, I was working, by then, 10-20 hours a week at<br>
$4-$7/hour in the local public library.  I earned my &gt;$1000 entrance fee to<br>
UCA fair and square working, in about a month.)  When they go to an Adventist<br>
academy, they end up working on the grounds crew, with an old, authoritarian<br>
brother telling them in excruciating detail exactly how to mix the gas for the<br>
lawnmower, and warning them over and over of the dangers of electric shock<br>
from the spark plug.  Any wonder why many kids develop "bad attitudes"?<br>
<p>
I went to a boarding academy 1500-2500 miles from my parents.  When leaves<br>
came, I stayed at the academy or went home with friends.  During leave, when I<br>
spent time on campus, the rules changed.  Stay in the gym or up at the ball<br>
field until 7:30, then in the dorm until 6 in the morning?  No way!  6 inches<br>
from girlfriend or social (no contact: verbal, written, direct or indirect<br>
with girlfriend for prescribed period of time)?  Ha!  We were sitting on the<br>
lawn at 10:30 one night, enjoying the clear evening, and waved to the girls'<br>
dean as she walked by with her dog.  No Problem.<br>
<p>
I have this notion that if you work/study hard, behave yourself, act<br>
intelligently and responsibly, and do your best to be a likable person, you<br>
should be respected and trusted.  At UCA (during the school sessions,) and<br>
from the aspect of those who run the residence halls and other student<br>
services at Andrews, this is utterly and completely false.  TRADITIONAL<br>
ADVENTIST EDUCATION "KNOWS" WHAT IS BEST FOR THE STUDENTS, WHO CANNOT EVER BE<br>
TRUSTED TO KNOW WHAT'S BEST FOR THEMSELVES.  AND, OF COURSE, SINCE WE (THE<br>
OUTNUMBERED AND UNDERSTAFFED ADMINISTRATORS) MUST CONTROL THEIR BEHAVIOR,<br>
NEEDS OF STUDENTS FOR SELF-DETERMINATION AND SELF-RESPONSIBILITY MUST<br>
NECESSARILY TAKE A LOW PRIORITY.  Until, in college, you reach the age of 22,<br>
or get married, whichever is first.  I have tried to reason with Andrews<br>
dormitory and Student Affairs personnel, and at times Campus safety, with<br>
generally dismal results.<br>
<p>
For example: in 1988 I suggested, personally and verbally, to Dean Knight or<br>
Dean Murray that dormitory worship services be held at an accessible time in<br>
the Andrews Science Complex, sometime around 6:30 or 7:30 in the evening.  I<br>
repeated this suggestion personally and verbally to Newton Hoilette when he<br>
first arrived and met with students in the cafeteria.  He had heard of the<br>
idea, but it just never was important enough to matter.  When my wife<br>
graduated in 1992 it had still not been acted upon.  <br>
<p>
For any Andrews faculty member reading this, I offer this challenge: pick a<br>
week in February.  Every night that week, start at the science complex and<br>
walk to the mens' dorm--I'll make it easy: Meier--and join any of the hall<br>
worships at 7:00 or deans worship at 7:00 on Thursday.  Then walk back to the<br>
science complex and teach your 7:30 class.  You can't drive your car, because<br>
parking around the dorms is reserved for residence hall residents, and it is<br>
the only place on campus they can legally park.<br>
<p>
Who is Adventist education for?  I hope the answer to that is the students.<br>
<p>
Working with IBM over the past year has been an amazing education in how hard<br>
they will work to make "the customer" happy.  If you ever work with IBM, at<br>
least their Scientific Supercomputing groups or their Federal Systems Company,<br>
the most powerful thing you can tell your IBM rep to say is that something is<br>
"unacceptable to the customer."  If you hear of an internal IBM discussion<br>
about whether or not to do something for you--and you don't particularly need<br>
or want it, you say that "this customer is completely satisfied with the<br>
current situation, and would find &lt;whatever&gt; unnecessary, and probably<br>
unacceptable."  As a relatively low-level representative of the customer, it<br>
takes someone pretty high up in the management ranks of IBM to overrule me.<br>
(Or, at least that's the impression they've successfully left!  :)<br>
<p>
So must Adventist education be.  Adventist education was originally started to<br>
meet the needs and desires of Seventh-day Adventist Christian families who<br>
wanted to have their children brought up in an environment compatible with<br>
their beliefs on doctrine and lifestyle.  So be it.  But at least this<br>
"customer" has gone away from Adventist education (along with an excellent<br>
technical education and fond memories of many other teachers and students) a<br>
deep-seated bitterness over my treatement at the hands and rules of Adventist<br>
educational establishment.<br>
<p>
Until Adventist education can shed its image of hassling students over<br>
seemingly trivial rules that nobody (not even those enforcing them) really<br>
believe in, and start treating the students as people worthy of respect and<br>
potential (not guaranteed or able-to-be-forced) souls for the Kingdom,<br>
enrollment will continue to decline.<br>
<p>
I was told once by a college residence hall dean: "Look, Bill: most of these<br>
rules are there so we can enforce them if we need to.  Part of life in any<br>
large organization is learning what rules are important and which are not."<br>
He was defending the existing rules by saying they weren't generally relevant<br>
and were capriciously enforced!  The curfew checks and so forth are supposedly<br>
"because we worry about you if you're not here" but have the civil authorities<br>
ever been alerted that so-and-so isn't back in the dorm yet, it's a<br>
blizzard/tornado/hurricane out there, and we're worried?  But after the fourth<br>
false fire alarm in a night, they won't give you a pass to go for a walk<br>
outside at 3:00AM on a clear warm spring night to relax.  Not policy....<br>
<p>
Andrews Advertisers: if you want a glowing recommendation of the Andrews<br>
University Computer Science Department, refer people to me.  You'll be hard<br>
pressed to find a more positive yet honestly believed endorsement.  <br>
<p>
However, while the parent is still on the phone or reading my electronic mail<br>
response I will tell the parents to rent/buy a house, apartment or trailer<br>
near Berrien Springs, call it the/a family residence, and claim that the<br>
student is living at home and doesn't need a meal plan or a dorm room.  That<br>
way they can enjoy the benefits of an Adventist education, friends, and social<br>
environment without the tyrannical oppression of people "who know what's best<br>
for them."  (I can offer hints for maintaining the illusion to the right<br>
people, too.  Michigan Bell sells Call Forwarding pretty cheap.  Who knows<br>
where (616) 473-pqrs might actully ring?)<br>
<p>
Sorry for the length and the rambling, but that's what SDAnet is for.  Right,<br>
Steve?  :)<br>
<p>
Thanks for your patience, and I really do wish the best for Adventist<br>
education.<br>
<pre>
---
Bill Nickless System Support Group &lt;nickless@mcs.anl.gov&gt; +1 708 252 7390
<p>
(Obviously I'm not speaking for Argonne National Laboratory, the Department of
                         Energy, or even IBM!)
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
