<title>Jul_1992: Re: New Directions for SDA-L</title>
<h1>Re: New Directions for SDA-L</h1>
Jeff Tosk (<i>UMBJTO%LLUVM.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 6 Jul 1992 16:58:32 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#17">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#17">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#17">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#17">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0018.html">Lola: "Libertarian SDAs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Steven Timm: "Test"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0004.html">Steven Timm: "New Directions for SDA-L"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; A topic:</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Why do the "Right to Life" people almost never speak up about</i><br>
<i>&gt; drunk driving (causes tens of thousands of deaths per year), war,</i><br>
<i>&gt; capital punishment and other needless loss of life?</i><br>
 <br>
Why does the Sierra Club not speak up on the First Amendment, or<br>
gun rights, or ...<br>
 <br>
The "Right to Life" descriptor isn't a very good one in that it<br>
uses a phrase with a very wide potential set of meanings to label<br>
a movement that is focused on a single question.<br>
 <br>
Don't you know anyone who belongs to more than one organization?<br>
A person may be interested in more than one thing, and trying to<br>
get any given organization to address *all* the potential interests<br>
of its members will result in one that is so diluted as to be of<br>
no interest to anyone.<br>
 <br>
Or do you think that the NRA is wrong to not address the problem<br>
of third-world hunger, to make an extreme example?  (I know an NRA<br>
member who also belongs to the Sierra Club and the ACLU, among other<br>
things.  She's interested in the various foci of these organizations,<br>
so she gives each some of her time and financial support.)<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; What is their real issue?</i><br>
 <br>
Maybe opposing abortion is the only issue that some members of the<br>
above-mentioned movement are interested in.  Most of them have more<br>
interests than that one, but I suspect that they address them in<br>
other fora.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; They don't seem very loving or concerned with the quality of life.</i><br>
 <br>
Odd.  Some of those that you seem to be talking about that *I* know<br>
I'd describe in completely different terms...some others I'd be afraid<br>
to let into my neighborhood.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; They have even taken life from time to time in</i><br>
<i>&gt; the form of bombings and burnings.</i><br>
 <br>
Would you say that those in the 1970's anti-war movement who bombed<br>
computer centers and so on were typical of the entire population of<br>
the anti-war movement?<br>
 <br>
Any group who feel strongly about some subject will include extremists<br>
of one type or another.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; Where are they really comming from?</i><br>
 <br>
Foes of abortion or just the extremists?<br>
 <br>
Personally, I've almost given up with either side to point of wishing<br>
a pox on both their houses.  Not because of the "average" member of<br>
either side, but from having to deal with extremists of either side.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
