<title>Jul_1992: Special day of prayer</title>
<h1>Special day of prayer</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun,  5 Jul 1992 19:17:41 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#15">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#15">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#15">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#15">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Steven Timm: "Test"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">callen roy: "Re:  "Discovered--Noah's Ark""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0023.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Special day of prayer"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In a letter to all N. American SDA churches, (it was read in mine this<br>
past Sabbath), A. C. McClure called for a special day of prayer with<br>
regard to issues of religious liberty and issues of church and state. <br>
While not taking any stand on any particular court decision, it referred<br>
to "recent troubling decisions of the Supreme Court."<br>
<p>
Was this letter read from the pulpit elsewhere in other SDA churches? <br>
Was there any response to it?<br>
<p>
In our case, the letter was followed by a message from a guest speaker,<br>
preaching on Judges 17 and 18, which had five different sides and none<br>
of them were right, stressing the point that right and left is not the<br>
same <br>
as right and wrong.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Steven Timm: "Test"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">callen roy: "Re:  "Discovered--Noah's Ark""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0023.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Special day of prayer"</a>
</ul>
