<title>Jul_1992: Re: Enoch and Moses</title>
<h1>Re: Enoch and Moses</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  1 Jul 1992 22:49:56 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#3">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#3">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#3">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#3">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0004.html">Steven Timm: "New Directions for SDA-L"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0002.html">Steven Timm: "Re: alt.sdanet"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Glen McCluskey asks some questions about Enoch.  First, Mary was dogmaed<br>
into heaven in 1954 by the Catholics, but I've not heard of anyone else<br>
going to heaven recently.<br>
<p>
The more important question was, essentially, "does walking with God<br>
as Enoch did require that you be a hermit?"  I would argue the opposite.<br>
Though it has been a while since I read the particular section of<br>
Patriarchs and Prophets, I recall that in his day Enoch was known as a<br>
prophet, and was <br>
well known to the people of his day.  He did not shun contact, but<br>
thrived from it.  However, he did have a place of retreat where he could<br>
be alone with God.<br>
<p>
We find the same behavior exhibited by Christ:  Close and frequent<br>
contact with people, broken by long times of solitary prayer and<br>
meditation.<br>
I would not say it is impossible to be a Christian whilst locked up in<br>
your closet, but such a position makes it more difficult to love your<br>
fellow man.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
