<title>Jul_1992: New Directions for SDA-L</title>
<h1>New Directions for SDA-L</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+%ANDREW.CMU.EDU%CMU.EDU@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 1 Jul 1992 23:24:15 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#4">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#4">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#4">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#4">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Jeff Tosk: "Re: New Directions for SDA-L"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Enoch and Moses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0017.html">Jeff Tosk: "Re: New Directions for SDA-L"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Some history for new members:<br>
SDA-L was created in late 1990 as a list for fellowship among SDA<br>
students and faculty, particularly those at secular universities.  In<br>
early 1991 it was discovered by the moderator of SDAnet (that's me,<br>
Steve Timm), who immediately proposed a two-way cross-distribution of<br>
messages between the two lists.  This led to record traffic on both<br>
lists.<br>
 <br>
Few people were happy with the arrangement, SDA-L people because they<br>
didn't want so much traffic or such controversial topics, SDAnet people<br>
because<br>
the cross-link defeated the moderation of the list.  So it was agreed that<br>
the SDAnet side would stop sending messages to SDA-L.  SDAnet was to be<br>
the place for controversial topics and inquiries from non-SDA's, while<br>
SDA-L would retreat to topics of fellowship and survival in the<br>
university world.<br>
Also the SDA-L echo to SDAnet would continue.  At this time several of<br>
the big mouths on SDA-L signed up to SDAnet and started directing their<br>
posts there, and traffic on SDA-L dropped essentially to zero, where it<br>
has stayed ever since.<br>
 <br>
So now the question is, what else is there that's discussable on SDA-L<br>
 <br>
1)  If you like the low traffic the way it is, don't say anything.<br>
2)  Otherwise, post on a topic of your choice, and we'll see how it works.<br>
 <br>
 From my experience with being the moderator of SDAnet, I have found that<br>
traffic only keeps going if every once in a while someone takes a real<br>
effort to liven it up.  I'm not prepared to be the provocateur on SDA-L<br>
as well.  I think what we need is a collective of several people who<br>
take responsibility for content of the list, and by this I mean, generate<br>
some content.  The listowners have enough trouble maintaining the mechanics<br>
of the list.<br>
 <br>
Jerome Grimmer is researching whether or not we can have a library of files<br>
available for people to get.  This important service is something SDAnet<br>
can't provide.  We need more people, particularly people who are going<br>
to be in the same place for a few years, to guarantee the stability of<br>
the content of the list.  Like Christine, Jerome and I are students and<br>
will eventually have to move on. (Although I can't imagine working at a<br>
place without net access).  If you see a niche you can fill, please<br>
speak up.  If nobody responds, we'll assume everyone likes the low SDA-L<br>
traffic and we don't have a problem.<br>
 <br>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
