<title>Jul_1992: Holy Spirit and Conscience</title>
<h1>Holy Spirit and Conscience</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  1 Jul 1992 21:59:18 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#6">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#6">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#6">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#6">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: "Discovered--Noah's Ark""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Jeff Tosk: "Re: New Directions for SDA-L"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0008.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Holy Spirit and Conscience"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
(I fully expected school choice to get more response than the Holy Spirit.<br>
But I'm not giving up.  I'll continue to post about the Holy Spirit as long <br>
as I keep learning something, and I encourage others to do the same.)<br>
<p>
One of the functions of the Holy Spirit is to reprove for sin. (John 16:8,9).<br>
We become convinced of the wrongness of a deed as the Holy Spirit speaks<br>
to our conscience (and here I include the ministry of the Spirit through<br>
the <br>
word of God.)  This knowledge leads to a repentance and a turning away<br>
from sin.<br>
<p>
Yet I fear that sometimes this understanding of the Holy Spirit can be<br>
misused.  Often you hear somebody say "The Holy Spirit hasn't told me<br>
this is important as yet," often with regard to the Sabbath.  In some<br>
cases the person is absolutely sincere in this.  Others seem like<br>
blatant ignorance or abuse of the principle.  <br>
<p>
How should these circumstances be handled?  Is the Holy Spirit a license<br>
to do as we please?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
