<title>Jul_1992: Re: right to life</title>
<h1>Re: right to life</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 2 Jul 1992 10:38:16 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#10">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#10">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#10">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#10">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Steven Timm: "Right to Life"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Daniel R. Bidwell: "Re: Evolution at Andrews University"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Why do the "Right to Life" people almost never speak up about drunk</i><br>
<i>&gt; driving (causes tens of thousands of deaths per year), war, capital</i><br>
<i>&gt; punishment and other needless loss of life?  What is their real issue?</i><br>
<i>&gt; They don't seem very loving or concerned with the quality of life.</i><br>
<i>&gt; They have even taken life from time to time in the form of bombings</i><br>
<i>&gt; and burnings.  Where are they really comming from?</i><br>
 <br>
Below is an interesting posting showing the views of various special<br>
interest groups on the subject of life.<br>
 <br>
What this illustrates is that these groups are not at all consistent<br>
in their views, perhaps because they don't have a source of divine<br>
inspiration.  I am not sure that we want to get into a discussion of<br>
abortion in this forum.  But it might be profitable to discuss some of<br>
the issues with the Christian view of life:<br>
 <br>
	- humans are created in the image of God<br>
 <br>
	- God says "thou shalt not kill"<br>
 <br>
	- we live in a world that is fallen and sinful<br>
 <br>
	- God blessed the children of Israel and sanctioned their<br>
	killing in some cases (wars)<br>
 <br>
	- Paul can be interpreted to support the formation of a civil<br>
	police function which by its nature sometimes must use deadly<br>
	force<br>
 <br>
	- most of us would support the American Revolution which<br>
	involved the slaughter of the British (guerilla warfare!)<br>
 <br>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
 <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
This information originally came from a SPY magazine survey, reported<br>
by Utne Reader (Jan/Feb, 1992, pg.152, "Kill Ted Bundy!  But save the<br>
cows!").  Given the current discussions on GRANOLA, I thought others<br>
might find this interesting.<br>
 <br>
The following organizations were asked about their position on<br>
life-and- death issues:<br>
 <br>
 * Council for a Livable Word (CLW) - pro-disarmament<br>
 * American Life Lobby (ALL) - anti-abortion<br>
 * Washington Legal Foundation (WLF) - pro-capital punishment<br>
 * National Coalition Against the Death Penalty (NCADP)<br>
 * Ducks Unlimited (DU) - conserve wetlands to provide ducks for hunting<br>
 * People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PeTA)<br>
 * American Vegan Society (AVS) - wear no animal-derived clothing<br>
 <br>
Below are their reponses to each question.<br>
 <br>
1.  Would you kill a human fetus?<br>
 <br>
(CLW)   - Lean toward yes: "We must balance sanctity-of-life against the<br>
                            specter of unlimited population."<br>
(ALL)   - No: "Life is sacred in all cases."<br>
(WLF)   - No: "There is nothing inconsistent with being pro-death<br>
               penalty and pro-life."<br>
(NCADP) - "We have no position; it's not important."<br>
(DU)    - "I can't comment, you know."<br>
(PeTA)  - "We would have to poll our members to find their views."<br>
(AVS)   - No: "It is a living creature whose life we must respect."<br>
 <br>
 <br>
2.  Would you kill a death-row inmate?<br>
 <br>
(CLW)   - No: "This is the destruction of innocent life."<br>
(ALL)   - Yes: "We want to protect all *innocent* life."<br>
(WLF)   - Yes: "You know it.  Sanctity-of-life-does not apply."<br>
(NCADP) - No: "The death penalty is morally wrong."<br>
(DU)    - "Again, I can only talk about fowl."<br>
(PeTA)  - "I can't comment unless a member asked about it."<br>
(AVS)   - No: "It's ridiculous to kill someone to reform him."<br>
 <br>
 <br>
3.  Would you kill a brain-dead person?<br>
 <br>
(CLW)   - No: "Euthanasia is a form of suicide."<br>
(ALL)   - No: "You're dead or you're not dead."<br>
(WLF)   - "I don't know."<br>
(NCADP) - "We can't address that."<br>
(DU)    - No comment.<br>
(PeTA)  - "We don't take a stand on that."<br>
(AVS)   - No.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
4.  Would you kill a soldier in conventional warfare?<br>
 <br>
(CLW)   - Yes: "I would defend my home and country."<br>
(ALL)   - No: "We oppose war."<br>
(WLF)   - "We don't get involved in that."<br>
(NCADP) - "As a group we can't agree."<br>
(DU)    - Yes: "i suppose so. Yes."<br>
(PeTA)  - We'd be more convcerned with animals."<br>
(AVS)   - No: "But we are not passive.  We disarm them with love."<br>
 <br>
 <br>
5.  Would you kill innocent civilians in a nuclear war?<br>
 <br>
(CLW)   - No: "Definitely not."<br>
(ALL)   - No: "We oppose war."<br>
(WLF)   - "No comment."<br>
(NCADP) - "Again, we can't take a position."<br>
(DU)    - No.<br>
(PeTA)  - "Again, we really are concerned with animals."<br>
(AVS)   - "Definitely not."<br>
 <br>
 <br>
6.  Would you kill a cow for food?<br>
 <br>
(CLW)   - Yes.<br>
(ALL)   - Yes: "That's not a concern to us."<br>
(WLF)   - "The only issue we get involved in is the death penalty."<br>
(NCADP) - "We don't address those issues."<br>
(DU)    - "I can only talk about fowl."<br>
(PeTA)  - No: "We oppose any process that harasses an animal."<br>
(AVS)   - No. "We are total vegetarians."<br>
 <br>
 <br>
7.  Would you kill a cat for a lab experiment?<br>
 <br>
(CLW)   - No.<br>
(ALL)   - Yes: "If animal-rights people were honest, even broccoli is<br>
                alive."<br>
(WLF)   - "The only issue we get involved in is the death penalty."<br>
(NCADP) - "I can't say."<br>
(DU)    - No comment.<br>
(PeTA)  - No: "It is wrong to exploit or abuse any animal."<br>
(AVS)   - No: "We oppose any sort of animal torture."<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
