<title>Jul_1992: Right to Life</title>
<h1>Right to Life</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+%ANDREW.CMU.EDU%CMU.EDU@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 2 Jul 1992 11:17:33 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#11">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#11">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#11">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#11">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steven Timm: "Re: View Magazine"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0010.html">McCluskey G: "Re: right to life"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A couple of emailings ago the topic was "Right to Life".<br>
 <br>
Here I am speaking for myself, from my personal perspective as an SDA.<br>
I am not quoting from any SDA publication.  This is just my thinking.<br>
 <br>
SDAs do not believe that an eternally living soul is created at<br>
conception that will live on and on into eternity.  So we do not<br>
hold to any New Age or Catholic or other belief that says that<br>
such an eternal everlasting life must be protected even from the first<br>
nanosecond of life in the womb.  My personal concern for the fetus<br>
begins with the first possibility of real consciousness.  When does<br>
that begin?  I don't think there is a clear answer to the question.<br>
When babies can freely be aborted at an age later than prematures<br>
can readily survive then to me its clear we are well into the time zone<br>
of conscious viable life that is being murdered.  So, for the baby<br>
in the womb, my concern about life escalates throughout the pregnancy.<br>
 <br>
What about mom?  Just as rape has a devastating impact on a woman for<br>
the rest of her life, so does an abortion.  Certainly the sense of<br>
guilt and loss of having terminated a late term pregnancy has got to<br>
weigh heavily on any mother.  To a lesser degree this can also be<br>
true from the first nanosecond after conception.  Before the first<br>
nanosecond of conception in the case of an unmarried couple.<br>
 <br>
Certainly there are circumstances where we are out of blacks and whites<br>
and into the grey.  What about a rape situation?  What about medical<br>
complications?  We cannot be iron clad in ruling what can and cannot<br>
be done.<br>
 <br>
What about a woman's right to decide for herself?  Here is my answer:<br>
I'd like to see somebody put together a video as follows:<br>
 <br>
 * Scenes from the swet shop days; long hours of child labor with<br>
   supervisors brutalizing kids to get yet another ounce of work out<br>
   of tiny kids working the textile mills or what ever.  A scene<br>
   in which the owner of one of these mills turns to the camera and<br>
   says -- "I have a right to do with these kids what ever I want to".<br>
 <br>
 * Scenes of child abuse in the home 50 or more years ago when people<br>
   looked the other way when a mom or dad smashed their child in the<br>
   face with a fist.  And then turns to the camera to say that "I have<br>
   a right to do what ever I like in my own home".<br>
 <br>
 * What about dad beating up mom and turning to the camera to say<br>
   that he has a right to do anything he wants to do in his own house.<br>
 <br>
It is interresting that today a parent can be thrown in jail on the<br>
rumor that he or she has abused a premature child of 6, 7 or 8 months<br>
and yet a 9 month baby not quite yet born can be murdered and that<br>
is considered pro-choice.  To me, pro-choice makes sense as something<br>
that someone else can decide when its decided before a fetus becomes<br>
a conscious fetus.  To me a fetus becomes a baby when its brain can<br>
register pain, certainly by the time mom can first feel activity.<br>
 <br>
I don't believe the laws on abortion should be thrown to the wind, nor<br>
do I believe they should be radical pro-life.  We seem to be polarizing<br>
in this country and that I think is a mistake.  I believe the rules,<br>
just like the taxes, need to be graduated.  Perhaps even no restrictions<br>
at the real early end of the scale.  And a full review board and federal<br>
judge at the other end of the pregnancy.  People seem so humanly<br>
procastinating in their tendency to put off the decision.  So, if<br>
9 months is still ok for an abortion, then people will wait till<br>
the last millisecond of 9 months.  By then we clearly have human life<br>
that could have been a born baby for a month or two, even three these<br>
days with modern prenatal technology.<br>
 <br>
Well, those are my thoughts.  If Steve thinks this topic is too likely<br>
to burn out of control then I'll not protest if this post of mine does<br>
not get posted.<br>
 <br>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
