<title>Jul_1992: the apostacy</title>
<h1>the apostacy</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu,  2 Jul 1992 11:22:12 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#13">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#13">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#13">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#13">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0014.html">callen roy: "Re:  "Discovered--Noah's Ark""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steven Timm: "Re: View Magazine"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
  When does your church say the early Christian church went into<br>
apostacy?  I mean, what date?<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
[The apostasy was a gradual process over a period of hundreds of years.<br>
The Sabbath was already in danger as early as 130 or 140.  Yet we still <br>
accept a New Testament that was only codified in the late 300's as Scripture.<br>
Other practices such as baptism by immersion persisted in the church for<br>
a few hundred years after that (and continue to this day in the Orthodox<br>
church).  The canonical date where the apostate church received power <br>
is 538 AD.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
