<title>Jul_1992: Religious Liberty</title>
<h1>Religious Liberty</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 7 Jul 92 18:31:42 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#20">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#20">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#20">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#20">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Steven Timm: "Our advertisement in current issue of Dialogue"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Joanne Figueredo: "RE: day of prayer"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
With regard to the postings about A.C McClure's letter seeking prayer<br>
about religious liberty issues and how recent court decisions have <br>
turned out, it is significant that the SDA church's Religious Liberty <br>
department is moving toward seeking legislation to protect religious <br>
liberty, rather than relying on constitutional protection alone.  I will<br>
excerpt below a portion of the one-page "Perspective" column in the <br>
May/June 1992 issue of Liberty magazine.  It is entitled "A PLEA TO<br>
CONGRESSIONAL STAFFPERSONS and was released by Gary M. Ross on <br>
May 11, 1992."<br>
<p>
***************************************************************************<br>
<p>
    Religious liberty is no "luxury:"  it remains the inalienable<br>
  right granted by God Himself to His creation and is therefore not <br>
  subject to human manipulation.<br>
<p>
    Because of this verity, the Seventh-day Adventist Church joins many <br>
  other organizations in deploring "Oregon v. Smith" and in advocating <br>
  expeditious consideration by Congress of the reversal bill introduced by<br>
  Mr. Solarz (D-N.Y.)<br>
  ...<br>
  ...<br>
    Egregiously the "Smith" ruling subordinates religious expression to<br>
  laws that are facially neutral and generally applicable.  Redress is <br>
  obtainalbe through exemptions granted by legislatures, but in Justice <br>
  Scalia's own words, "leaving accommodation to the political process will<br>
  place at a relative disadvantage those religious practices that are not<br>
  widely engaged in."<br>
<p>
    But, replied Justice O'Connor, "the First Amendment was enacted <br>
  precisely to protect the rights of those whose religious practices are<br>
  not shared by the majority and may be viewed with hostility."<br>
<p>
    Worse even than vacating a reasonable and workable test, the Court<br>
  (1) did so without argument, inasmuch as the relevant oral arguments <br>
  presupposed that test; (2) subsequently denied a petition for rehearing; <br>
  and (3) immediately demonstrated through "Hershberger" and other findings<br>
  that its new rule of law was not an aberration.<br>
 <br>
    A consensus of historic magnitude underlies the Religious Freedom<br>
  Restoration Act....<br>
<p>
    Enactment of this bill, H.R. 2797, is absolutely imperative.<br>
  ...<br>
  ...<br>
    "Adventists often encounter religious liberty problems in Communist, <br>
  Muslim, and other nations," says Pastor Al McClure, president of the <br>
  church in North America, "but it is sobering to note that the United<br>
  States Supreme Court has upset decades of settled constitutional law<br>
  regarding the most special rights of minorities."<br>
<p>
****************************************************************************<br>
<p>
I assume this is what Pastor McClure had in mind when he sent the letter<br>
some of you netters have referred to to the churches in this division.<br>
It was not read at my home church this past week.  Maybe it was read at<br>
an earlier week and I missed it.  I can understand why it may not be<br>
read.  The pastor in a given Adventist church gets a fair amount of mail <br>
each week (at least, this is what one pastor told me was the case with<br>
him) and there is only so much time in the church service to discuss<br>
matters such as these.  Still, this does seem like an issue important <br>
enough to merit special mention from the pulpit.<br>
<p>
It is sad that we feel we must advocate legislative means to protect what<br>
had long been thought of as a basic constitutional right.  It appears that<br>
such a bill is turning out to be necessary however.<br>
<p>
Any comments?<br>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
