<!-- body="start" -->
Thanks for the reply Steve,<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; [The SDA church official stand is that Genesis 1 is literally true and</i><br>
<i>&gt; that the world was created in six literal days a few thousand years ago.</i><br>
<i>&gt;  Those who believe otherwise have learned to keep their mouth shut. </i><br>
<i>&gt; There are some hints in early Ellen G. White writings of where so-called</i><br>
<i>&gt; apemen fossils may have originated, but no article of faith on this. </i><br>
<i>&gt; The universe is thought to be much older because of our belief that</i><br>
<i>&gt; intelligent life exists elsewhere in it.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Evolution is officially a taboo topic on SDAnet.</i><br>
<p>
Noting your last line here, I am not interested in seeing flames, just <br>
curious.<br>
<p>
I take it from your first paragraph that SDAs must hold views similar to<br>
many Creation Scientists who claim that carbon and other forms of dating<br>
are inaccurate for one or more reasons such as the Flood, speed of light<br>
decreasing, etc.. <br>
<p>
Is this addressed in any rigourous fashion? I'm curious partly because I<br>
like to understand the beliefs of others, and also because I wonder how you<br>
would respond to potential converts who say "well I agree with you about <br>
the Sabbath, but I disagree with regards to you understanding of Genesis."<br>
In an increasingly humanistic society, one needs well thought out answers<br>
to the questions posed by those coming to understand the truth.<br>
<p>
Also, what is the Biblical basis for believing intelligent life (presumably<br>
material, and not spirit) exists elsewhere in the universe?<br>
[The reference to the sons of God in Job 1 is the best clue, also in<br>
the latter part of Job "the morning stars sang together, and all the sons<br>
of God shouted for joy.SCT]<br>
<p>
Thanks,<br>
<p>
Drew Corrigan.<br>
<p>
[Harold Coffin's book "Origin By Design" is perhaps the most complete <br>
setting forth of Biblical Creationism. (Pacific Press, 1983).  He works <br>
for the Geoscience Research Institute, an organization funded by the church <br>
to explore scientific alternatives to the evolutionary hypothesis.  As far<br>
as I know he has never advocated that the speed of light decreased or some <br>
of the really far-out stuff, but he certainly does dispute the conventional<br>
interpretation of organic and inorganic dating methods.<br>
<p>
As to how we should relate to people who have trouble believing the creation <br>
story, I face this problem regularly myself with my "significant other"<br>
and would be open to anyone who has a solution to this problem on the net.SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
