<title>Jul_1992: accepting creationism?</title>
<h1>accepting creationism?</h1>
Danny Kumamoto (<i>kumamoto@verisys.slb.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 9 Jul 92 14:00:51 JST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#24">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#24">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#24">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#24">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Re: accepting creationism?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Special day of prayer"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0025.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Re: accepting creationism?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To SDAnet,<br>
<p>
Steve writes:<br>
<i>&gt; As to how we should relate to people who have trouble believing the creation</i><br>
<i>&gt; story, I face this problem regularly myself with my "significant other"</i><br>
<i>&gt; and would be open to anyone who has a solution to this problem on the net.</i><br>
<p>
"Knowning the Truth About Creation" by Norman L.  Geisler (ISBN<br>
0-89283-389-0, Servant Books, 1989) sort of touches on this issue in<br>
the chapter titled "The Philosophical Arguments:"<br>
<p>
	Rational arguments offer proof but do not necessarily<br>
	persuade unbelievers of God's existence.  They may be <br>
	objectively correct but not always subjectively <br>
	convincing. [...] They can "lead the horse to the <br>
	water," but only the Holy Spirit can persuade a person<br>
	to drink. [pp. 79]<br>
<p>
I haven't read Harold Coffin's "Origin by Design," so I cannot compare<br>
the two, but I think Geisler did a good job presenting the creationist<br>
position, although he didn't do justice to "language." (That is, he<br>
could of at least mention the fact that any honest non-creationistic<br>
linguist would admit that the origin of language is "unknown."  Any<br>
and every language origin theory, excluding extra-terrestrial ones,<br>
has been debunked by linguists, as far as I know.  In fact, today, any<br>
presenter of "language origin" would be laughed off the stage, swiftly<br>
and promptly, by linguists.)<br>
<p>
Books I would recommend for unbelievers (of creationism or just plain<br>
theism) would be C.S. Lewis' "Mere Christianity" and G.K. Chesterson's<br>
"Orthodoxy."  They were both, at best, agnostics before accepting<br>
Christianity AND creationism (I had to write this, since creation no<br>
longer seems to be a part of today's "Christianity." :-) Please note<br>
that their presentations are a bit philosophical (i.e., not a light<br>
reading, in my opinion).<br>
<p>
Danny<br>
<p>
Internet:  kumamoto@verisys.slb.com or kumamoto@sj.ate.slb.com<br>
SLOWNET:   Verisys, Inc. -- An NTT-Schlumberger Company<br>
           2-2-1 Fuchinobe, Sagamihara-shi, Kanagawa-ken 229, Japan<br>
<p>
	Love. Hm.  The older I get, the less I know about such<br>
	large subjects.<br>
				-- Walker Percy, "Lancelot"<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
