<title>Jul_1992: Community Service Work on the Sabbath?</title>
<h1>Community Service Work on the Sabbath?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 13 Jul 1992 10:16:11 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#29">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#29">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#29">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#29">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0030.html">McCluskey G: "service jobs and the Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Historical Trivia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0034.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Community Service Work on the Sabbath?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The following letter to the editor was in the July 6, 1992 Pacific Union<br>
Recorder:<br>
<p>
	SABBATH A DAY OF RESTORATION<br>
<p>
Thank you very much for publicizing in your June 1 issue La Sierra University's<br>
contribution to the clean-up of Los Angeles following the recent uprising. . .<br>
<p>
We are writing to let you know of one correction in your story. According<br>
to the story, members of the La Sierra University community "traveled to<br>
downtwon Los Angeles May 3."  In fact, the La Sierra group whose photograph<br>
appears on page 22 joined in the relief efforts that took place on Sabbath,<br>
May 2.<br>
<p>
While the group was student-organized, it enjoyed the support of University<br>
administrators and faculty members.  The trip was approved by University<br>
President Fritz Guy; and Don Van Orman, vice president for financial affairs,<br>
Bob Dunn, associate dean of the College of ARts and Sciences, and Charles<br>
Teel, Jr., professor of religion and sociology and director of the Stahl Center<br>
for World Service, joined students and others as they worked in LA.<br>
<p>
We believe the University's participation in these Sabbath clean-up efforts<br>
in an appropriate expression of the meaning of the Sabbath.  Deuteronomy 5<br>
makes clear that the purpose of the Sabbath includes renewal of the world:<br>
on the Sabbath, Israel is to rest, as a sign of rest from bondage that they<br>
enjoy because of God's Exodus liberation.  Exodus 20 suggests that the Sabbath<br>
is also an affirmation of the goodness of creation--and thus of the freedom<br>
and dignity of persons as God created them.  Work on behalf of freedom and<br>
dignity is therefore an appropriate form of Sabbath-keeping.<br>
<p>
Finally, Jesus' healing miracles on the Sabbath underscore this fundamental<br>
emphasis on the Sabbath as a day for making the world whole.  That is why<br>
we believe it made sense for LSU to assist in LA on the Sabbath.  And that is<br>
why we believe it is important for RECORDER readers to know that our trip<br>
took place on Sabbath, May 2.<br>
<p>
		Julio C. Munoz, Editor<br>
		Pamela Y. Lowe, Associate Editor<br>
		La Sierra CRITERION<br>
		Riverside, California<br>
<p>
------------------<br>
<p>
I have a few questions for subscribers on SDAnet about this.  First, do you<br>
generally agree that clean-up efforts following the riots in LA was an<br>
appropriate task on the Sabbath?  What would your local SDA congreation say<br>
about this?  Is this an isolated belief or is it generally accepted that<br>
community service projects of this type are appropriate to do on Sabbath<br>
(rather than Sunday) as in this case?  *IF* the Sabbath is "a day for making<br>
for world whole", would clean-up projects like picking up litter along the<br>
freeway, painting over inner-city graffiti, or pulling weeks in a public<br>
park also be appropriate for a Sabbath afternoon?<br>
<p>
What impact do you think this might have on future religious liberty cases<br>
before the Supreme Court in regards to Sabbath observance and a service<br>
employee's refusal to work on the Sabbath?  If clean-up efforts on the<br>
Sabbath (rather than Sunday) is justified as a Sabbath activity, how can<br>
SDA defend a refusal to work in a service-related occupation on the Sabbath?<br>
<p>
My basic understandin of Sabbath observance is that the day has been set<br>
apart by God for His people to refrain from the work and mundane things of this<br>
life.  We have been given six other days every week to take care worldly<br>
things.  I am having difficulty understanding *WHY* LSU decided that this<br>
clean-up effort had to be done on Sabbath.  Why couldn't they do it on Sunday?<br>
Should not out-of-ordinary projects be done on Sabbath *ONLY* if it cannot be<br>
done on another day of the week?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<p>
[Ignoring the fact that this was probably the only time such a group could <br>
be got together, the effort is commendable.  Jesus asked the Pharisees<br>
"Is it lawful to do good on the Sabbath?"  He never got an answer, but he <br>
proceeded to show by actions what His thoughts were on the matter.<br>
Although I personally view the Sabbath as a time primarily for the church <br>
family to focus on healing and building relationships within itself and with <br>
God, I also believe kindness is always appropriate.  <br>
 <br>
If you examine the miracles of Jesus and the number of healings of long-term,<br>
chronic disease that He performed on the Sabbath, even though these people<br>
could have waited longer, I think we see that although sometimes kindness <br>
can wait until after the Sabbath, it need not do so.  However, we should not<br>
use participation in such activities on the Sabbath to excuse involvement<br>
for the rest of the week.  More comments are welcome.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
