<!-- subject="service jobs and the Sabbath" -->
<!-- id="9207131451.AA00295@seashore.usl.com" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Jul_1992: service jobs and the Sabbath</title>
<h1>service jobs and the Sabbath</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 13 Jul 92 10:51:53 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">McCluskey G: "He's heeerrrrreeeee!!!!!!!!"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Steven Timm: "Community Service Work on the Sabbath?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0032.html">malcolm butler: "Re: service jobs and the Sabbath"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; What impact do you think this might have on future religious liberty</i><br>
<i>&gt; cases before the Supreme Court in regards to Sabbath observance and a</i><br>
<i>&gt; service employee's refusal to work on the Sabbath?  If clean-up</i><br>
<i>&gt; efforts on the Sabbath (rather than Sunday) is justified as a Sabbath</i><br>
<i>&gt; activity, how can SDA defend a refusal to work in a service-related</i><br>
<i>&gt; occupation on the Sabbath?</i><br>
<p>
I've wondered about this for years.  We rely on services such as<br>
electricity and telephones, which require people to work on the<br>
Sabbath to maintain.<br>
<p>
If a relative dies in a distant area, we will probably fly there on<br>
Sabbath.  If our child gets sick, we may go to a pharmacy on Sabbath<br>
to fill a prescription.<br>
<p>
At the same time, we would frown on someone working for a utility on<br>
Sabbath or flying a plane or working as a pharmacist on Sabbath.<br>
<p>
It seems to me that a different view of the Sabbath is implied by<br>
these things, but I've never been able to flesh out what that view is.<br>
Perhaps others can help with thinking this through.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
