<title>Jul_1992: Re: service jobs and the Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re: service jobs and the Sabbath</h1>
malcolm butler (<i>malb@boojum.ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 14 Jul 92 13:12:09 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#32">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#32">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#32">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#32">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Steven Timm: "Until it's someone you know..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0031.html">McCluskey G: "He's heeerrrrreeeee!!!!!!!!"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0030.html">McCluskey G: "service jobs and the Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Glen McCluskey writes:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I've wondered about this for years.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
[ examples of using electricity, telephones, pharmacy, aeroplanes etc<br>
on Sabbath ]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;It seems to me that a different view of the Sabbath is implied by</i><br>
<i>&gt;these things, but I've never been able to flesh out what that view is.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Perhaps others can help with thinking this through.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
When we consider what we will and won't do on Sabbath, we often think<br>
only of the effect it will have on ourselves:  will this somehow<br>
``disrupt'' the day for me?  Will it affect _my_ day?  So when we go to<br>
the pharmacy, use the telephone, or turn on the electric light, we<br>
justify it as insignificant, yet it is easy to forget that someone,<br>
somewhere, is doing what is to them a perfectly ordinary day's work in<br>
order to provide it for us.  Is not this a rather selfish attitude to<br>
the Sabbath?<br>
<p>
In a world where everyone kept the Sabbath, would everything stop for<br>
24 hours, or would we share the jobs around?  Would we consider some<br>
things essential, and if so, which?  It is possible to do without a<br>
lot, if we really tried, yet how many of our Sabbath acitivities would<br>
stop, including church programs, if we only carried out the bare<br>
necessities?  Would we be better or worse off?<br>
<p>
To balance this, I know many people who work in various areas on<br>
Sabbath, but mostly in ``health services'' such as nurses, doctors,<br>
hospital ancillary staff, an ambulance officer or two, etc.  Yet there<br>
are many other areas that at least by our practices we appear to take<br>
for granted as an essential.<br>
<p>
<p>
Malcolm Butler<br>
<pre>
-- 
Switched Networks Research Centre,               malb@ee.uts.edu.au
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia            +61 2 330 2344
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
