<title>Jul_1992: Until it's someone you know...</title>
<h1>Until it's someone you know...</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 14 Jul 1992 00:38:21 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#33">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#33">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#33">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#33">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Community Service Work on the Sabbath?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0032.html">malcolm butler: "Re: service jobs and the Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0035.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Until it's someone you know..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A few months ago I tossed out a hot potato which I thought would raise a <br>
firestorm on the net, and there were no responses at all.  It regarded the <br>
court ruling made some time back in the trademark case of SDA Kinship <br>
versus the General Conference.  (Kinship is the organization of <br>
homosexuals and lesbians which draws from Adventist members.)  As I remember,<br>
the court found for Kinship because they were not using the name<br>
"Seventh-day Adventist" in conjunction with "church."  The details are<br>
to be found <br>
in Spectrum.  I had originally only published the short blurb that appeared<br>
in the Review.<br>
<p>
What struck me about the Spectrum report was that the secretary of<br>
Kinship who spoke on the record to Spectrum was a classmate of mine at<br>
Andrews<br>
University.  I had at one time gone on a date with her, and never suspected<br>
this might be the case; it also implied that another female classmate of<br>
mine whom I knew to be living with her might well be more than a<br>
roommate.<br>
<p>
I raise this question now because I will shortly be faced with giving<br>
counsel to yet another friend who has recently been through the breakup<br>
of such <br>
a relationship.  And though I could pound the keyboard for hours about the <br>
gay rights lobby that wants to pervert the morals of our children, this<br>
won't help my friends.<br>
<p>
What does the SDA church have to say to homosexuals today?  (not AT, _TO_)<br>
What will it take to develop an approach which emphasizes Bible morality<br>
and relationship theology, not fear-mongering and insults?<br>
<p>
I could say more, but I'd like to hear from the net on this one.<br>
<p>
Steve<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
