<title>Jul_1992: Re: Until it's someone you know...</title>
<h1>Re: Until it's someone you know...</h1>
Stan Macasieb (<i>Stan_Macasieb@isu.comm.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 14 Jul 1992 14:31:52 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#35">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#35">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#35">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#35">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Until it's someone you know..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Community Service Work on the Sabbath?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0033.html">Steven Timm: "Until it's someone you know..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0036.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Until it's someone you know..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
{Anecdote Alert!!!}<br>
<p>
Boy, does this baby hit real close to home.<br>
<p>
I had dated a girl right out of HS who was pretty nice, somewhat<br>
aggressive. It was one of those summertime romances which fell<br>
apart one semester into my freshman year in college. The killer<br>
part was that, when we were going out, she wanted to be with me<br>
all the time. So much so that she enrolled at the same college,<br>
and the same dorm, as I was. By the time she arrived on campus<br>
the next year, I didn't want anything to do w/ her. <br>
<p>
She became very active in some campus activities, particularly<br>
gay and lesbian rights groups. It was my final year in college<br>
when a friend of mine asked me if I knew that my ex was a <br>
lesbian. <br>
<p>
Knowing her family history and background, it really didn't <br>
come as a surprise. Sometimes I think that, because I was the<br>
last male she had dated, that I was somewhat responsible for<br>
making her turn tail. But I don't think so. She will do what<br>
she wants, regardless of what I have to say. For what it's<br>
worth, I don't feel it's my fault that she is a lesbian.<br>
<p>
I hope that, for her sake, that she continues to be her own <br>
person, and that she doesn't follow other people just because<br>
they say they're right. And I have no qualms about admitting<br>
that I dated a lesbian. As disgusting and immoral the practice<br>
is, she made her own choice and my only response is to be<br>
quiet. We haven't talked for years, though friends of mine <br>
have given me some updates from campus, where she writes a<br>
column for the campus newspaper.<br>
<p>
I'm not a preacher, nor do I profess to have the answers. That's<br>
why I feel that, no matter what I could say to her, any counsel<br>
about the immorality of her lifestyle would be fruitless. <br>
Instead, I would try to counsel along lines more familiar to<br>
me, the love that Jesus Christ has for all people, even those<br>
who are on the fringe of life. Inclusion is a more effective and<br>
uplifting technique, IMHO, than hammering my morality.<br>
<p>
It's true: until it's someone you know or if you are in that <br>
situation yourself, you have no idea whatsoever how to deal <br>
with the situation.<br>
<p>
Maybe I'll post a real response later. Back to work, ya know?<br>
<p>
{Cancel Anectdote Alert}<br>
<p>
--Stan Macasieb (stanm@comm.mot.com)<br>
    Communications Sec'y<br>
    North Shore SDA Church, Chicago<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
