<title>Jul_1992: RE: Until it's someone you know...</title>
<h1>RE: Until it's someone you know...</h1>
Joanne Figueiredo (<i>Joanne_Figueiredo@vos.stratus.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 14 Jul 92 13:48 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#37">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#37">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#37">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#37">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Steven Timm: "More on lesbianism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Until it's someone you know..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;It regarded the court ruling made some time back in the trademark case</i><br>
<i>&gt;of SDA Kinship versus the General Conference.  (Kinship is the organization</i><br>
<i>&gt;of homosexuals and lesbians which draws from Adventist members.)  As I</i><br>
<i>&gt;remember, the court found for Kinship because they were not using the name</i><br>
<i>&gt;"Seventh-day Adventist" in conjunction with "church."  The details are</i><br>
<i>&gt;to be found </i><br>
<i>&gt;in Spectrum.  I had originally only published the short blurb that appeared</i><br>
<i>&gt;in the Review.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;What struck me about the Spectrum report was that the secretary of</i><br>
<i>&gt;Kinship who spoke on the record to Spectrum was a classmate of mine at</i><br>
<i>&gt;Andrews</i><br>
<i>&gt;University.  I had at one time gone on a date with her, and never suspected</i><br>
<i>&gt;this might be the case; it also implied that another female classmate of</i><br>
<i>&gt;mine whom I knew to be living with her might well be more than a</i><br>
<i>&gt;roommate.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I raise this question now because I will shortly be faced with giving</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;What does the SDA church have to say to homosexuals today?  (not AT, _TO_)</i><br>
<i>&gt;What will it take to develop an approach which emphasizes Bible morality</i><br>
<i>&gt;and relationship theology, not fear-mongering and insults?</i><br>
<p>
These are very difficult questions for the SDA church to face. Especially<br>
now with AIDS, its something so hard. I'm not an SDA church leader and<br>
I don't even know the "official" church stand on homosexuality but as a<br>
member I can share some thoughts that young adult groups around here have<br>
discussed. First of all, knowing someone who is homosexual does make it<br>
very personal and we all have to remember that no matter what, condemning<br>
others for ANYTHING is not the Christian way. The Bible does talk about<br>
homosexuality being a sinful thing, but so is lying, stealing, etc. and<br>
we are taught that God doesn't like ANY sin. So, if homosexuals are frowned<br>
upon, so should all other sinners be treated so. <br>
<p>
Now, this is easy to say, but when it comes right down to it, most people<br>
still have some "homophobia" ideas. I know that I catch myself sometimes<br>
going along with jokes or whatever but its wrong. <br>
<p>
In my opinion, God bases his judgement on intent. He loves everyone, no<br>
matter what but sin is sin. I'm sorry that I don't have the theological<br>
intelligence to explain this any better but this is what I mean: <br>
<p>
     God created man and women to be together. I truly feel bad for<br>
     those that have different tendencies because they are still<br>
     people, like me, and circumstances should not be blamed on them.<br>
     But, homosexuality is not God's plan (just like any sin) and if<br>
     you engage in it intentionally, then you are sinning. <br>
<p>
Now, since we are all sinners, we should not be pointing the finger at them<br>
since none of us are any better. I think this is what Steve was talking<br>
about as far as "relationship theology" goes. But, I don't think there could<br>
be or should be a "Bible morality" idea supporting homosexuality. Just<br>
because we feel empathy, does not mean we should try to justify certain<br>
behaviors. <br>
<p>
Also, there is the health issue of homosexuality (and promiscuity). If I<br>
know I could die from doing certain things, then I'll try not to do them. <br>
Isn't that a simple concept? I know if I had a personal friend or relative<br>
who had the risk of dying from something like AIDS, I would do anything I<br>
could for that not to happen. <br>
<p>
Ultimately, its in God's hands and as far as I am concerned, thats where I'm<br>
going to leave it. What I try to live by is that I have to try to treat <br>
others like I want to be treated (golden rule). <br>
<p>
I just want to end with a story. In a group discussion about this once,<br>
a teacher told us about someone she knew that was homosexual(I'll call her<br>
'Lisa'). Lisa had always felt very self-conscious of the fact that she felt<br>
certain feelings for women instead of men. This weighed heavy on her as<br>
she got older and being a religious person, she always felt so guilty. Finally,<br>
she went ahead and had relationships with women. But, in the end she couldn't<br>
continue knowing that it was getting in the way of her and God. So, she<br>
took a stand that she would be celibate all her life. She would rather not<br>
experience sex, then to experience it in a "wrong" way. When I heard this<br>
I felt like crying. People like Lisa suffer. And I don't know if she was<br>
able to keep her stand, but quite truthfully, I don't care. All I know is<br>
that here was someone who had great courage. Don't we all try to lead<br>
sinless lives?? And what happens?? It doesn't work as easy as it sounds.<br>
So how can we expect others to be sinless if we aren't??? <br>
<p>
There's only one other thing. One point that bothers me is how do you<br>
justify things like gay rights parades?? I sin but the last thing I want to<br>
do is flaunt it. Maybe someone else has more thoughts to add to this....<br>
<p>
Sorry for such a long letter!! And I hope I didn't say anything that could<br>
be misunderstood. <br>
                               God bless,    ~Joanne<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
