<title>Jul_1992: More on lesbianism</title>
<h1>More on lesbianism</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 14 Jul 1992 17:27:47 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#38">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#38">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#38">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#38">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Steve Hix: "Churches, licensing, and taxation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Joanne Figueiredo: "RE: Until it's someone you know..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0043.html">Lisa Parry: "Book Recommendation"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As we look at the issue of homosexuality within and near the borders of <br>
the SDA church, it is helpful to examine the past record of the denomination<br>
on this.  The church at one time had a healing ministry for homosexuals,<br>
led by one Colin Cook, who claimed to be a recovered former homosexual.<br>
It turned out he wasn't quite recovered and led to a rather unsavory<br>
and unfortunate experience of which I don't know all the details.<br>
At that time he was sponsored by the denomination. <br>
<p>
Now I understand he is again trying to resume his ministry, this time on <br>
his own.  If any details are available, I would be interested to hear them.<br>
Needless to say this is a sore point with Kinship.<br>
<p>
The politically correct would have us believe that a homosexual orientation<br>
is born in, perhaps is even genetic.  Suppose this is the case.  Still<br>
this would be no different from alcoholism, which seems to show genetic <br>
factors.  No one believes alcoholism is any more acceptable just because<br>
it is an inherited tendency, nor does that inherited tendency inhibit<br>
recovery.  <br>
<p>
In fact, how is any sin different from alcoholism:  there is an inherited<br>
tendency to do it, and recovery is possible.  The "disease model" of sin<br>
is one which has a lot to teach us, but shouldn't be pushed too far.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
