<title>Jul_1992: Churches, licensing, and taxation</title>
<h1>Churches, licensing, and taxation</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 14 Jul 92 11:19:51 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#39">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#39">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#39">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#39">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Churches, licensing, and taxation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Steven Timm: "More on lesbianism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0040.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Churches, licensing, and taxation"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In our local paper this morning, there was an interesting<br>
item from Berkeley, CA:<br>
<p>
Because of declining local tax revenues, Berkeley is now<br>
considering enforcing an ordinance dating from the mid-70s.<br>
<p>
This ordinance requires churches inside the city limits to<br>
obtain a business license to continue operating.<br>
<p>
It also requires that the church pay a percentage of its<br>
offering to the city as taxes.<br>
<p>
Some Berkeley-area churches are unhappy about the proposed<br>
move.  Some aren't complaining, on the other hand.<br>
<p>
The city council apparently sees no problem with enforcing<br>
the ordinance (other than trying to collect from some<br>
uncooperative congregations).<br>
<p>
	seh<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
