<title>Jul_1992: Re: Until its someone you know..</title>
<h1>Re: Until its someone you know..</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 15 Jul 1992 00:05 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">McCluskey G: "note on SDAnet netiquette"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Churches, licensing, and taxation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In response to Joanne's story about "Lisa" and her choice of celebacy<br>
rather than homosexuality, I'd like to remind you that there are many<br>
devout Christian heterosexual singles who choose celebacy also.  The<br>
thing that has always troubled me about homosexuality is that somehow<br>
there's the idea that because a person has a sexual attraction to the<br>
same sex that they must act on it.  Many single people have sexual feelings<br>
for others of the opposite sex but because they believe that sex outside<br>
of marriage is sin, they abstain.  It's almost as if the world has come<br>
to the notion that sexual urgings must be carried out in acts of sin.<br>
Even if a gay or lesbian is struggling with their sexual feelings, there<br>
is no excuse for acting on them any more than two people of the opposite<br>
sex.  I personally feel that fornication between heterosexuals is just as<br>
sinful as homosexuals.  Why can't Christians view them as the same sin<br>
rather than single them out?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
