<title>Jul_1992: Book Recommendation</title>
<h1>Book Recommendation</h1>
Lisa Parry (<i>parry@elrond.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 14 Jul 92 19:27:39 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Dan Blake: "Re: Land seizure by eminent domain"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">McCluskey G: "note on SDAnet netiquette"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0038.html">Steven Timm: "More on lesbianism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This has little to do with any of the subjects under discussion, but I wanted<br>
to recommend a book.  It's called _The_Man_from_Lancer_Avenue_, by Trudy<br>
Morgan.  It's about Jesus, a story on His life set in the setting of today.<br>
Instead of fisherman, Andrews, Peter, James, and John are car repairmen.  Simon<br>
the zealot is pictured as a skinhead Nazi (I think), the man with leprosy is a <br>
homosexual with AIDS.<br>
<p>
It really gives some good ideas on how Jesus MIGHT confront many situations <br>
present today.  It's written in story form, and I wholeheartedly recommend it!<br>
<p>
Available at the Adventist Book Center.  <br>
<pre>
