<title>Jul_1992: Holy Spirit; Gen. 1; Apostasy</title>
<h1>Holy Spirit; Gen. 1; Apostasy</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  1 Jul 1992 21:59:18 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#46">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#46">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#46">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#46">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Dan Blake: "Holy Spirit; Gen. 1; Apostasy"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Dan Blake: "Holy Spirit; Gen. 1; Apostasy"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One of the functions of the Holy Spirit is to reprove for sin. (John 16:8,9).<br>
We become convinced of the wrongness of a deed as the Holy Spirit speaks<br>
to our conscience (and here I include the ministry of the Spirit through<br>
the word of God.)  This knowledge leads to a repentance and a turning away<br>
from sin.<br>
<p>
...example of someone either ignoring the H.S. or ignorant of the<br>
Word of God...<br>
<p>
[You ask]<br>
(Q1) How should these circumstances be handled?<br>
(Q2) Is the Holy Spirit a license to do as we please?<br>
<p>
(A2) Absolutely not.  This is the what Jude was compelled to write <br>
against, "Ungodly persons who turn the grace of our God into licen-<br>
tiousness and [simultaneously] deny our only Master and Lord, Jesus <br>
Christ" (Jude 1:4). <br>
<p>
(A1) You must discern whether this individual is ignoring the H.S. or<br>
is ignorant of the WoG.  If the former, may I suggest you witness to<br>
him with the gospel.  If the later, you may want to disciple him in<br>
the precepts of the Christian faith.  Ask him about his relationship<br>
as a child of God and what it means to be submissive to the authority<br>
and rule of God.<br>
----------------<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
