<title>Jul_1992: Re: Until it's someone you know...</title>
<h1>Re: Until it's someone you know...</h1>
<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 15 Jul 92 09:35:47 EDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#49">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#49">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#49">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#49">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0050.html">Ben Clausen: "sharing creationism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Dan Blake: "Holy Spirit; Gen. 1; Apostasy"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0033.html">Steven Timm: "Until it's someone you know..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Fred Christiansen writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; This is probably not exhaustive, but I reckon there are two basic reasons</i><br>
<i>&gt; for homosexuality - being persuaded by Satan's sophistries (in all its forms)</i><br>
<i>&gt; because we are not wise in God's ways and words (Jer 50:6; Ps 119:11), and</i><br>
<i>&gt; outright rebellion against God's order and against His design for our bodies.</i><br>
<p>
Somehow I doubt you've ever conversed all that much with many homosexuals.  I<br>
had a friend a few years back that was gay.  He told me that for him, there was<br>
no choice in the matter.  He was physically repulsed by the thought of sexual<br>
relations with a woman.  He wanted to know why God would allow him to be born<br>
in such a way that he -had- to live his entire life in guilt and misery simply<br>
because he wanted to love someone that was of the same gender, and -couldn't-<br>
love someone of the opposite gender in the same way.  There was no rebellion in<br>
him, just fear and sadness.  He got no comfort from other so-called Christians.<br>
They merely told him he was sinning against God and would be condemned  to<br>
destruction for his evil ways.  Self-righteous hypocrites.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Is it His design for any to have homosexual tendencies?  I say No (cf. Rom 1).</i><br>
<p>
Perhaps not, but apparently, a lot of people do.  We should avoid persecuting,<br>
and try comforting.  Don't tell them what Scripture says, invite them to find out<br>
for themselves, and find what peace they may.  Let God be their judge, not us.<br>
We do not know all of His plan, only what has been revealed to us in His Word,<br>
and His word was, after all, written down by human hands, subject to the failings<br>
of us all.  As has been said before, Scripture does not claim infallibilty for<br>
Itself.  The only words which -must- be infallible are those of our Lord Himself,<br>
who told us to love each other, and who reproaches us to not worry about the mote<br>
in another's eye until we have removed the beam from our own.  Words to live by...<br>
<p>
Bob Moynihan                Disclaimer:  I don't speak for HP, just myself.<br>
moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com                                                   <br>
