<title>Jul_1992: sharing creationism</title>
<h1>sharing creationism</h1>
Ben Clausen (<i>GRIBCL%LLUVM.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 15 Jul 92 16:36:20 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#50">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#50">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#50">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#50">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0051.html">Dan Hamstra: "Homosexuality in the SDA church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0049.html">moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com: "Re: Until it's someone you know..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
RE: sharing creationism<br>
<p>
     In my work in the nuclear physics community I have been quite<br>
reticent to emphasize creation research as my major job<br>
responsibility. To tell people that I am a creationist I would<br>
compare to Christ telling people that He was the Messiah. Desire of<br>
Ages, p.414. says --- Jesus charged the disciples to tell no man<br>
that He was the Christ. This charge was given because of the<br>
determined opposition of the scribes and Pharisees. More than this,<br>
the people, and even the disciples, had so false a conception of<br>
the Messiah that a public announcement of Him would give them no<br>
true idea of His character or His work. But day by day He was<br>
revealing Himself to them as the Saviour, and thus He desired to<br>
give them a true conception of Him as the Messiah.    The ideas<br>
that scientists envision when they hear the term creationism is<br>
rather distant from my beliefs.<br>
     Plenty of scientists ask me about my job. My response is that<br>
I am studying the relation between science and religion. The first<br>
two weeks in July I spent working on a kaon scattering experiment<br>
at Brookhaven National Laboratory on Long Island, NY. This last<br>
Saturday night I was talking to one of the graduate students<br>
helping with the experiment. It started with a question about my<br>
job. He spent awhile asking me what the SDA church believes, and<br>
finished by saying that he wished that he too could believe.<br>
Emphasizing the creation/evolution controversy that evening would<br>
have put up a barrier and directed his interest away from the<br>
essentials.<br>
     There are a number of examples of Christ avoiding controversy.<br>
(He didn't always but it seems there are more examples of avoiding<br>
than confronting.) The woman at the well hoped to silence<br>
conviction by turning to points of religious controversy (where to<br>
worship), but Jesus wanted to lift her thoughts above matters of<br>
form and ceremony, and questions of controversy (see John 4 and DA<br>
p.188). Thomas made his doubts prominent, but Jesus didn't<br>
overwhelm him with reproach, nor did He enter into controversy with<br>
him. He revealed Himself. Thomas was unreasonable in dictating the<br>
conditions of his faith, but Jesus broke down the barriers by His<br>
generous love and consideration. Unbelief is seldom overcome by<br>
controversy. It is rather put upon self-defence, and finds new<br>
support and excuse. Instead Jesus needs to be revealed (see John 20<br>
and DA p.808).<br>
     However, having said all that, the evolution/creation issue<br>
does need to be addressed at some point in sharing Christianity<br>
with a scientist. The standard evolutionary model is THE scientific<br>
model. It has the most evidence in the literature because that is<br>
the paradigm under which most scientists work. One would have no<br>
reason to consider another type of model except that the Bible<br>
presents a different model. Of course there is always the<br>
possibility that we have misconceptions about exactly what the<br>
Bible is trying to say about early earth history events. My<br>
approach then is to determine what the important themes throughout<br>
the Bible are and see how they are related to Genesis 1-11. These<br>
themes include: life isn't meaningless, God has a purpose; life<br>
doesn't improve on its own, we need outside help; evil is not<br>
normal or just; death and suffering are not part of God's preferred<br>
plan for development; God does intervene in non-scientific ways at<br>
times; God demands our worship because He is Creator; the Sabbath<br>
memorializes a seven day creation week; the NT authors interpret<br>
Genesis 1-11 as literal, etc. There have been unjustifiable science<br>
theories based on interpretation of individual texts, e.g., a<br>
flat earth, a geocentric universe, fixity of species. However, the<br>
themes I mentioned in general are related to the overall thrust of<br>
the Bible in the Great Controversy and concerning our salvation. I<br>
have not seen a model that is able to include these themes without<br>
also including a recent 6-day creation of life and a catastrophic<br>
widespread flood.<br>
     With that in mind I need to again look at the scientific<br>
evidence. What would I share with a skeptic? In the history of<br>
science, the theories aren't quite as final as may seem apparent at<br>
any one point in time in their development. The perfect wave theory<br>
of light of 100 years ago has had to go through some rather major<br>
revolutions (relativity and quantum mechanics). The simple<br>
classical mechanics theories are now being re-examined under new<br>
developments in chaos theory. Plate tectonics, laughed at 50 years<br>
ago, is now the accepted paradigm. And catastrophism is becoming<br>
much more acceptable in geology these days, e.g. an extra-<br>
terrestrial impact causing the extinction of the dinosaurs.<br>
     Enough creation type research is finding alternative<br>
explanations to standard evolution to suggest that it is not as<br>
unreasonable as some may think. (If people are interested I could<br>
give examples of some specifics, but I think I have said about<br>
enough for one posting.) However, one should not expect that<br>
naturalistic science will ever come up with supernatural<br>
intervention as an explanation for origins. Scientists feel that<br>
would be going back to the Middle Ages where anything you don't<br>
understand is attributed to God, thus stifling personal research.<br>
<p>
     Ben Clausen<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
