<title>Jul_1992: Homosexuality in the SDA church</title>
<h1>Homosexuality in the SDA church</h1>
Dan Hamstra (<i>hamstra@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 17 Jul 92 21:22:36 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#51">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#51">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#51">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#51">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0052.html">McCluskey G: "Re: Homosexuality in the SDA church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0050.html">Ben Clausen: "sharing creationism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I recently had a Sabbath dinner discussion with a group of people who are open<br>
about their homosexuality and are also active SDA's.  At the table were three<br>
of us who were "straight" (two male and one female) and five who were not (four<br>
male and one female).  A few of these individuals are very active in the Kinship<br>
organization and since this court ruling against the General Conference had<br>
recently passed, a large part of our discussion centered on Kinship and where<br>
they would go from here.<br>
<p>
I came to form the following opinions based on these few hours of interaction.<br>
<p>
These people are just the same as all my "straight" friends.  They have work<br>
problems, they have relationship problems, they joke, they laugh, and actually<br>
enjoy talking about things other than homosexuality.  In short, I generally<br>
don't think of them as "these people" but rather as my friends.  I also found<br>
that they have a great deal of concern about their (the SDA) church and where<br>
they can fit into organization.<br>
<p>
Comparing homosexuality to alcoholism is something I used to do but I have a<br>
hard time thinking that way now.  During my last year in school at Andrews (I<br>
work here now) there were two situations that started building a contrast in<br>
my mind.  I had one friend who was very active in student government that was<br>
discovered to be involved in a homosexual relationship with another student.<br>
He had his student leadership positions removed and was subsequently expelled<br>
from school.  At the same time I had a student (I was teaching a freshman<br>
level class) who had a car accident, was found to be under the influence of <br>
alcohol, and was the first student to enter an alcohol rehab program that<br>
had just been started at AU.  Both situations were commonly known, I think<br>
most of the things I outlined here were even in the student paper on campus.<br>
I realized at that time that we have radically different approaches as a<br>
school and as a denomination to dealing with these two situations.<br>
Back to my Sabbath dinner.  I did not sense from any of my homosexual friends<br>
that they consider their homosexuality as a problem.  I can't say that I'm<br>
sure they do have a problem (I'm still forming a personal opinion on this)<br>
even in light of all of the "proof texts" that I know exist to condemn this<br>
lifestyle.<br>
<p>
To the issue of celibacy.  What if two SDA men wanted to get married?  If they<br>
could get past the legal issues, would the church allow them to be members?<br>
Would their sexual activity after this marriage still be "adultery" even<br>
though they have gone through this act of commitment?  Should the church make<br>
this a litmus test as we seem to do with smoking? Or, should we let God worry<br>
about whether or not they're sinning and we accept them as they are because in<br>
fact, "all have sinned and come short of the glory of God"?<br>
<p>
These are not necessarily my opinions, my opinions tend to change as time goes<br>
by, but I thought these anecdotes might help add a different slant to the<br>
discussions.<br>
<p>
Dan Hamstra<br>
Microcomputer Services Manager<br>
Andrews University<br>
hamstra@andrews.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
