<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Hi Glen in ref to your EMail, are you sure that Homosexuality can be a</i><br>
<i>&gt; genetic defect. If so, we can excuse a lot of things.</i><br>
<p>
I am not in favor of homosexual practices at all.  My point was that<br>
we take a lot of things for granted -- so long as they don't affect us<br>
personally.  For example, we might condemn homosexuals, but how many<br>
of us are temperate in other ways?  I have been in SDA subcultures<br>
where people would stuff themselves at Sabbath lunch and lie in a<br>
stupor the rest of the day.  This is no more temperate than other<br>
practices we strongly condemn.<br>
<p>
I think in too many cases we confuse our personal willpower with<br>
strength given by God.  I've been reading Philip Yancey's book<br>
"Disappointment with God" and it stirs the pot a bit on these issues.<br>
He talks about people who talk loudly about their prayer life and all<br>
that God has done for them, and then about people who are just as<br>
sincere but whom God doesn't seem to answer.<br>
<p>
I think that SDAnet readers by and large are well above average in<br>
intelligence, education, and so on.  I also think there is a twilight<br>
world out there of people in just the opposite position.  I'm not<br>
totally convinced that our standard theological approaches apply to<br>
them.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
