<title>Jul_1992: Some random thoughts on homosexuality</title>
<h1>Some random thoughts on homosexuality</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 22 Jul 1992 22:24:24 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#61">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#61">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#61">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#61">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0062.html">Lola: "homosexuality/SDA"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Steven Timm: "Race Relations: a correction"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Paul Gates spoke against the idea of regarding homosexuality as a genetic<br>
influence, because by this rationality we could excuse all sorts of behavior.<br>
Actually I was the one that put forth that position for the sake of argument.<br>
My point was that even if there is a genetic component to this condition, <br>
that does not make it excusable, or irreversible.  Although I compared<br>
homosexuality to alcoholism, I didn't mean to suggest that it is a<br>
disease.<br>
It is, however, an alleged genetic condition from which recovery is<br>
possible and necessary.  It's no more or less a disease than any other<br>
sin.<br>
<p>
However, in the Adventist church, there seem to be two levels of sin.<br>
You don't see anyone get disfellowshipped for pride, covetousness, <br>
greed, backbiting, gossip, politicking, or many other sins.  When it <br>
comes to the so-called "public" sins, condemnation is more at the ready <br>
for pregancy out of wedlock, adultery, divorce, and homosexuality. <br>
(Although this condemnation, too, is disappearing, replaced by the I'm<br>
OK, You're OK philosophy.)<br>
<p>
When I was writing my still-to-be-accepted book manuscript, I struggled <br>
with what to say about homosexuality, because there was nothing in my <br>
relationship-theology development of the relationship between lovers to<br>
indicate that this should always be between male and female.  I decided<br>
at that time to say nothing about it.  Now I don't have that luxury.<br>
<p>
This topic can't be treated without recognizing that in Genesis God<br>
created the image of God as a relationship between man and woman, and<br>
that the image of God is only realized in relationships.  The logical<br>
extensions of that argument, however, give pause for thought.  If we are<br>
to accept the<br>
Bible's prohibitions against homosexuality at face value [which I believe<br>
we must] how can we ignore the nearby counsels on the role of women<br>
which we would dearly love to argue were culture-bound?  How, indeed,<br>
can we develop a moral theology that is any different from the "natural<br>
theology" of the Catholic Church?  Or should we?<br>
<p>
This whole issue begs the question of what the role in general the human<br>
body plays in Adventist theology.  Here we find some delicious<br>
ambiguities.<br>
I don't remember if I have posted them before.  If so, someone please<br>
warn me, otherwise you will see them soon.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
