<title>Jul_1992: Re: homosexuality/SDA  (Judging)</title>
<h1>Re: homosexuality/SDA  (Judging)</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 23 Jul 1992 21:39:53 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#63">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#63">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#63">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#63">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Steven Timm: "Towards a theology of the human body"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0062.html">Lola: "homosexuality/SDA"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0062.html">Lola: "homosexuality/SDA"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Lola articulated a point of view commonly heard in arguments of this type<br>
<p>
"It's not for us to judge."<br>
<p>
While the verses in the Bible that speak against judging are many,<br>
including Matthew 7, there are also pro-judging verses in the Bible.<br>
First Corinthians 5:12,13, 6:2,3<br>
<p>
"For what have I to do to judge them also that are without?  do not ye<br>
judge them that are within?  But them that are without God judgeth. <br>
therefore put away from yourselves that wicked person.  <br>
Do ye not know that the saints shall judge the world?  And if the world<br>
shall be judged by you, are ye unworthy to judge the smallest matters? <br>
Know ye not that we shall judge angels?  how much more things that<br>
pertain to this life?<br>
<p>
<p>
If we look at the first few chapters of Acts, we see that judgment<br>
happened frequently, and God's authority was exercised in the church. <br>
If we think that the church today can run without rules to govern the<br>
behavior of its members, we are only deceiving ourselves.  <br>
<p>
The key difference between then and now is that at that time the church<br>
authorities were under the clear, present, and daily guidance of the<br>
Holy Spirit.  Only under this influence can we hope to judge fairly. <br>
But once<br>
given this power, judge we can and judge we must.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
