<title>Jul_1992: Towards a theology of the human body</title>
<h1>Towards a theology of the human body</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 23 Jul 1992 22:05:35 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Gross: "Judging"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Steven Timm: "Re: homosexuality/SDA  (Judging)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0067.html">Mark T Brower: "Re: Towards a theology of the human body"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The Mormons point to the body as an essential part of the trip from spirit<br>
world through life to exaltation.  The Christian Scientists believe that<br>
the mistake Adam made was not in eating the fruit, but falling asleep and <br>
dreaming he had a body in the first place, and that we are deluded into <br>
believing we have one, as soon as we clear ourselves of this delusion,<br>
we'll be free.<br>
<p>
Adventists would generally not accept either of the above extremes.<br>
But for years the care or neglect of ones body is one of the category of <br>
"visible sins" which has served as a yardstick for the self-righteous.  <br>
(Unfortunately, the emphasis on health seems to be slipping just as the <br>
rest of the world is realizing that we were right.)  <br>
<p>
Bull and Lockhart in _Seeking A Sanctuary_ claim that the central<br>
sociological tension of Adventists as a group is the conflict between<br>
two images.  One as the model minority, practicing good health, doing<br>
all sorts<br>
of humanitarian activities, and being a model to the country,.  The<br>
other as the peculiar minority:  who are different and enjoy the<br>
difference, and emphasize their status as a peculiar and oppressed<br>
people.<br>
<p>
The question to be answered is the following:  Our church says a lot<br>
about caring for ones' body.  But what is, or should be, our motivation<br>
to do so?<br>
<p>
1)  Salvation by Numete<br>
2)  To live longer and happier on this earth<br>
3)  To make the time on earth *seem* longer<br>
4)  To deny and mortify self, punishing our animal passions<br>
5)  To make our church the best health club around<br>
6)  To look really sexy to attract others to our church<br>
7)  To keep our channels to God open the best they can<br>
8)  Others?  Add yours<br>
<p>
<p>
Bull and Lockhart also reported in their book that in advertising in SDA<br>
publications, female images were used more than male over the past few<br>
years by a factor of 3 or 4 to 1.  Why's that?  Is it appropriate to use<br>
a pretty face to sell a holy product?  (I think yes, it gets me every<br>
time.)<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
