<title>Jul_1992: Judging</title>
<h1>Judging</h1>
Gross (<i>grossg@dg-rtp.dg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 24 Jul 92 9:14:54 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#65">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#65">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#65">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#65">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Bob Moynihan: "Re: homosexuality/SDA  (Judging)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Steven Timm: "Towards a theology of the human body"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Folks:<br>
<p>
It's been a while, but that is how work goes!!<br>
<p>
I've followed with some interest the discussion on homosexuality, and<br>
I would like to make a few points.  First, if we accept the Bible as<br>
the inspired Word of God to us, then we must also accept that God will<br>
protect His Word so that we have it today.  This means that the<br>
proscription against homosexuality in both the OT and NT still apply<br>
today.  Either God is right, or He isn't God at all.<br>
<p>
The problem is not sexual orientation or sexual sins but our sin<br>
nature.  That is, our propensity to sin.  Since Adam and Eve ate the<br>
forbidden fruit, humanity has consistently tried to impose its own<br>
view of right and wrong, good and evil, upon each other and God.  <br>
<p>
When those who accept the full weight and import of Scripture make<br>
statements based on what God says, they are accused of judging.  As<br>
one who accepts God's judgements of right and wrong, good and evil,<br>
let me say that when I condemn homosexual practices I am not judging<br>
-- I am merely repeating what God has caused to be written in His<br>
Word.  God said it and that is sufficient.  I seriously doubt that God<br>
would have condemned something that was genetically passed on to<br>
humans.  I don't believe that homosexuality is genetically based.<br>
<p>
Now having said all that let me move on to what I believe is what Gad<br>
calls us to do.  While we are supposed to call sin sin, we are also<br>
supposed to let the Love of God shine through us.  If we go around all<br>
the time condemning others for their sins, we will miss our own sins.<br>
A homosexual is no more vile than any other sinner -- sin is sin is<br>
sin!!  There is forgiveness and restoration for all who come to Christ<br>
Jesus.  I personally know of two homosexuals who not only came to<br>
Christ, but their conversions were accompanied with the miraculous --<br>
that is, they found their sexual orientations changed.  One is now<br>
dead of AIDS that he contracted prior to coming to Christ, but his<br>
family (wife and two kids) are still free of the disease to this day.<br>
The other person is now attending seminary to become a minister of the<br>
Gospel of Jesus Christ.<br>
<p>
I also know of other sinners who at conversion had the miraculous<br>
happen in their lives, as well.  And that is the whole point -- the<br>
conversion of sinners from darkness to light, from death to life, from<br>
sin to righteousness.  That is what Christianity is about, that is the<br>
calling of the Church universal.  Was it not our Lord's final charge<br>
to us to go into all the world and preach the Gospel, making<br>
disciples!?  Were we not also told that the Gospel would be an offense<br>
to many!?  The world does not want the absolute morality of God.  They<br>
want the relativistic morality of our archenemy.  Yet, we who follow<br>
Christ are the modern day equivalents of the old prophets!  We are to<br>
stand before the world and call the world to repentance in Jesus<br>
Christ, and this means that we must also call the people's sins sin in<br>
the sight of God.<br>
<p>
Just my thoughts on things.<br>
<p>
En Agape,<br>
<p>
Gene Gross<br>
&lt;&gt;&lt;<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
