<title>Jul_1992: Re: Towards a theology of the human body</title>
<h1>Re: Towards a theology of the human body</h1>
Mark T Brower (<i>mtb@cblpo.att.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 24 Jul 92 09:35 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#67">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#67">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#67">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#67">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Paul Gates: "Re: homosexuality/SDA  (Judging)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Bob Moynihan: "Re: homosexuality/SDA  (Judging)"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0064.html">Steven Timm: "Towards a theology of the human body"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0069.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Towards a theology of the human body"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I figured I'd jump in on this one, even though I'm not an SDA.<br>
<p>
I've spent some time working this issue through, starting about <br>
2 years ago.  I had allowed my physical condition to degenerate, <br>
using my spare time for more "spiritual activities" such as <br>
Bible study and fellowship.  God needed to overcome an inaccurate<br>
philosophy of mine, one that had developed subconsciously over<br>
the years where I thought of physical health activities as <br>
"vanities" of "those jock types" or "health nuts."<br>
<p>
The bottom line for me theologically is twofold:<br>
<p>
	1) Just as we are to view ourselves as merely stewards<br>
	   (not owners) of our financial resources, so we are to <br>
	   view our bodies as gifts of God that we are entrusted <br>
	   to manage wisely.  We are neither to obsess over our <br>
	   physiques, nor are we to squandor them.  (All the classic <br>
	   passages on stewardship apply.)<br>
<p>
	   So, for instance, when I realize that my back is such <br>
	   that I must swim regularly to avoid weakening it and <br>
	   precipitating injury, I would be foolish not to do so.<br>
<p>
	2) As a husband, it is part of my ministry to keep a<br>
	   sufficiently attractive body that my physical relationship<br>
	   with my wife is not inhibited.  To do otherwise would<br>
	   not be loving my wife, but rather being selfishly lazy.  <br>
<p>
	   Also, as a corollary of the first point, to let myself<br>
	   degenerate to the point that I'm risking serious injury<br>
	   (back problems) or death (heart attack), is also not<br>
	   serving my wife.<br>
<p>
These two points helped me to put this area of my life into<br>
perspective.<br>
<p>
Just my $.02 worth,<br>
Mark<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
