<title>Jul_1992: More theology of the body</title>
<h1>More theology of the body</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 27 Jul 1992 21:37:44 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#71">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#71">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#71">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#71">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0072.html">Steven Timm: "Sexual Ethics in the Adventist Ministry"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0070.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Towards a theology of the human body"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I may have posted this story before to the net, but if so it was a long<br>
time ago:<br>
<p>
Those who have been Adventists for a while will remember the book<br>
_Creeping Compromise_ by Joe Crews.  In it he recounts a story of a<br>
sermon he gave at an academy, warning the young people to abstain from<br>
many modern vices including (gasp!) mixed swimming.  He recalls that<br>
afterwards two young <br>
ladies came up to him, evidently troubled.  "We were on the boardwalk,<br>
at the beach, witnessing all summer.  This is our friend Tom, who has<br>
come to know the Lord as a result of our witness."<br>
<p>
Joe Crews asked Tom, "Were you influenced by the attractiveness of these<br>
young ladies and the provocative attire they were wearing?" <br>
"Yes, of course," Tom replied.<br>
<p>
Crews ends the episode by saying that the young ladies were shocked that<br>
their attire would have influenced Tom, and uses the episode to build<br>
his case against the evils of mixed swimming, whether or not people are<br>
clothed in costumes which he considers modest.  But I've wondered ever<br>
since:<br>
<p>
1)  Was it better that Tom not come to know God at all than be attracted<br>
with the wrong motive?<br>
<p>
2)  If only pure motives were accepted in the initial seeking of God,<br>
would any of us ever find God?<br>
<p>
3)  I do not claim that the end justifies the means, but is there some time<br>
when the display of the human form is appropriate and holy, even if<br>
there is a chance it may be misunderstood?<br>
<p>
4)  What would Jesus do in a situation like this?  Wear a 3-piece suit <br>
to the beach?<br>
<p>
5)  Just because Jesus could do the appropriate thing in a situation,<br>
does that mean we necessarily can or should do it?<br>
<p>
6)  Is it time to have the "La Sierra Bikini Team" and make beach<br>
witnessing into a recognized intercollegiate sport?<br>
<p>
7)  Whenever a witnessing approach involves meeting someone on their<br>
level, there is a certain amount of tempation involved both for the<br>
witness and the witnessee.  How do we know how much is too much?<br>
<p>
Some of my questions are tongue-in-cheek, some of them are deadly serious.<br>
I hope you all can tell the difference.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
