<title>Jun_1992: Seeking Advice on Trapped Emotions</title>
<h1>Seeking Advice on Trapped Emotions</h1>
Rolaant (<i>USER7C1M@um.cc.umich.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 3 Jun 92 15:00:20 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#8">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#8">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#8">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#8">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Eric Snyder: "Anger"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: HIGH SABBATH - The Jews Answer (Continued)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To Whoever is listening:<br>
 <br>
There is a good friend of mine here who is having trouble with anger.<br>
He apparently does not express it but keeps it inside. He has talked to<br>
me about this, and expresses the fear that he may sometime lose control<br>
over his stored anger. In that event he might do just about anything. He<br>
has asked me for advice on how he can release it safely, without hurting<br>
anyone or anything. I have suggested physical exercise, but this is <br>
apparently not enough. I am no expert in situations such as this, so I<br>
seek helpful advice from anyone who may have wisdom to share.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Eric Snyder: "Anger"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: HIGH SABBATH - The Jews Answer (Continued)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
</DOC>
