<title>Jun_1992: Re: What is Love (Agape)</title>
<h1>Re: What is Love (Agape)</h1>
Gross (<i>grossg@dg-rtp.dg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 1 Jun 92 12:36:27 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#1">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#1">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#1">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#1">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0002.html">Ben Clausen: "mother's pride"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0000.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Dave:<br>
<p>
There are a number of words that the Greeks used for love -- some more<br>
akin to the English term "like" than our word "love."  However, I want<br>
to confine my remarks to eros, phileo, and agape.<br>
<p>
Eros, from which we get our word erotic, is the sensual love.  It is<br>
neither good or bad.  We get great sensual pleasure out of a beautiful<br>
vista (and there are definitely some in Dave's neck of the woods!!).<br>
The negative side of this is the lust of the flesh often seen in what<br>
is sometimes called erotica, or just plain pornography (soft and<br>
hard).<br>
<p>
Phileo, from which the name Philadelphia comes, is the brotherly or<br>
familial love.  It is neither good nor bad.  Phileo is not necessarily<br>
a selfless type of love, either.  It is basically, "I love you because<br>
of what you do for me, or because of what I am when I'm with you."  In<br>
the discourse between the Risen Christ and Peter, Jesus asks Peter<br>
twice if Peter loves Him with an agape type love.  Peter responds with<br>
(paraphrased), "Yes, Lord, I phileo You."  Finally, Jesus asked him if<br>
he did love Him with a "phileo" love.  And it is at this point I want<br>
to stop for a moment.<br>
<p>
There is a uniqueness about what we as Christians are called to with<br>
respect to love.  The word agape is used consistently for the type of<br>
love we are called to.  Yet, often, our love is in the phileo stage,<br>
and so remains for a long time in some cases.  I don't know that this<br>
presents a problem -- initially.  But we must all yield to the Spirit<br>
if we are ever to grow beyond simply phileo.  Agape love conveys the<br>
sense of love without reason or strings attached.  I don't know too<br>
many people who show this sort of love, even inside the many churches<br>
of Christianity.  It is a rare commodity.<br>
<p>
Yet, it need not be so.  Phileo can, and should, lead to agape.  As He<br>
loved (agape), so we should love (agape) others.  And initially, it<br>
will start as phileo.  But by teaching the disciples of Christ what is<br>
meant by the love that Jesus calls us to, they will then have<br>
something to model.<br>
<p>
The arguments in the churches seems to come from the fact that the<br>
love of many is a base sort of love.  It is self-centered love (see 1<br>
Cor. 13 for more on this subject).  Those who are spiritual elders in<br>
the Faith need to exhibit agape, in as much as is possible for them as<br>
mere humans.  It is on the shoulders of the elders of the Faith that<br>
the task of discipling and leading falls, and if the congregants of a<br>
church are at war, then where must we start with the repairs and<br>
healing!?  <br>
<p>
Elders, please look to your own lives for a moment and examine<br>
yourselves as to the love you show in your dealings with the other<br>
saints about you.  What level of love are you presenting to them to<br>
model?  What level of love are you teaching them both in word and<br>
deed?  And this is not to sound pompous nor self-righteous for the<br>
Lord knows well, as do I, that I fail in this myself.  But we have a<br>
heavy task placed upon us -- to whom much is given, much is required.<br>
<p>
I know this does not directly address Dave's posting, but I hope it<br>
helps some.<br>
<p>
BTW, Dave, PRAISE GOD!!  He has saved your position yet again!<br>
<p>
En Agape,<br>
<p>
Gene<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
