<title>Jun_1992: mother's pride</title>
<h1>mother's pride</h1>
Ben Clausen (<i>GRIBCL%LLUVM.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 01 Jun 92 08:56:44 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#2">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#2">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#2">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#2">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Tim Swensen: "day of crucifixion"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Gross: "Re: What is Love (Agape)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here is a quote from the Desire of Ages (page 145) on a mother's pride. It is<br>
in relation to Mary at the feast of Cana:<br>
 <br>
   "As Mary had heard the disciples' testimony in regard to Jesus, she had been<br>
   gladdened with the assurance that her long-cherished hopes were not in vain.<br>
   Yet she would have been more than human if there had not mingled with this<br>
   joy a trace of the fond mother's natural pride."<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This doesn't seem to be particularly critical of a mother's natural pride.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
