<!-- body="start" -->
Well, I am reluctant to lean on Pathfinders too hard, having enjoyed it<br>
as a youngster and also having been a leader for several years.  However,<br>
my experience as leader was quite different from what Steve was talking<br>
about.  Our club was so little and the members of the church so poor that<br>
we could not afford the uniforms (why are they SO expensive?).  So, we<br>
could not participate in the fairs, parades, and other competitions<br>
because uniforms were a requirement for participation.  Never the less, we<br>
had a club -- my husband and I bought matching t-shirts for all the kids --<br>
and we were very active in witnessing, visiting the elderly, as well as<br>
crafts and general fun.  The kids loved it, the parents loved it (mostly for<br>
the break from the kids one evening a week and on weekends!), and it was<br>
an all around good experience.  I hope something like that is going on<br>
when our kids (forthcoming) are that age -- and I hope somebody young and<br>
energetic as we were is around to lead out!<br>
 <br>
Lola Aagaard<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
