<title>Jun_1992: HIGH SABBATH - The Jews Answer</title>
<h1>HIGH SABBATH - The Jews Answer</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 02 Jun 92 07:19:55 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#6">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#6">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#6">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#6">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: HIGH SABBATH - The Jews Answer (Continued)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Lola: "Pathfinders"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I asked the Jews what is meant by High Sabbath.  Here are their answers.<br>
Their answers do not pin down a relationship to the weekly Sabbath.<br>
And yet while "preparation day" for the 7th day Sabbath makes sense,<br>
it really does not fit Passover.  And, while dealing with the dead on<br>
a weekly Sabbath was not allowed, it would have been acceptable in<br>
the weekly Sabbath context.  There was a distinction in what you could<br>
do on a weekly Sabbath vs an annual Sabbath.  That is the case even today,<br>
according to the Mishna.<br>
<p>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<i>&gt;Evidently in the early hundreds CE the term High Sabbath was used,</i><br>
<i>&gt;at least by some.  Today the meaning seems to be lost to speculation.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Does anyone have any historically authentic explanation to offer?</i><br>
<i>&gt;Any seriously plausible speculation?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;One theory is that it means an annual Sabbath coincident with a weekly</i><br>
<i>&gt;Sabbath.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Another is that it is one of the more important annual Sabbaths of</i><br>
<i>&gt;the year.  But then which ones?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Thanks,</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;David Buxton</i><br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Hard to tell without the context, but the Sabbath before Passover is <br>
known as "the Big Sabbath" (Shabbat HaGadol).<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Hi Dave -- long time no hear.<br>
<p>
I don't know the early history, so this is more of a modern day<br>
view.  The Sabbath before Yom Kippur is often referred to in this<br>
way.   However, as Yom Kippur is sometimes on a Sabbath day, some<br>
people might consider Yom Kippur occurring on a Sabbath to be a<br>
great Sabbath -- but even then, I think the more common use today is<br>
the Sabbath immediately before Yom Kippur.  [Day of Atonement]<br>
<p>
Rosh HaShanah begins a period of repentance by Jews and judgement<br>
by G-d, -- there's a prayer said on those days, which poetically<br>
pictures G-d seated with the hosts of heaven around, and on Rosh<br>
HaShanah G-d records in his books the fate of everyone for the<br>
coming year, and on Yom Kippur he seals the books.  So the<br>
intervening days - including one Sabbath -- the great Sabbath --<br>
are days to repent, to reflect, to plan the year, to plan to be a<br>
better person and to do acts of goodness and charity -- for this<br>
same prayer says that even G-d's edicts can be made less severe<br>
through our own actions of prayer, repentence and charity.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
At a guess this sounds like Shabbos Hagadol which is the Sabbath<br>
before Pesach.  The question is what language was this in, what was<br>
the context, and how was the reference set up.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
No problem, it sounds even more as the Sabbath before Passover as<br>
the name translates as the"Great Sabbath" or "Big Sabbath"<br>
By definition it is alway a sabbath day that occurs each year.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
It might conceivably be a translation of "shabbat shabbaton" or<br>
Sabbath of Sabbaths, a term used especially for the Day of Atonement.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Here are some miscellaneous observations, none historically verified to<br>
the period in question.<br>
<p>
Yom Kippur is called "shabbat shabbaton" (in Leviticus, I think), which<br>
one might call a sabbath of sabbaths.  Note also that Yom Kippur is the<br>
day when the Jubilee year was proclaimed (and possibly the sabbaticals<br>
also).<br>
<p>
The Shabbat before Pesach has held an important place in the calendar.  It<br>
is known as Shabbat haGadol "the great sabbath" in modern times (at<br>
least since the 18th century, probably much earlier).  Other sabbaths<br>
during the year have names as well, although none seem to correspond as<br>
well to your question, off the top of my head.<br>
<p>
Hope this is not a rehash of what you already know.<br>
<p>
Shabbat Shalom,<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Sorry if I spoke over your head.  I assumed from your interesting<br>
question that you knew more than you actually do about Judaism.  <br>
<p>
Anyway, Pesah (hebrew for "passing over") is indeed Passover and the<br>
sabbath preceeding it is known as Shabbat hagadol (hebrew: "the great (or<br>
big) sabbath).<br>
<p>
I might suggest that you look at some of the great books about the Jewish<br>
calendar.  Check out your local library or university library.  A<br>
couple of suggestions off the top of my head are Michael Strassfeld,<br>
"The Jewish Holidays" and Arthur Waskow, "Seasons of our Joy" --<br>
these are both modern, practical guides to the holidays along with<br>
historical information about the holidays and calendar.  There are<br>
also a number of denser books about the traditional calendar, which you<br>
can find in the bibliographies of those two.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
If you like I could inquire as to what the Jews have to say about<br>
annointing the dead on a weekly Sabbath vs an annual Sabbath?<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
