<title>Jun_1992: A curious reference to SDA's</title>
<h1>A curious reference to SDA's</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Jun 92 12:37:05 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#10">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#10">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#10">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#10">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Dave Buxton: "What to do about Anger"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Eric Snyder: "Anger"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yesterday's June 3 NPR Morning Edition included a piece from the BBC.<br>
In it, a chap was interviewing the editor of Belgrade, Yugoslavia's<br>
only independent newspaper regarding Slobodan Milosevic, the president<br>
of what's left of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro?).  The editor<br>
characterized Milosevic as a political opportunist and not an idealogue.<br>
If my memory serves me, the editor added something like "He's not a<br>
Marxist, he's not a Communist, he's not any of those.  If it served him,<br>
he might be a Freemason, a [.. I can't remember exactly, but it was<br>
respectable ..], or even a Seventh-day Adventist."<br>
<p>
Did anyone else catch this?  It piqued my curiosity as to what that editor<br>
in Belgrade knows or thinks he knows about SDA's.  8-)<br>
<p>
Reminded me of the time a few years back when I was traveling and<br>
flipped on PBS on the motel room's TV.  It became shortly evident that<br>
the program was surveying feminist movements in various lands.<br>
A particular interview occured in Cuba.  The interviewer asked the<br>
Cuban woman how feminism appealed to women in Cuban society.  The only<br>
detail to the response that I remember is that the feminist could not<br>
persuade Seventh-day Adventist women to join.  ... I was proud of 'em!<br>
<pre>
-- 
