<title>Jun_1992: What to do about Anger</title>
<h1>What to do about Anger</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 04 Jun 92 15:29:14 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#11">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#11">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#11">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#11">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steve Hix: "Re: What to do about Anger"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Fred Christiansen: "A curious reference to SDA's"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steve Hix: "Re: What to do about Anger"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Guess I'm surprised we didn't see an avalanche of posts in response<br>
to the request for help regarding a friend having a problem with<br>
anger.  What is Christianity all about if we cannot answer questions<br>
like that?<br>
<p>
I've been telling myself that I've been posting a bit<br>
too often, talking too much and need to sit back on the listening<br>
end a bit more.  But I guess I'll plunge in here.<br>
<p>
A tape of a sermon by an ex-druggie evangelist comes to mind.  He was<br>
telling his story about his former life styles.<br>
<p>
He compared two schools that he attended:  One was a no rules coed<br>
type of school where it was ok to have room mates of the other sex.<br>
The idea was to have the maximum fun with the minimum of rules.<br>
He describes how close to suicide he came.  The other school he<br>
compared it with was a military academy with a very tough regimen.<br>
This he described as where he enjoyed the happiest of his school days.<br>
<p>
Why is it that the no rules sort of a system seems to have so much<br>
appeal to people as being the answer to love and happiness.  And<br>
yet, even by the metrics of the world its missery and it offers one<br>
of the most direct paths to suicide.<br>
<p>
There is the story of a high school class that bannered their class<br>
moto of something to the effect of lets all go off and seek happiness<br>
and let the world be d_____.  Lets go and be selfishly happy, is<br>
what they were saying.  That sounded intruiging and so somebody<br>
tracked the class for the next several years.  They experienced an<br>
unusually high incidence of divorce, failure, even suicide.<br>
<p>
What happens when somebody comes face to face with suicide?  They can<br>
do do it.  That of course would be too bad.  But lets say that the<br>
response is -- OK, I'm about the most miserable person in the world.<br>
Lets pretend I just jumped off the bridge.  I'm dead now.  My own<br>
happiness no longer means anything to me.  From here on I'm going<br>
to set my life asside.   So now instead of pursuing<br>
my own happiness I'm going to go help others.  I'm going to try<br>
and bring happiness to a lot of other people.  You all know whats<br>
going to happen -- The discovery that helping others brings happiness<br>
to ourselves.  Anyone whose total focus is on himself is doomed to<br>
misery, and anger.  Anyone who aggressively pursues the helping of<br>
others is going to benefit the most himself.<br>
<p>
What about anger?  If we are helping someone who has no feet, how<br>
can we be angry with someone who has stolen our shoes?  If we are<br>
helping someone who is homeless and lives under a highway overpass,<br>
then how can we be angry if our insured house burns down?  If we are<br>
helping someone miserable with AIDs, how can we be angry about<br>
a bit of hay fever?<br>
<p>
But even a Budhist can learn that.  To turn to Jesus we don't have<br>
to pretend that we have jumped off a bridge.  Yet, to dedicate our<br>
lives in service to Him we do have to die to self.  Is that death<br>
to self the end of happiness?  No!  Not by a long shot.  Amazingly<br>
enough it is the beginning of the only true form of happiness that<br>
humans can come to know.  In the service of our King there is much<br>
more to do than helping bums under a bridge.  We can also bring people<br>
to eternal salvation.  In that context, what room is there for<br>
anger?  Only to the degree that we turn inward on ourselves, so miserable<br>
that we are not happy enough; to the degree that we are selfish, to<br>
that degree will we be angry and miserable.  Instead we must turn<br>
in service to our creator who has taught us the rewards of being<br>
a servant rather than a master.<br>
<p>
If we die to self, we die to the pursuit of personal happines and<br>
set out in pursuit of the salvation and well being our our neighbor.<br>
Jesus is our example of how to go about doing that.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
