<title>Jun_1992: Anger and how to deal with it</title>
<h1>Anger and how to deal with it</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Jun 1992 18:10 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#13">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#13">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#13">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#13">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Anger and how to deal with it"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steve Hix: "Re: What to do about Anger"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0014.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Anger and how to deal with it"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I've given some thought about the problem with internal anger and the<br>
fear that it would erupt into rage.  Physical exercise, as suggested,<br>
would help a bit but there are others things one can also do.  For example,<br>
I was told once by a professional that rolling rocks (not boulders!) down<br>
a hill can release angry emotions.  Also throwing rocks at a tree or other<br>
appropriate target out in the woods can help.  Personally, I found one of<br>
the best ways to defuse anger was to fly a kite (honest!).  Many times I<br>
saw my life much like the kite.  When there was an average amount of wind<br>
(adversity), the kite seemed to fly the best.  The sudden absence of wind<br>
was catastrophic (the kite crashed) and huge gusts of wind would send the<br>
kite into fits.  As I fly my kite, identifying my own anger about my<br>
personal winds, I would relax and dissipate much of my angry energy.  I've<br>
tried "helping others" in the past but this usually left me feeling quite<br>
irritable and agitated unless it involved physical activity such as<br>
gardening, painting, etc.  Another activity I found helpful was to wash<br>
and hand wax my car (or somebodyelse's).  All of the approaches, however,<br>
do not address the underlying cause.  Clearly, feelings of rage and being<br>
out of control are signals that something needs to be done about your life.<br>
For example, I used to try to attend and participate in almost every<br>
church/ward function possible.  Soon I found that I had no time to just<br>
sit and relax, clean my house, or exercise.  My pent-up agitation about<br>
consumed me until I realized that if I cut back to only minimal activities<br>
and allowed myself to stay home and do things I needed to--then I felt<br>
less angry.<br>
<p>
Obviously, anyone who feels to the point of rage needs to try to identify<br>
the "why" and "what" of the underlying problem.  A professional counselor<br>
can really help here.  Although it may cost some money, it's worth it in<br>
the long run because internal anger will eventually destroy your physical,<br>
spiritual, and/or mental health.<br>
<p>
Cheryl Berthelsen<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
