<!-- body="start" -->
I think that we have to realize that anger is a natural emotion and even God<br>
gets angry sometimes.  The Bible tells us, "Be ye angry, and sin not, let not<br>
the sun go down upon your wrath."<br>
<p>
I personally know what it is like to repress emotions, it's a behavior that <br>
at one time I indulged quite frequently.  I would make up imaginary<br>
arguments in my head with other people that I wouldn't otherwise dare to<br>
confront.<br>
Now I've moved to the point where I like to talk things out more.<br>
<p>
Anger can be a sign of two things(at least):<br>
<p>
1)  A source of love being threatened.<br>
<p>
2)  A response to control that someone else exercises over you.<br>
<p>
A close friend of mine went for counseling to a psychiatrist, and she <br>
was told, "Write down everything that makes you angry."<br>
<p>
Bit by bit, as she wrote down the various things that made her angry<br>
she realized how others had been manipulating her, and then she was able <br>
to relate in a way so that she would not be vulnerable to this, thus<br>
reducing the amount of anger.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<p>
<p>
"Remember, he's not a real doctor."<br>
                                    "I've got a masters degree--in Science."<br>
