<title>Jun_1992: Church _en Francais_</title>
<h1>Church _en Francais_</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 14 Jun 1992 06:22:57 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#20">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#20">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#20">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#20">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "SDA Hospital Ethics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Patricio Navia: "Farewell (temporary) to sda-l &amp; Sdanet."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yesterday I had the opportunity to visit the French-speaking main<br>
Adventist church here in Geneva.  It was interesting in many respects,<br>
not the least of which is because I hardly understand a word of French. <br>
Nevertheless, <br>
I could tell just from the form that was followed that they were having the <br>
mission story in Sabbath school, or the announcements, or the nominating <br>
committee report, or scripture reading as the case may be.<br>
<p>
I saw at the SDA church what I had also seen posted in various places<br>
on the street, a poster advertising a full-scale model of the Bible<br>
sanctuary, which is displayed in Lausanne.  Evidently they are planning<br>
to have it up all summer as a outreach tool.<br>
<p>
Our church is marked on all the maps of the city, and listed in the various<br>
public church listings, so it's well known and easy to find.<br>
<p>
Geneva is essentially a Protestant city, thanks to John Calvin and friends,<br>
so most of the big old churches are Protestant churches, including the giant<br>
Temple de St. Pierre.  Here it is possible to see the very pulpit from<br>
which Calvin and Farel preached in the early days of the Reformation. <br>
Also there is a pipe organ to die for.<br>
<p>
I'm having more fun than I can stand, and getting a bit of work done, too.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
