<title>Jun_1992: SDA Hospital Ethics</title>
<h1>SDA Hospital Ethics</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Jun 1992 00:09 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#21">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#21">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#21">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#21">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Steven Timm: ""God loves you, but....""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0020.html">Steven Timm: "Church _en Francais_"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Although I am no longer a member of the SDA Church I still receive <br>
the Pacific Union Recorder and the Adventist Review.  I read this <br>
mostly out of curiosity now and occasionally find something that <br>
really bothers me.  This week's Recorder has an article entitled <br>
"AHS/West seeks new ways to focus hospitals on mission."  The first <br>
four sentences posed four questions and then stated that<br>
<p>
"these are only a few of many ethics problems pondered at a mission <br>
conference sponsored by Adventist Health System/West".  <br>
<p>
The questions were:<br>
<p>
"How much involvement should a Seventh-day Adventist hospital <br>
have in community affairs such as holiday events, blood drives, <br>
health fairs, service clubs, parades, and disaster relief programs?"<br>
<p>
"Should Adventist hospitals accept funds raised by spontaneous <br>
nonAdventist community-sponsored projects when those funds come <br>
from walk-a-thons, auctions which include locally produced art, <br>
jewelry, wine and a weekend trip to Las Vegas or from a gala ball <br>
held on Friday night or Sabbath?"<br>
<p>
"In the current economic survival climate, when is it acceptable for <br>
an Adventist hospital to joint venture with another hospital serving <br>
the same geographical area?"<br>
<p>
"How many nonAdventist employees are acceptable in an Adventist <br>
hospital?"<br>
<p>
My personal opinion is that *IF* these are really the "tough ethical <br>
questions" facing Adventist hospital in the US, then somebody is <br>
really hiding their head in the sand!  NonAdventist hospitals struggle <br>
with REAL ethical questions such as:<br>
<p>
How many nonpaying welfare patients can we afford to care for and <br>
when should they be shipped to county facilities?<br>
<p>
Can we afford to do honest diagnosis coding when the level of <br>
reimbursement for Medicare patients is based solely on the codes <br>
rather than the actual care given?<br>
<p>
What do we do about uninsured but not poverty stricken (at least <br>
not yet) patients and their families?<br>
<p>
<p>
What really appalls me about this article on the SDA ethical <br>
"dilemmas" is the second question about accepting funds if raised by <br>
methods not "approved" by the church (BTW, I never knew walk-a-<br>
thons and the sale of art was evil!).  Now come on people!  Have we <br>
lost all the thinking leaders in the SDA church?  Is this really a <br>
problem?  <br>
<p>
If you look in the Bible, you find many, many instances where God's <br>
people were given gifts from pagan cultures and there was no <br>
question that this was to be accepted and put to use in the Lord's <br>
work.<br>
<p>
Take the Exodus of Israel from Egypt.  The Israelites were told to ask <br>
for gold, silver, and clothing from their Egyptian neighbors and in <br>
Exodus 12:36 it says in the NIV that they "plundered the Egyptians".  <br>
We know later that this silver, gold, and precious clothe was used to <br>
build and furnish the wilderness Sanctuary and to make priestly <br>
garments.  Did it matter that much of the jewelry so obtained was <br>
probably used in pagan Egyptian worship?  NO!  It was sacred to the <br>
Lord and his work.<br>
<p>
How about the fall of Jericho.  In Joshua 6:19, the Israelites are told <br>
that all the gold, silver and articles of bronze and iron were sacred to <br>
the Lord and must go into His treasury.  This was plunder and booty <br>
from a pagan city.  They were not told to leave any golden idols <br>
behind but give all to the Lord's treasury.<br>
<p>
What about the Queen of Sheba's visit to King Solomon found in I <br>
Kings 10?  The Queen of Sheba (from a pagan country) gave Solomon <br>
120 talents of gold, large quantities of spices and precious stones.  <br>
Did Solomon first ask her about where all these riches came from?  <br>
No!  In fact, the following verse says that Hiram's ships brought gold <br>
from Ophir and great cargoes of Almugwood and precious stones.  <br>
The wood was used to make the supports for the Temple and the <br>
Royal Palace.  They also made harps and lyres for the musicians.<br>
<p>
What about the gifts brought by the three wise men to Baby Jesus?<br>
<p>
Lastly, what about Paul's discussion about whether meat that had <br>
been offered to idols should be eaten?  He clearly indicates that the <br>
history of an object (where it came from, where it's been, how it has <br>
been used before) is irrelevant to Christians.<br>
<p>
Gifts given to God's church are to be accepted and used for His work.  <br>
It should not matter in how the money was raised.  I would like to <br>
ask these SDA hospital "ethicists" the following questions:<br>
<p>
Would they accept a large donation from an SDA member if they <br>
knew the money was won in a state lottery?<br>
<p>
How about money from law suit settlement?  (I had a great aunt who <br>
was in a car accident years ago.  She promised the Lord that half of <br>
whatever she got from the insurance company to settle the damages <br>
would be donated to help build her local SDA church.  As you can <br>
guess, they graciously accepted her gift of $25,000 and I suppose she <br>
felt that the settlement was larger because half had been "dedicated" <br>
to the Lord).<br>
<p>
Recently, Pacific Union College Alumni Association was raising money <br>
by offering Master Card and Visa credit cards to church members.  <br>
We were told that a certain percentage of the interest on these card <br>
would be given to PUC.  Knowing what SDAs know about God's plan <br>
to NOT live on credit, is this within the guidelines of "ethical" <br>
fundraising?<br>
<p>
<p>
Cheryl Berthelsen<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
