<title>Jun_1992: "God loves you, but...."</title>
<h1>"God loves you, but...."</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Jun 1992 04:05:11 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#22">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#22">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#22">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#22">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Steven Timm: "Transition is complete"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "SDA Hospital Ethics"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0024.html">Jim Dunn: "Re: "God loves you, but....""</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
How many times have we heard the phrase "God loves the sinner, but he<br>
hates the sin." ?  While I don't dispute that God hates sin, I wonder<br>
the message<br>
we are sending when we say "God loves you, but..."  It is my experience<br>
that when the statement "I love you" is followed by "but", then what<br>
comes afterward doesn't matter, the message has been made clear that<br>
whatever love<br>
is offered is conditional.<br>
<p>
What would be a better way to express the unconditional love of God?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
