<title>Jun_1992: Re: "God loves you, but...."</title>
<h1>Re: "God loves you, but...."</h1>
Jim Dunn (<i>nol2321@dsacg2.dsac.dla.mil</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Jun 92 8:06:03 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#24">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#24">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#24">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#24">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Victor Ortiz: "Re: "God loves you, but....""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Steven Timm: "Transition is complete"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0022.html">Steven Timm: ""God loves you, but....""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0025.html">Victor Ortiz: "Re: "God loves you, but....""</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; How many times have we heard the phrase "God loves the sinner, but he</i><br>
<i>&gt; hates the sin." ?  While I don't dispute that God hates sin, I wonder</i><br>
<i>&gt; the message we are sending when we say "God loves you, but..."  It is</i><br>
<i>&gt; my experience that when the statement "I love you" is followed by a</i><br>
<i>&gt; "but", that what comes afterward doesn't matter, the message has been</i><br>
<i>&gt; made clear that whatever love is offered is conditional.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; What would be a better way to express the unconditional love of God?</i><br>
<p>
Well Steve, the best way I could come up with was, "For God so loved<br>
the world that He gave His Only Begotten Son."<br>
<p>
But I wonder if we sometimes focus *only* on the unconditional Love of<br>
God without loving the person enough to also tell them about the<br>
immutable justice of God.  We know that "God is Love," and we also know<br>
that "justice is the foundation of His throne."  It would seem to me<br>
that telling a person about the Love of God without explaining that He<br>
is also exercising mercy towards us, because of our sin, would be only<br>
half the story -- sort of like eating the cake but not getting any<br>
icing...<br>
<p>
We would do well to remember that it cannot be the Love of God *alone*<br>
that saves us from the lake of fire, for those who will be standing in<br>
that fire will also be recipients of the unconditional love of God.<br>
<p>
It is not only the Love of God, but also His Grace that we need.  If you<br>
do a study on Grace, you will find that it is much more than forgiveness;<br>
it is also Power -- the great Power of God to "will and to do of His Good<br>
Pleasure."  We must not sit back and drink in the Love of God without also<br>
seeking His Grace.<br>
<p>
I tell people of the Great Unconditional Love of God, but I also try to<br>
explain that His Grace and Forgiveness are Conditional -- that we must be<br>
baptised into death with Him for those things to be ours -- we must die<br>
to sin AND self for Christ cannot share the throne of our hearts with any<br>
other god -- we cannot serve two masters.<br>
<p>
"For God so Loved the world that He gave His Only Begotten Son, that<br>
whosoever BELIEVETH on His, should not perish but have everlasting life."<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
  | James Dunn, USA-DoD-DLA-DSAC-OLC, Tech-N-Logistics, FTS(614)692-9713 |
