<!-- subject="Re: SDA hospital ethics" -->
<!-- id="9206171628.AA19728@quad4" -->
<!-- inreplyto="SDA hospital ethics" -->
<title>Jun_1992: Re: SDA hospital ethics</title>
<h1>Re: SDA hospital ethics</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Jun 92 9:28:27 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#26">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#26">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#26">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#26">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Steven Timm: "I'm back"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Victor Ortiz: "Re: "God loves you, but....""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; "these are only a few of many ethics problems pondered at a mission </i><br>
<i>&gt; conference sponsored by Adventist Health System/West".  </i><br>
<p>
Since we do not have the whole list we do not know what the others are.<br>
Hence, it is difficult to come up with a list of the issues which we judge<br>
are the heavy-duty ones in order to compare/contrast them with the ones which<br>
they feel are the heavy duty ones.  I have no idea why the writer selected<br>
these, but I unwilling to assert that these *must* be THE heavy-duty issues.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; "How much involvement should a Seventh-day Adventist hospital </i><br>
<i>&gt; have in community affairs such as holiday events, blood drives, </i><br>
<i>&gt; health fairs, service clubs, parades, and disaster relief programs?"</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; "Should Adventist hospitals accept funds raised by spontaneous </i><br>
<i>&gt; nonAdventist community-sponsored projects when those funds come </i><br>
<i>&gt; from walk-a-thons, auctions which include locally produced art, </i><br>
<i>&gt; jewelry, wine and a weekend trip to Las Vegas or from a gala ball </i><br>
<i>&gt; held on Friday night or Sabbath?"</i><br>
<p>
Cheryl, I appreciate your Scripturally-based arguments on what money<br>
*is* acceptable.  Do you feel, then, that any and all money is acceptable?<br>
How about money from a drug dealer?  (NPR had a story one time about a<br>
dealer who was loved in his community because of his generosity towards<br>
community projects such as gyms, community centers, etc.)  How about<br>
money from a purveyor of pornography?  How about money for abortions?<br>
Wherever the line is drawn, the policy should be based upon Scriptural<br>
principals, so your contribution is helpful.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; "In the current economic survival climate, when is it acceptable for </i><br>
<i>&gt; an Adventist hospital to joint venture with another hospital serving </i><br>
<i>&gt; the same geographical area?"</i><br>
<p>
There are some hints of moral relativism here which I hope they perceive and<br>
turn away from.  I would contend that 2 Corinthians 6:14 applies here.  As<br>
do the other Scriptural injunctions against partnerships (numerous in Proverbs)<br>
and any financial/legal involvement with non-Christians.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; "How many nonAdventist employees are acceptable in an Adventist </i><br>
<i>&gt; hospital?"</i><br>
<p>
A fair question since hospitals are to be an arm of SDA ministry and mission.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; My personal opinion is that *IF* these are really the "tough ethical </i><br>
                                                    ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
See my first comments.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; questions" facing Adventist hospital in the US, then somebody is </i><br>
<i>&gt; really hiding their head in the sand!  NonAdventist hospitals struggle </i><br>
<i>&gt; with REAL ethical questions such as:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; How many nonpaying welfare patients can we afford to care for and </i><br>
<i>&gt; when should they be shipped to county facilities?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Can we afford to do honest diagnosis coding when the level of </i><br>
<i>&gt; reimbursement for Medicare patients is based solely on the codes </i><br>
<i>&gt; rather than the actual care given?</i><br>
<p>
What evidence is there that SDA hospitals are falsifying diagnostic codes?<br>
If widespread, it would indeed by deceitful and a disgrace.  If rare, it<br>
would no less be deceitful and disgraceful, but *would* indicate that policy<br>
and practice is to be honest.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What do we do about uninsured but not poverty stricken (at least </i><br>
<i>&gt; not yet) patients and their families?</i><br>
<p>
Good questions.  I have been concerned for some time that SDA hospitals have<br>
been trending towards being run more like businesses rather than as<br>
ministries and missions.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What really appalls me [...]</i><br>
<i>&gt; Now come on people!  Have we lost all the thinking leaders in the SDA church?</i><br>
<p>
Very strong language!  There is much evidence to suggest otherwise.<br>
I know too many godly, self-sacrificing leaders, teachers, pastors,<br>
missionaries, doctors, et al, to agree.  Do we need to become wiser in<br>
applying God's ways to daily life?  I readily accept that.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Knowing what SDAs know about God's plan to NOT live on credit, is this</i><br>
<i>&gt; within the guidelines of "ethical" fundraising?</i><br>
<p>
To be honest, in all my SDA schooling (grade 1 thru B.S.) I never once<br>
heard anyone indicate that Scripture said Christians (let alone SDAs) must<br>
not borrow.  Oh, sure, here and there folk saying credit could be a trap,<br>
you just have to learn to use it wisely (even contemporaries such as Larry<br>
Burkett say credit is OK if managed properly).<br>
<p>
I did not learn what Scripture had to say re Lordship and financial matters<br>
(in the broadest sense) until I attended the Advanced Seminar of the Institute<br>
in Basic Life Principles (Bill Gothard, Jim Sammonds; and developed further<br>
in Men's Manual #2 and the Scriptural Principles for Financial Freedom<br>
videotape seminar by Jim Sammonds of IBLP).  I recommend this material<br>
heartily.  It changed our lives, and those of several friends, dramatically.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S. Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  For I know the thoughts that I have toward you, says the Lord, thoughts of
    peace and not evil, to give you hope and a future (Jer 29:11).
</pre>
