<title>Jun_1992: Re: Gifts of the Spirit</title>
<h1>Re: Gifts of the Spirit</h1>
Glen Pringle (<i>pringle@bruce.cs.monash.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 26 Jun 92 11:59:17 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#29">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#29">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#29">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#29">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0030.html">Steven Timm: "Gifts of the Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Rolaant: "Living the Christian Life"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0030.html">Steven Timm: "Gifts of the Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steven Timm writes:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; But a question I posed at that seminar, which was not answered to my</i><br>
<i>&gt; satisfaction at that time and still troubles me to some extent, is this.</i><br>
<i>&gt; If we see that a certain gift is missing from our church, what should we</i><br>
<i>&gt; do about it?  Must we be content with the gifts we have already, or</i><br>
<i>&gt; should we ask for more?  Is it appropriate to ask for a specific</i><br>
<i>&gt; spiritual gift?</i><br>
<p>
1 Cor 12:12-31 talks about the church having different gifts making<br>
up the whole body.  Specifically v28 says "In the church God has put<br>
all in place: in the first place apostles, in the second place<br>
prophets, ..." (Good News).  To me this passage says that a church<br>
needs all the gifts and if one is missing it is appropriate to pray<br>
that the gift which is missing be given.  I don't see anything<br>
inappropriate about praying for the church to receive a gift (as<br>
opposed to asking for something personally.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; As I read the Bible, it is appropriate:  1 Cor. 14:1  "Follow after</i><br>
<i>&gt; charity, and desire spiritual gifts, but rather that ye may prophesy."</i><br>
<i>&gt; When was the last time any of us prayed for the gift of prophecy?  Or</i><br>
<i>&gt; the gift of tongues, for that matter?  We know that "...your Heavenly</i><br>
<i>&gt; Father shall give the Holy Spirit to them that ask Him."</i><br>
<p>
I've remember being quoted 1 Cor 12:11, about the Holy Spirit giving<br>
gifts as _he_ wishes (emphasis as put by the pastor who told me this).<br>
What he said amounted to that we shouldn't pray for a specific gift<br>
(this was at a time when I was learning about tongues but that's<br>
another story :-).  But as you've noted, 1 Cor 14:1 tells us to<br>
"eagerly desire the greater gifts" (NIV, from memory).  I would see<br>
this almost as a command.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Are we asking?  Are we ready to receive?  Or is the Spirit already among</i><br>
<i>&gt; us, working, and most of us don't even know it?</i><br>
<p>
Yes, no, no (at least in some of the churches I've been involved in).<br>
The Holy Spirit is, I feel, largely undiscovered in the SDA church<br>
(well in this city at least).  We talk about the Spirit of Prophecy,<br>
and ask the Holy Spirit to come into our lives, but not a lot of<br>
people really know what they're asking for; they haven't learnt who<br>
the Holy Spirit is, what he wants to do for us, what the baptism of<br>
the Holy Spirit is (as opposed to water baptism - see Acts 1:1-5).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I hope we can build a doctrinal and practical discussion on the Holy</i><br>
<i>&gt; Spirit here on SDAnet, but more importantly I hope we can know the</i><br>
<i>&gt; working of the Spirit in our lives both individually and corporately.</i><br>
<p>
Amen<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<p>
