<title>Jun_1992: School Choice, Church and State</title>
<h1>School Choice, Church and State</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 25 Jun 1992 20:42:47 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#32">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#32">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#32">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#32">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Steven Timm: "alt.sdanet"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Bill Nickless: "SDAnet traffic history"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0037.html">Steve Hix: "Re: School Choice, Church and State"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Today saw President Bush introduce a plan which is a variant of many<br>
others he has put out.  The plan would set aside $500 million to be used<br>
as scholarships for elementary and high school children to attend the<br>
school of their choice, even a religious one.  Although no one in<br>
Washington thinks it will actually pass Congress, the advocacy of such a<br>
measure by the President of the United States is still cause for concern.<br>
<p>
My mind is drawn to the scene in South Africa, where for years our<br>
Adventist secondary schools accepted government funds (These funds have<br>
now been cut off.)  Of course, the government funds came with strings<br>
attached, and the string was that as long as they took these government<br>
funds, they could not admit Black students.  The siren song of<br>
government money (which provided about 10% of the school's operating<br>
costs) served to keep Adventist primary and secondary schools segregated<br>
in S. Africa long after Catholic and Anglican schools had disdained the<br>
government money and integrated.<br>
<p>
For a description of the situation in Australia, I would point to Colin<br>
Standish's book _Defenders Of The Faith_.  Though I don't remember all<br>
the details, he recounts one remark made to him by an education offical<br>
in <br>
the Australian church at the time:  "It was so easy to refuse government<br>
aid when none was offered."<br>
<p>
I realize that since I have no children, school-age or otherwise, this<br>
is a hypothetical situation for me.  I also realize that editorial views<br>
advocating just this type of aid to parents of children in parochial<br>
schools have been voiced by Roy Adams in the Adventist Review recently. <br>
So is this concern about government dollars going into our schools just<br>
an unfounded fear?  Do our schools in their weakened financial condition<br>
have the will power to stand up to the potential of a large chunk of<br>
cash?  Am I outdated in my concern, or is this really a problem?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Steven Timm: "alt.sdanet"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Bill Nickless: "SDAnet traffic history"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0037.html">Steve Hix: "Re: School Choice, Church and State"</a>
</ul>
</DOC>
