<title>Jun_1992: Re: school choice, church and state</title>
<h1>Re: school choice, church and state</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 26 Jun 92 08:02:34 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#34">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#34">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#34">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#34">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Randall A Helzerman: "School Choice, Church and State (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Steven Timm: "alt.sdanet"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; So is this concern about government dollars going into our schools</i><br>
<i>&gt; just an unfounded fear?</i><br>
<p>
How is this any different than the government allowing you to deduct<br>
charitable contributions (tithe) on your tax return?  In both cases<br>
the government is making a value judgement about what it thinks is<br>
important.  I would guess that most SDAs would consider such a tax<br>
deduction sacrosanct.<br>
<p>
We can argue that such a tax deduction is "right", because it promotes<br>
the social welfare of the society.  But so does school choice.  In<br>
both cases there may be a cost to be paid, though.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
