<title>Jun_1992: School Choice, Church and State (fwd)</title>
<h1>School Choice, Church and State (fwd)</h1>
Randall A Helzerman (<i>helz@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 25 Jun 92 21:42:34 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#35">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#35">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#35">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#35">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Steven Timm: "A new SDA-L experiment"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0034.html">McCluskey G: "Re: school choice, church and state"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Today saw President Bush introduce a plan which is a variant of many</i><br>
<i>&gt; others he has put out.  The plan would set aside $500 million to be used</i><br>
<i>&gt; as scholarships for elementary and high school children to attend the</i><br>
<i>&gt; school of their choice, even a religious one.  Although no one in</i><br>
<i>&gt; Washington thinks it will actually pass Congress, the advocacy of such a</i><br>
<i>&gt; measure by the President of the United States is still cause for concern.</i><br>
<p>
     As an SDA who is also a Libertarian (strange combo eh?  Any other<br>
Libertarian SDA's out there in netland?) I look at it from a different<br>
perspective.  To paraphrase a recent comment on SDAnet, God didn't<br>
give children to the state--he gave them to parents.  I believe that<br>
anything which gives parents greater control over the education of<br>
their children is inherently a good thing.<br>
<p>
The bill in question does not require anything of the private school <br>
except that they are legally a school.  Our schools already had to<br>
meet this standard.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  Am I outdated in my concern, or is this really a problem?</i><br>
<p>
     Not at all.  It is a definate source of concern when the state<br>
gets too much control over anything, most especially our institutions<br>
and church.  But this bill I percieve as weakening the power of the state<br>
over parents--many of whom simply can't afford to pay for both public<br>
and private schooling of their children.<br>
<p>
The ideal of course is that parents could send both their children and<br>
their $$$ whereever they wanted in a free market of school systems.<br>
However, since that is politically unfeasable at present, this is<br>
a good first step.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Steven Timm: "A new SDA-L experiment"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0034.html">McCluskey G: "Re: school choice, church and state"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
