<title>Jun_1992: Re: School Choice, Church and State</title>
<h1>Re: School Choice, Church and State</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 25 Jun 92 19:26:37 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#37">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#37">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#37">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#37">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: alt.sdanet"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Steven Timm: "A new SDA-L experiment"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0032.html">Steven Timm: "School Choice, Church and State"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0041.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: School Choice, Church and State"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Today saw President Bush introduce a plan which is a variant of many</i><br>
<i>&gt; others he has put out.  The plan would set aside $500 million to be used</i><br>
<i>&gt; as scholarships for elementary and high school children to attend the</i><br>
<i>&gt; school of their choice, even a religious one.  Although no one in</i><br>
<i>&gt; Washington thinks it will actually pass Congress, the advocacy of such a</i><br>
<i>&gt; measure by the President of the United States is still cause for concern.</i><br>
<p>
As well it should be.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; in the Australian church at the time:  "It was so easy to refuse government</i><br>
<i>&gt; aid when none was offered."</i><br>
<p>
Here, too.  I don't think that enough of us have really understood<br>
it though.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I realize that since I have no children, school-age or otherwise, this</i><br>
<i>&gt; is a hypothetical situation for me.  I also realize that editorial views</i><br>
<i>&gt; advocating just this type of aid to parents of children in parochial</i><br>
<i>&gt; schools have been voiced by Roy Adams in the Adventist Review recently. </i><br>
<p>
We can see pretty clearly that the public shool system is in shambles<br>
(there are some areas that are doing better than others, but they're<br>
shrinking).  I doubt if it has missed the notice of a lot of us that<br>
we're supporting both the public, and private school systems.  It can<br>
be a real burden, too.  This makes all the more tempting the feeling<br>
that we ought ot be getting some of it back.  We ought to be very careful<br>
how we "get some of it back".  Shoot, I'm paying taxes toward a public<br>
school system that I won't be using, and paying tithe that goes in part<br>
to a church school system that I'm also not using.  (Who said home-schooling<br>
was cheap?)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; So is this concern about government dollars going into our schools just</i><br>
<i>&gt; an unfounded fear?  Do our schools in their weakened financial condition</i><br>
<i>&gt; have the will power to stand up to the potential of a large chunk of</i><br>
<i>&gt; cash?  Am I outdated in my concern, or is this really a problem?</i><br>
<p>
If it isn't now, I think it will be.  And if we come to depend on outside<br>
money, it'll be all that much harder to do without it when the strings<br>
that come attached to the cash start to get uncomfortable.<br>
<p>
Watch for lots of persuasive voices clamoring to accept this money, because<br>
"it will only hurt the students if we don't take it".  Maybe so, but it's<br>
going to hurt a lot worse in the long run if we *do* take it.<br>
<p>
Anyone nervous about the way the current presidential election is going?  8}<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
