<title>Jun_1992: Re: School Choice, Church and State</title>
<h1>Re: School Choice, Church and State</h1>
Stan Macasieb (<i>Stan_Macasieb@isu.comm.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 26 Jun 1992 18:15:57 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">McCluskey G: "Re: Church and State and public schools"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Steven Timm: "SDAnet is 2 years old today"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0032.html">Steven Timm: "School Choice, Church and State"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The idea of a voucher system allowing parents the right to choose where to<br>
send their tax money and their children to is only another step in the <br>
erosion of the public school system in America.<br>
<p>
An idea originated by Thomas Jefferson, the public schools were designed to<br>
prepare children for life in the adult world, at least some level of<br>
competency in that world.<br>
<p>
The public school, by its nature, brings together children from different<br>
cultures and backgrounds in order that, as a byproduct of the three R's, <br>
they learn how to live with and understand people from other cultures.<br>
<p>
It is when people feel that a certain doctrine or principle should be emphasized<br>
in a child's education that we see a Balkanization of educational ideas. Results<br>
include the Catholic and our own SDA school systems.<br>
<p>
I see nothing wrong with their very existence, for they are free to espouse<br>
their doctrine as they see fit, so long as they still produce active members<br>
of this society. It is when government money, in the form of taxes, is used<br>
to, in essence, keep those parochial schools open is when the concept of<br>
the public school is undermined.<br>
<p>
For those who cannot afford a private school education, the voucher system is<br>
a tempting idea. Yet, pulling their money out of their local school will only<br>
erode even more the quality of the public school education. Not only the lack<br>
of funding will hurt the public school, but also the reinforcement of a<br>
lackluster image of public school education will be just as damaging.<br>
<p>
Not only that, you are saying that the government has abdicated its role<br>
as the educator of its citizenry, leaving it up to churches and entrepreneurs.<br>
Giving govt money to them is essentially an endorsement not only of their<br>
techniques, but of their doctrine.<br>
<p>
Because this country is looking again to the MTV quick fix for society's ills,<br>
the voucher plan will get more attention than it deserves. Drop it, George!<br>
<p>
--Stan Macasieb (stanm@comm.mot.com)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
