<title>Jun_1992: Re: Church and State and public schools</title>
<h1>Re: Church and State and public schools</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 29 Jun 92 08:24:19 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#42">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#42">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#42">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#42">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Steven Timm: ""Discovered--Noah's Ark""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0041.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: School Choice, Church and State"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; ... Not only that, you are saying that the government has abdicated</i><br>
<i>&gt; its role as the educator of its citizenry, leaving it up to churches</i><br>
<i>&gt; and entrepreneurs.  Giving govt money to them is essentially an</i><br>
<i>&gt; endorsement not only of their techniques, but of their doctrine.</i><br>
<p>
After reading SDA and religious liberty writings for many years, I<br>
have come to the opinion that the trend over the years has been toward<br>
the "isolationist" point of view.  That is, give us (churches) our<br>
religious liberty and we will go off into our own little world and we<br>
won't worry about society at large.<br>
<p>
Unfortunately, we do live in society.  Any government in any society<br>
has to promulgate some values else there won't be a government or a<br>
society.  Public schools, welfare, taxes, and defense are among the<br>
many areas where value choices have to be made.<br>
<p>
A religious liberty advocate may be right to, say, oppose prayer in<br>
public schools, or use of tax dollars to fund the military, or any<br>
other issue, but simply making choices on these individual issues is<br>
not enough.  One has to go further and outline a foundation upon which<br>
society's shared values should be based.  I have never seen this done<br>
by the folks pushing religious liberty the hardest.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
