<title>Jun_1992: a personal note of thanks to the Lord</title>
<h1>a personal note of thanks to the Lord</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Jun 92 11:02:18 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#18">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#18">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#18">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#18">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Patricio Navia: "Farewell (temporary) to sda-l &amp; Sdanet."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Dave Buxton: "CALVINISM - Posted on s.r.c."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A few weeks back, my eldest daughter (who just returned from Weimar Academy<br>
yesterday) was on a back-packing trip in the Sierras.  Sabbath afternoon,<br>
she, 3 or 4 friends, and a teacher decided to hike to the top of a nearby<br>
peak whose snowy top gleamed invitingly in the sunshine against an azure blue<br>
sky.  Near the top they had a choice of crossing a large snow patch or<br>
going around it.  To go around it to the left, up and around and down, would<br>
have involved scrambling over a field of loose granite "chunks".  To the right<br>
the sloping snow patch had a "knee" and dropped off towards who knows what.<br>
No good.  So, they chose to cross the snow.<br>
<p>
It might not have hit me either, since I have no experience in high country,<br>
but, in hindsight, they failed to recognize the effect of warm, sunny days<br>
and cold, even freezing nights on a snow bank.  The upshot was an icy crust<br>
of varying thickness, hiding the danger of a slippery slope.<br>
<p>
For the first x number of feet, their steps crunched through the crust to<br>
sure footing.  But then my Liesl took a step that didn't break through,<br>
slipped, and started to fall and slide downhill at the same time.  The fellow<br>
behind her, a slight fellow no taller than she, grabbed her and hung on.  With<br>
a little help, she was back on her feet.<br>
<p>
Once everyone's heart had calmed down they continued with much greater care.<br>
 From a vantage point, they looked back and could see where she fell, the<br>
distance to the knee in the slope, and what lay below.  Had the fellow not<br>
caught her, she was mere seconds from sliding off a cliff to rocks below.<br>
<p>
Praise ye the LORD. O give thanks unto the LORD; for he is good: for his<br>
mercy endureth for ever. (Ps106:1)<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S. Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  For I know the thoughts that I have toward you, says the Lord, thoughts of
    peace and not evil, to give you hope and a future (Jer 29:11).
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
