<!-- inreplyto="Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;" -->
<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;</title>
<h1>Re: Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;</h1>
Joseph Miceli (<i>miceli@reason.win.net</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Aug 1994 07:52:15</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#75">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#75">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#75">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#75">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0076.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Is abortion sin?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0074.html">Joseph Miceli: "Re: Is abortion sin?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0037.html">Marcus Stringer: "Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0122.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Marcus,<br>
<p>
You raise some good points.  However, part of the campaign of<br>
misinformation constantly waged by the abortion industry is to<br>
imply that a woman and her child, if she carries it to term in a<br>
crisis pregnancy situation, face the bleak certainty of no<br>
support, financial or otherwise, from any avenue, private or<br>
institutional.  This simply isn't true.  There are currently<br>
thousands of crisis pregnancy centers across the country<br>
offering free support services to the mother and child which<br>
range from medical treatment during and after pregnancy, to<br>
housing and job training and financial support while the mother<br>
struggles with what is undoubtedly a very difficult situation. <br>
Most of these centers are Christian, but some are Jewish, some<br>
secular, some feminist.  Unlike Planned Parenthood, which<br>
receives government tax dollar support to maintain its machine,<br>
and unlike abortion "doctors" who earn six figure incomes<br>
killing babies yearly, pro-life support centers are voluntarily<br>
funded and staffed by people who have nothing to gain<br>
financially from a woman in trouble.  CPCs exist, and are growing<br>
every day, and are addressing the very situation you described.<br>
<p>
One problem I have with the "every child a wanted child" slogan<br>
is its unrelatedness to reality.  It's the same thing as saying<br>
that if perfection in a policy area can't be achieved in the<br>
here and now, we should tolerate and even promote death as a<br>
proper and compassionate interim solution.  The problems you<br>
enumerated exist independently of whether abortion continues or<br>
not.  Third world hunger, overpopulation in many areas, unwanted<br>
children, violence in the home, violence in the streets, rape,<br>
murder, genocidal wars...all of these and every other variety of<br>
sin, misery and violence in our world will continue whether or<br>
not every child is wanted.  There simply is no direct one to one<br>
correllation between a child being planned and wanted and that<br>
child growing up to be a perfect citizen.  Many unwanted<br>
children grow up to be wonderful human beings, good parents,<br>
loving husbands and wives.  Many children who were planned and<br>
loved turn out to be human predators.  Many parents who didn't<br>
plan for a child or particularly want it at a certain stage in<br>
life end up being excellent parents as life itself teaches them<br>
the value of that child.  <br>
<p>
And if the unwantedness of an unborn child is just cause for<br>
its death, why not apply the same criteria to infants or<br>
toddlers, many of whom started by being wanted and loved, and<br>
end up being neglected and resented?  Ought society not step in<br>
and end their present and future misery?  Who knows, that dirty<br>
screaming little brat in the canned goods isle being yelled at<br>
by his mother could turn out to be a rapist; shouldn't we<br>
protect him (and others) from a probable life of misery and pain<br>
in the same unfailing way we do the unborn? <br>
<p>
The root problem fueling all others isn't unwanted pregnancies,<br>
it's sin - that bent we all have to do evil unless curbed and<br>
ultimately cured by Jesus.  Until He comes again and puts<br>
an end to sin and suffering, the interim solutions Jesus used are<br>
indeed the best.  Minister to the sick and troubled, give hope<br>
and help to those in less than ideal situations, respect and<br>
value the life God has given to each of us.  <br>
<p>
Joseph <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
