<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Is abortion sin?</title>
<h1>Re: Is abortion sin?</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Tue, 16 Aug 1994 07:06:09 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#76">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#76">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#76">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#76">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Stanleyned G. Macasieb: "Good-bye, for now"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Joseph Miceli: "Re: Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; When the children that are born are all loved, then I'll start picketing</i><br>
<i>&gt; the abortion clinics.</i><br>
<p>
Loved by *WHOM*, though?  Have you ever personally known a couple who had<br>
spent many years on a waiting list to adopt a child?  The length of the<br>
waiting list speaks of the unfulfilled demand for newborn infants to adopt.<br>
Are you implying that if all these couples adopted babies that would have<br>
otherwise been aborted, that they WOULDN'T be loved?  Keeping an "unwanted"<br>
child is not the only alternative to abortion.<br>
<p>
In another post, Marcus expressed concern about the "orphans" who go<br>
unclaimed because they are not aborted.  Given the large number of childless<br>
couples seeking such to adopt, perhaps someone could give details as to WHO<br>
and WHERE these supposedly "unwanted" children are, so that they can be<br>
adopted by those who have been waiting YEARS for that privilege. (Yes,<br>
many of them are willing to accept a handicapped child of another race,<br>
too.) Even in foreign coutries, the "orphan problem" is usually a<br>
result of the massive government red tape in allowing them to be adopted by<br>
"foreigners", rather than a lack of adoptive parents willing to assume that<br>
role.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; On the other hand, I do rather value my own life!</i><br>
<p>
As most people who have been allowed to be born do, I suspect. &lt;g&gt;  How<br>
secure is your own life, perhaps in the years to come, if being "unwanted"<br>
or "unloved" (by others) is ever considered grounds for terminating YOUR<br>
life?<br>
<p>
 /--------------+------------------------------------\<br>
<i> |              |  Internet: davesparks@delphi.com   |</i><br>
<i> | Dave Sparks  |  Fidonet:  Dave Sparks @ 1:207/212 |</i><br>
<i> |              |  BBS:      (909) 353-9821 - 14.4K  |</i><br>
 \--------------+------------------------------------/<br>
