<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Is abortion sin?</title>
<h1>Re: Is abortion sin?</h1>
Joseph Miceli (<i>miceli@reason.win.net</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Aug 1994 07:06:21</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#74">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#74">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#74">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#74">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Joseph Miceli: "Re: Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0073.html">Dennis Murphy: "re: abortion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Raylene,<br>
<p>
You wrote re: abortion<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt;I feel the industry must be maintained.</i><br>
<p>
Its all the big sin problem. I'd rather see children not be given the<br>
chance to live than to grow up unwanted. So many of our societal problems<br>
stem from children being abused or ignored by their parents.<br>
<p>
When the children that are born are all loved, then I'll start picketing the<br>
abortion clinics.<br>
<p>
On the other hand, I do rather value my own life!&lt;&lt;<br>
<p>
Unwanted by whom?  The mother and father?  Granted, in a crisis<br>
pregnancy (defined not as a life-threatening pregnancy but any<br>
one in which the mother feels herself in any kind of crisis) the<br>
baby is often not wanted by the mother and father for various<br>
reasons, but this in no way cancels the fact that most of those<br>
babies, if carried to term, are very much wanted by couples who<br>
cannot have children themselves.  A crisis pregnancy center I<br>
work with has found that only about 3% of crisis pregnancies end<br>
with a woman carrying a baby to term and giving it up to<br>
adoption to people who very much want that baby and will provide<br>
it a good home.  Of the women who choose to carry their babies<br>
to term rather than kill them, the vast majority choose to keep<br>
them and raise them themselves - much of the time alone, due to<br>
the "father" suddenly discovering the downside of sex and<br>
beating a hasty retreat.<br>
<p>
Raylene, the sad fact is that abortion, and the lifestyle<br>
changes in our society which have spawned it, have themselves<br>
largely created this "unwanted child" situation.  Prior to the<br>
1960's, almost 90% of unwed mothers carried their children to<br>
term and gave them up for adoption - now it's somewhere in the<br>
neighborhood of 5% nationwide.  Literally millions of<br>
unfulfilled requests for adoption die on the vine every year for<br>
want of babies to adopt, because the dominant culture screams<br>
out at a woman in trouble that the easiest, quickest and least<br>
troublesome way to end a tough situation is to abort her baby.<br>
Granted, there will never be a perfect 1-1 matchup between<br>
babies put up for adoption and couples who want them.  But the<br>
vast majority would, given current unfulfilled demand, be<br>
lovingly cared for in a heartbeat.<br>
<p>
My own opinion is that most people who are pro-choice are so in<br>
spite of the reality of what we know about the fetus at its<br>
earliest stages of development, simply because they can't see<br>
it. It doesn't exist outside the mother, and therefore we can<br>
safely theorize in comfort, passing legislation based on bad<br>
science (like Roe v. Wade) that has devastating effects on<br>
others. Interestingly, when women in crisis pregnancy situations<br>
are shown ultrasound images of their babies, even at very early<br>
stages of development, a growing majority - even of those who<br>
were very much intent on abortion - change their minds and<br>
choose to carry the baby to term.  Suddenly, the reality of what<br>
and who is inside them is graphically and visually shown them,<br>
and the lies they've been told by Planned Parenthood and others<br>
that their baby is just a blob of tissue are forcefully<br>
exposed. It is, after the baby who's life is taken from it, the<br>
woman who is most exploited by the abortion industry.  <br>
<p>
Despite misinformation to the contrary, the pro-life movement is<br>
largely populated by women, many of them post-abortal.  From the<br>
pain and suffering they've gone through has come their<br>
conviction and commitment to help others in like situations, and<br>
their stories are poignant and real.  If you'd like, email me your<br>
snailmail address, and I'll be happy to send you or anyone else<br>
some information on them.  God bless,<br>
<p>
Joseph <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
