<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;</title>
<h1>Re: Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Aug 94 17:39:16 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#122">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#122">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#122">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#122">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0123.html">Tony Dyson: "Results of sin"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0121.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "More on Gay Rights"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0037.html">Marcus Stringer: "Pro-Life, period &lt;Re: Abortion and all that&gt;"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Joseph,<br>
<p>
You share some excellent observations.<br>
<p>
It seems to me that we agree in practice more than we disagree in principle.<br>
Undoubtedly, the buzz words need to go, for there is no either/or to "pro-life"<br>
or "pro-choice."  Both supposed sides are at once "pro-life" and "pro-choice,"<br>
it's just that their focus, and the reasoning behind it is different.  <br>
Who's life<br>
and choices get consideration, and why?<br>
<p>
Here are four considerations (I'm sure there are many others) that seem<br>
to be missing from dialogues (do they exist?) on this issue.<br>
<p>
1) Freedom of choice a woman or a couple should have in using abortion.<br>
_Lack of_ freedom to choose NOT to have an abortion (I think that in China,<br>
abortion isn't an option in some cases, its mandatory), or to not pay tax<br>
for support of abortion.<br>
<p>
2) In spite of the wonderful work of crisis pregnancy clinics, too many<br>
children continue to be born in poverty by single mothers, or placed in<br>
orphanages where the older they get the more difficult it is to find a family<br>
(Not a small issue are some requirements for adoption that are still in<br>
place in many areas).  Parents are returning for kids they once gave<br>
to adoption, further disrupting their lives.<br>
<p>
Within this is the need for economic compensation and educational<br>
support for single or coupled women who carry the pregnancy to term.<br>
Or have the baby adapted.<br>
<p>
3) Picking and choosing where one wants their tax money to be<br>
spent will open up an economic "slippery slope" if you will... (for those<br>
familiar with this playing card in stirring up fears.)  ; )  Say for instance,<br>
if I want to stop my tax money from going to military spending,<br>
or subsidizing _tax breaks_ for some "religio-political" organizations?<br>
What grounds can be basis for exemption?  Will it be fair for other<br>
areas?<br>
<p>
4) Some people groups have, here to for, incurable, fatal genetic diseases<br>
in their population that don't appear in other groups.  Case in point, the<br>
Mediterranean community I posted about in "Eugenics....".  Should the<br>
rule against abortion, in general, apply without exception?<br>
<p>
Anyway, again I have no answers to impose on others, only a request<br>
for in depth, prayerful and loving dialogue/actions on this issue.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
