<title>Aug2_1994: Adventist Education</title>
<h1>Adventist Education</h1>
Jesse Lambeth (<i>jlambeth@unicomp.net</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Aug 94 22:05:35 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#9">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#9">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#9">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#9">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0010.html">SDA Net: "Re:  Adventist Education"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0008.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Abortion and all that"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi,<br>
  My wife and I are doing some long range goal planning and part of that is<br>
determining what the quality of education is in Adventist private schools. I guess what<br>
we are looking for is test scores that indicate the level of academic achievement for<br>
the school. i.e. 3rd grade children testing at 6th+ grade level, Average SAT's 1100+, etc.,<br>
Our Adventist education system has always been assumed to be high quality and what <br>
we need is hard evidence that proves it for us to base our decisions on. Our view is that a <br>
good educational system can pursue the highest academic standards without sacrificing <br>
the same level of committment to spiritual education. <br>
 <br>
 Thoughts,Statistics?<br>
jesse<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
