<title>Aug2_1994: Re: What does it mean?</title>
<h1>Re: What does it mean?</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Sat, 13 Aug 1994 00:55:29 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#7">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#7">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#7">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#7">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0008.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Abortion and all that"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Carlyle B. Edwards: "Babies Update"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Bill Sands, Jr. wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What does the Bible mean when it says that</i><br>
<i>&gt; the Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath?</i><br>
<p>
I've always interpreted that as applying to the case where Sabbath keeping<br>
becomes an end in and of itself, a "badge of righteousness", etc.  There are<br>
many examples of overriding principles which may actually supersede the<br>
letter of the ordinance itself, and Jesus even alluded to some of these.<br>
<p>
Take, for example, the case of a man whose house catches fire on Saturday.<br>
Although extinguishing the fire, technically, is "labor", if Sabbath is<br>
really "made for man" and his benefit, then rigidly interpreting it to<br>
prohibit doing something necessary is obviously contradicting the stated<br>
purpose.  Jesus cited the example of a man whose ox fell into a pit on<br>
Sabbath.  Winding up with a dead ox for the sake of conformity to an<br>
ordinance would not benefit the owner of the ox.  In a more contemporary<br>
context, how many SDAs would stop to change a flat tire that occurred on the<br>
way to or from Sabbath services?  Most, I'd guess.<br>
<p>
One historical event worth noting is the Maccabean revolt.  The Jewish<br>
rebels at first refused to fight on Sabbath, but this "rule" became an<br>
obvious weakness, and they finally fought on Sabbath and prevailed.  It must<br>
also be remembered that Joshua's march around Jerich lasted for seven<br>
consecutive days, one of which obviously was the Sabbath.<br>
<p>
I've often wondered aboout those who "labor" on Sabbath, such as SDA<br>
pastors, ushers, organists, and SS teachers.  Do they "keep" Sunday as a day<br>
of rest to compensate for their Sabbath labors?<br>
<p>
 /--------------+------------------------------------\<br>
<i> |              |  Internet: davesparks@delphi.com   |</i><br>
<i> | Dave Sparks  |  Fidonet:  Dave Sparks @ 1:207/212 |</i><br>
<i> |              |  BBS:      (909) 353-9821 - 14.4K  |</i><br>
 \--------------+------------------------------------/<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
