<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Abortion and all that</title>
<h1>Re: Abortion and all that</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Sat, 13 Aug 1994 00:56:01 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#8">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#8">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#8">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#8">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Jesse Lambeth: "Adventist Education"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0007.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: What does it mean?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
George Tasker wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Let us now consider the case of the poor lady who falls pregnant to a </i><br>
<i>&gt; rapist.  On the basis of the above if the baby is a boy then that boy will</i><br>
<i>&gt; possibly have the same tendency as the father.  So this boy reaches teen </i><br>
<i>&gt; years or more and rapes another girl himself.  Which then is the greater </i><br>
<i>&gt; sin?  Is it to have an abortion in the first place thereby preventing this</i><br>
<i>&gt; problem or should the pregnancy be allowed to go ahead in the full</i><br>
<i>&gt; knowledge  that coming from a rapist that this is going to significantly</i><br>
<i>&gt; increase the  chances that the person will grow up and commit the same</i><br>
<i>&gt; crime as his sire?</i><br>
<p>
It's an interesting hypothesis, although I think the figures show that only<br>
a tiny fraction of the elective abortions are for the reasons you have<br>
stated as acceptable.  The Bible, however, speaks to the question of<br>
executing a child because his father was a criminal:<br>
<p>
Ezek 18:19 "Yet you ask, `Why does the son not share the guilt<br>
           of his father?' Since the son has done what is just<br>
           and right and has been careful to keep all my<br>
           decrees, he will surely live. (NIV)<br>
<p>
Ezek 18:20 The soul who sins is the one who will die. The son<br>
           will not share the guilt of the father, nor will<br>
           the father share the guilt of the son. The<br>
           righteousness of the righteous man will be credited<br>
           to him, and the wickedness of the wicked will be<br>
           charged against him. (NIV)<br>
<p>
The fact is, the Bible advocating judging the son on his own merits, rather<br>
than engaging in a "preemptive first strike" based on the theory that he<br>
MIGHT follow in his father's footsteps.  Another thing you've overlooked is<br>
a greater than 50% probability that a rapist's offspring might be FEMALE. To<br>
carry your idea to its logical conclusion, you'd have to at least wait until<br>
the child was born and determine his/her gender prior to doing a "preventive<br>
execution", since presumably few baby girls grow up to be "rapists".<br>
<p>
Like I said, it's an interesting hypothesis, but I don't even think the<br>
so-called "pro choice" camp is actively promoting THAT idea as justification<br>
for the MILLIONS of abortions performed every year.<br>
<p>
The other nasty side effect of that theory is that it undermines the role of<br>
a person's free will and responsibility for his/her actions.  Would you like<br>
to see accused rapists turned lose on the theory that "my father was a<br>
rapist, so I was genetically pre-disposed to be one, too"?  If you want to<br>
eliminate rape, you'd have to try the tactics of Pharaoh and Herod, and kill<br>
ALL the male children.<br>
<p>
 /--------------+------------------------------------\<br>
<i> |              |  Internet: davesparks@delphi.com   |</i><br>
<i> | Dave Sparks  |  Fidonet:  Dave Sparks @ 1:207/212 |</i><br>
<i> |              |  BBS:      (909) 353-9821 - 14.4K  |</i><br>
 \--------------+------------------------------------/<br>
