<!-- body="start" -->
Fred,<br>
<p>
A moving story, and I agree Elder Finley used great wisdom in<br>
answering the woman.  Her story points up the fact that the<br>
overwhelming number of abortions are performed as a form of<br>
post-conception birth control, and have nothing to do with the<br>
usual hypotheticals of rape, incest and danger to the mother. <br>
Sadly, women have been the ones hurt the most, and men have<br>
profited the most from legalized abortion.  Men want the fun and<br>
excitement of sex without the responsibilities, and women are made<br>
to bear the burden.  Thinking, under pressure as in Elder Finley's<br>
story, that abortion will provide a solution to the problem, women<br>
often consent to pressure from the man, only to find that they<br>
suffer from post-abortion syndrom, which manifests itself in a<br>
variety of ways.  Depression and anger are common, and a deep<br>
seated sense of guilt sometimes torments the woman for years,<br>
especially when she later carries a wanted baby to term.  <br>
<p>
If our society is so concerned that the rights of women who are<br>
the victims of rape, incest or who have problem pregnancies be<br>
protected, then do so.  But need we continue the abortion on<br>
demand industry so that men and women can pursue a reckless and<br>
valueless lifestyle at the expense of innocent children?<br>
<p>
Joseph Miceli <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
