<!-- body="start" -->
Harvey,<br>
<p>
Detailed replies to your points on the sanctuary will follow<br>
shortly, but one point I wish to make clear at the outset: I don't<br>
allow Ellen White's writings to "explain" or "interpret" the Bible<br>
for me.  To do so is simply to set her above Scripture, something<br>
you of course are at liberty to do, but which I will not.  The<br>
points I raise regarding the sanctuary as discussed by Paul in<br>
Hebrews will be confined to that epistle and other Bible material<br>
bearing on it.  To forestall your (probable) next question, yes, I<br>
believe sister White was a fully inspired prophet of God.  I do<br>
not accept her writings as canonical, which she herself denied. <br>
Either we examine the Bible without recourse to her writings as<br>
final arbiter, or we do not believe in "the Bible, and the Bible<br>
alone."  I'm setting this forth now so that we don't get<br>
sidetracked into a discussion of the inspiration of the Spirit of<br>
Prophecy, which is a worthy topic in itself, but not the topic at<br>
hand.<br>
<p>
Joseph Miceli <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
