<title>Aug2_1994: God's shadow</title>
<h1>God's shadow</h1>
Dan Crowe (<i>dcrowe@puc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 13 Aug 1994 13:42:28 -0700 (PDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#19">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#19">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#19">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#19">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0020.html">Dennis Hidalgo: "Dr. Hasel"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0018.html">Dan Crowe: "Mobile throne?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Fri, 12 Aug 1994 Bill Sands wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I do find a bit of a problem with the Bible texts which speak of God</i><br>
<i>&gt; as a being which does not cast a shadow...a shadow of turning as one</i><br>
<i>&gt; text says.</i><br>
<p>
The NIV translation of that verse, reprinted below, avoids that problem.<br>
<p>
  "Every good and perfect gift is from above, coming down from<br>
   the Father of the heavenly lights, who does not change like<br>
   shifting shadows."  (James 1:17, NIV)<br>
<p>
There are no other texts which might even imply that God does not cast a<br>
shadow.  Also the word for 'shadow' in James 1:17 occurs only in that<br>
verse.  Several other verses speak of God's shadow, however.  In most, if<br>
not all, cases, shadow is used figuratively in the sense of protection. <br>
Whether or not God casts a physical shadow is a moot question, IMHO.<br>
<p>
  "He who dwells in the shelter of the Most High<br>
    will rest in the shadow of the Almighty."  (Psalm 91:1, NIV)<br>
<p>
Four verses in Psalms (17:8; 36:7; 57:1; 63:7) use the phrase "under the<br>
shadow of [God's] wings." <br>
<p>
Two verses in Isaiah (49:2; 51:16) use the phrase "in the shadow of [God's]<br>
hand."<br>
<p>
Consider also the following verses: Psalm 121:5; Isaiah 25:4; Luke 1:35.<br>
Song of Songs 2:3 might also apply.<br>
<p>
Daniel Crowe<br>
Assistant Professor of Physics<br>
Pacific Union College<br>
dcrowe@puc.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
