<title>Aug2_1994: Re: What does it mean?</title>
<h1>Re: What does it mean?</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 14 Aug 1994 00:17:45 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#32">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#32">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#32">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#32">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "Breath or Blood"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0031.html">SDA Net: "Fact of life/potential for life"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave, as usual poses another interesting question.  Where do these come<br>
from???   he writes" I've often wondered about those who 'labor' on<br>
Sabbath, such as SDA pastors, ushers, organists and ss Teachers.<br>
As one of these "laborers" (a usher, deacon, SS teacher, and instrumentist)<br>
I can assure you that these are not "labors".  They are activities that<br>
mean a good deal to me.  They are part of being able to unwind.  I can't<br>
begin to tell you how many co-workers of mine have expressed amazement<br>
and admiration about the way that I can just lay everything down and forget<br>
about it for a day.  I have actually had co-workers tell me that they<br>
envy my ability to do this.  I try to share with them that they could<br>
do the same, but few ever do.  My personal opinion, is that if Sunday<br>
keepers would observe Sunday the way that Adventists observe Sabbath,<br>
they would gain a much greater and deeper blessing.  You don't know<br>
just how sweet it is to totaly forget your work concerns, and everything<br>
else and really rest and recharge.  Teaching SS and playing my<br>
instrument is a vital part of that recharging process for me.<br>
(I play the banjo, fiddle, and am working on the steel-drums, slowly<br>
I might add.  For something as simple looking as a steel pan, it is<br>
amazing how difficult it is to learn to play.<br>
<p>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker 		woody@knapper.cactus.org
