<title>Aug2_1994: Reading the mail</title>
<h1>Reading the mail</h1>
<i>LaurieD764@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Sun, 14 Aug 94 01:05:16 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#25">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#25">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#25">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#25">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Joseph Miceli: "(no subject)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Woody Baker: "shadows"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
When I get home from the last meeting on Sabbath (sometimes after midnight),<br>
I often unwind by "lerking" through the mail. Tonight was church board in my<br>
largest church.  We had a long agenda.  As I read thtough, I decided to<br>
respond to several things at once.<br>
<p>
 Although I did not know Dr. Hasel well, it hurts to know of his death.  I<br>
respected and admired him for his work, and his attitude.  I will feel the<br>
poorer knowing that he is no longer using his abilities for God.<br>
<p>
As to the rolling thrones...Our church has been studying Ezekiel in Prayer<br>
meeting, and as a matter of fact Ezekiel 1,3,10,11 and Daniel 7 all mention<br>
wheels in connection with the presence of God and His throne.  Does God use<br>
machinery...Or I.D. cards?  Can He understand computers?  If not, why not?<br>
 Maybe there's more of a reflection of God in humanity than we have realized!<br>
<p>
The discussion about pastors has been interesting and enlightening to me.  I<br>
often wonder what people's thoughts are, and I think that MOST of my church<br>
members are too nice to tell me their true thoughts when they are unhappy<br>
with something..  (Not that I feel unloved)  <br>
<p>
Here in Texas, our new conference president, Elder Steve Gifford has given<br>
each church a packet setting out a proceedure for finding a new pastor when a<br>
vacency occurs.  When I handed one to one of my Elders, he gave me a real<br>
strange look, untill I told him to keep it for the future.  The process<br>
involves communication between the church(es) and the conference on<br>
preferences, but the conference holds the last say.<br>
<p>
My wife is having a fusion on her neck Monday a week.  She has been in a lot<br>
of pain for a long time.  I covet your prayers for her.<br>
<p>
Well, I'm out for the night.<br>
<p>
God Bless you all<br>
<p>
Laurie Dewitt<br>
<p>
"I have determined to know nothing among you save Jesus Christ and Him<br>
Crucified"<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
