<title>Aug2_1994: (no subject)</title>
<h1>(no subject)</h1>
Joseph Miceli (<i>miceli@reason.win.net</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 14 Aug 1994 16:01:33</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#26">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#26">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#26">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#26">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Mladen Kuzminski: "144 000 - are they Jews?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">LaurieD764@aol.com: "Reading the mail"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Bill,<br>
<p>
The vision recorded in Ezekiel 1 and following is just that- a<br>
vision.  Visions communicate truth to us via symbols, such as the<br>
wheels within wheels that have puzzled Bible students for<br>
centuries.  No one seriously believes God was showing Ezekiel<br>
literal circles of wheels flying about in heaven; rather, He is<br>
communicating something of spiritual significance to us in<br>
symbol.  For someone to postulate that because Ezekiel saw wheels<br>
on God's throne the literal throne of God in heaven must also have<br>
wheels is to miss the meaning of the vision by a mile.  If<br>
everything shown in visions were literal, then we ought to believe<br>
that Jesus has snow white hair, eyes that burn with fire, legs of<br>
burnished to the color of brass, and so on.  When He speaks, we<br>
ought to expect to see a literal sword flash from His mouth, and<br>
when He addresses the wicked, we should witness Him thrash them<br>
with a literal rod of iron.  Obviously, we understand these things<br>
to be symbolic, just as the wheels of Ezekiel are symbolic.<br>
<p>
If the throne of God truly does have wheels making it mobile, why<br>
didn't He indicate such on the type, the ark of the covenant which<br>
always sat in the MHP of the tabernacle and sanctuary?  Here is<br>
the best representation we have of God's throne, and we don't find<br>
wheels at all.  It was always stationary, and always found in the<br>
MHP.  If types teach us about antitypes, then we ought to draw a<br>
reasonable correlation between the ark and God's throne in heaven.<br>
<p>
Another problem with conjecturing a mobile throne in heaven is<br>
that it somehow strikes one as a bit absurd.  What need does God<br>
have for a mobile throne?  And with infinite power at His command,<br>
with His throne room surrounded by beings who fly, why should He<br>
choose to place His throne on wheels to gain mobility?  Isn't this<br>
concept a bit of an insult to God?<br>
<p>
This idea is really just an attempt to get around the plain words<br>
of Paul in Hebrews that Christ had already entered into the MHP of<br>
the heavenly sanctuary in his day.  I'm recuperating from an<br>
allergic reaction to a wasp sting today, so I'll elaborate<br>
tomorrow.<br>
<p>
Joseph Miceli <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
