<title>Aug2_1994: How do we offer PRAISE?</title>
<h1>How do we offer PRAISE?</h1>
Bill Sands Jr. (<i>sands@andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 14 Aug 1994 16:24:34 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#28">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#28">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#28">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#28">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Mark E. Bishop: "Re: your mail"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Mladen Kuzminski: "144 000 - are they Jews?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0038.html">Dan Crowe: "Re: How do we offer PRAISE?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 From Bill Sands, Jr.<br>
<p>
In the New Testament we are told to praise the Lord no matter what.<br>
After reading that passage I began to wonder HOW we offer praise,<br>
especially when times arise where death and misfortune surround us.<br>
What constitutes offering praise? Is it only done in song? Or can<br>
it be merely an attitude? Does it have to be done out loud, or in<br>
a group, or by ourselves?<br>
<p>
For example, I am in absolute awe when I go out for a walk in the<br>
forest or through a vineyard (we have many of both in Michigan). Does<br>
a mental attitude of happiness and joy constitute praise to God?<br>
<p>
I also am in awe when I consider the many mechanical things which<br>
humanity has devised--the 747, the internal combustion engine,<br>
the many improvements in planting and harvesting.<br>
<p>
Those happy thoughts easily generate praise! But what about tragedy<br>
and sorrow? How do we praise God in our tears and fears? When an<br>
innocent child is shot by accident and dies--how do we praise at<br>
times like that?<br>
<p>
When a woman is raped and murdered in the big city or small town,<br>
how does her father and mother, or lover, or children praise God?<br>
Why would they want to offer praise?<br>
<p>
What does it mean to praise God no matter what?<br>
<p>
Is it unrealistic? Is it stretching the meaning of the text <br>
to say that whatever happens--praise the Lord?<br>
<p>
Any ideas?<br>
<p>
Bill Sands, Jr.<br>
sands@andrews.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
