<title>Aug2_1994: Re:  Close of probation</title>
<h1>Re:  Close of probation</h1>
SDA Net (<i>sdanet@andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 14 Aug 1994 17:41:34 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">SDA Net: "Fact of life/potential for life"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Mark E. Bishop: "Re: your mail"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I heard the close of probation best explained in a sermon by <br>
Smuts Van Rooyen.<br>
<p>
He points out that the common perception of the "close of probation"<br>
is actually putting people *on* probation--(better not mess up after<br>
the close of probation since there is no mediator).<br>
<p>
He points to the legal system and notes that in the legal sense, when <br>
your probation is up, the court has no more claims against you and <br>
you are free to go. The heavenly probation works the same way,<br>
Once it has been shown that you have been justified by Christ,<br>
there is no need to keep you on probation. <br>
<p>
Hope this helps....<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
