<title>Aug2_1994: Fact of life/potential for life</title>
<h1>Fact of life/potential for life</h1>
SDA Net (<i>sdanet@andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 14 Aug 1994 17:46:57 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#31">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#31">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#31">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#31">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0032.html">Woody Baker: "Re: What does it mean?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0030.html">SDA Net: "Re:  Close of probation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0054.html">Rolaant Loyd McKenzie: "Re: Fact of life/potential for life"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Too often the debate "abortion is murder" turns into a definition contest<br>
with various people disputing when life begins. <br>
<p>
One thing that is not in dispute, however, is that once a sperm and ovum<br>
unite, a unique combination of genes is created which has the potential to grow<br>
into a living human being.  I think the debate could sometimes be carried<br>
farther if we were to say:  "all right, the fetus may not be alive, but<br>
it has a unique potential for life.  How shall we protect that potential life?"<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
