<!-- subject="Re: Close of probation" -->
<!-- id="wwx<w" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Close of probation" -->
<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Close of probation</title>
<h1>Re: Close of probation</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 14 Aug 1994 19:18:58 -0700 (MST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">SDA Net: "Re: Close of probation (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Benjamin Siyowi Mapani: "when does life begin?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In-Reply-&gt;To: &lt;9408142141.AA29666@edmund&gt; from "SDA Net" at Aug 14, 94 05:41:34 pm<br>
<p>
[SDA Net writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; I heard the close of probation best explained in a sermon by </i><br>
<i>&gt; Smuts Van Rooyen.</i><br>
<i>&gt; [..]</i><br>
<i>&gt; He points to the legal system and notes that in the legal sense, when </i><br>
<i>&gt; your probation is up, the court has no more claims against you and </i><br>
<i>&gt; you are free to go. The heavenly probation works the same way,</i><br>
<p>
According to Webster's, "probation" can have these meanings:<br>
1)  critical examination and evaluation or subjection to such examination<br>
    and evaluation;<br>
2a) subjection of an individual to a period of testing and trial to<br>
    ascertain fitness;<br>
2b) the action of suspending the sentence of a convicted offender and giving<br>
    him freedom during good behavior under the supervision of a probation<br>
    officer<br>
<p>
Our time on earth is indeed a time of ascertaining our fitness for heaven<br>
(delaying for the moment what constitutes that fitness), so the "2a"<br>
meaning seems a good description.  It also seems that "2b" is a good<br>
description.  Permit me to elaborate.<br>
<p>
Adam and Eve were created in the physical, mental, and spiritual image of<br>
God (Gen 1:26).  God had great plans for them, but first their trust in<br>
and loyalty to God must tested (Gen 2:16,17) [1]; they were on probation.<br>
When they disobeyed God's clear command [2] and violated the terms of their<br>
probation [3], judgment would have been executed against them (eternal<br>
death), had not Jesus interposed (Rev 13:8), saying, "Let the punishment<br>
fall upon me" (cf. Isa ch.53).  This obtained for Adam and Eve a second<br>
chance, a second probation.  What love!  What mercy!  What grace!<br>
<p>
We, who were born after -- born physically, mentally, spiritually, and<br>
morally weakened -- are beneficiaries of that second probation (albeit<br>
the first for us).  The terms of this probation are basically the same<br>
(Rom 6:23, 8:6, 1 John 3:4), except for one important difference - God<br>
now supplies the desire and power to obey which we lack (Phi 2:13).<br>
Will we accept these gifts?<br>
<p>
During this time of probation, God has a plan of redemption, a plan of<br>
restoration.  This plan has two aspects (yet they are one, like siamese<br>
twins):  One part addresses the problem of our sins, the other the problem<br>
of Sin.  Jesus is the center of both.  By His death as our Substitute, we are<br>
reconciled; by His life as our Example, we are saved (Rom 5:10, Mat 1:21).<br>
Both have as their purpose to restore mankind to the image of God.  While<br>
our restoration physically and mentally has its limits and does not fully<br>
occur until Christ's coming (1 Cor 15:53,54), the restoration of our<br>
character, the spiritual/moral image of God, is not so limited (Eph 4:22-24;<br>
Col 3:9,10; Rom 12:2; Phi 2:5; Heb 8:10/Jer 31:33; 2 Pet 1:4).  Indeed,<br>
the character developed here on earth is the character taken to heaven,<br>
if it is fit for heaven.  Oh Lord, recreate me in Your image!<br>
<p>
The provisions made possible by Jesus' life, death, and resurrection are<br>
available to all.  But all will not benefit.  What is the key that unlocks<br>
this storehouse?  A belief, a faith, a trust in God that surrenders all,<br>
nothing held back, no double mind/heart.  The proof of this belief, this<br>
faith, this trust that God says what He means and means what He says is<br>
a life of obedience.  "Well done, good and faithful servant.  Enter into<br>
the joy of your Lord."<br>
<p>
[1] Note that the test was the lightest possible; there was not the slightest<br>
    need for Adam and Eve to eat of the forbidden tree.  Moreover Satan's<br>
    rebellion in heaven was explained to them and they were warned that he<br>
    would try to ensnare them.<br>
[2] Eve reckoned she could take a risk and not get conned (Jer 9:23,24),<br>
    while Adam could not conceive of there being any solution (cf. Isa 42:16)<br>
    to the problem he faced.  Each had their rationalization for distrusting<br>
    and disobeying God's command.<br>
[3] Trust and obey .. and live; distrust and disobey .. and die.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Once it has been shown that you have been justified by Christ,</i><br>
<i>&gt; there is no need to keep you on probation. </i><br>
<p>
Once justified, then no more on probation?!  Sounds like "once saved, always<br>
saved".  Sounds like "evangelical Adventism".  I submit that the parable<br>
of Mat 18:23-35 teaches us that probation continues even after forgiveness,<br>
that our sins can come back upon our heads and we can lose that justification.<br>
BTW, our sins are not blotted out (Acts 3:19; cf Jer 17:1) until the times<br>
of refreshing, which occur at the end of the anti-typical Day of Atonement.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen ("Canajun, eh?" from Ontario)  Email: fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com
Disclaimer: I do not speak for Motorola Computer Group       Fax: 602-438-3836
"For the transgression of a land many are the princes thereof: but by a man of
 understanding and knowledge the state thereof shall be prolonged." Prov 28:2
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
