<title>Aug2_1994: Re: How do we offer PRAISE?</title>
<h1>Re: How do we offer PRAISE?</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Sun, 14 Aug 1994 21:48:44 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Benjamin Siyowi Mapani: "when does life begin?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Tony Dyson: "Punishment vs consequences"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0028.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "How do we offer PRAISE?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0083.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: How do we offer PRAISE?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Bill Sands asked:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; When a woman is raped and murdered in the big city or small town,</i><br>
<i>&gt; how does her father and mother, or lover, or children praise God?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Why would they want to offer praise?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; What does it mean to praise God no matter what?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Is it unrealistic? Is it stretching the meaning of the text </i><br>
<i>&gt; to say that whatever happens--praise the Lord?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Any ideas?</i><br>
<p>
It's GOD that you're praising, not the circumstances.  Job did that.  He<br>
didn't "thank God" for the calamities, but rather for the fact that a loving<br>
God had a purpose, albeit unknown to him, for everything He allowed to<br>
happen to Job.<br>
<p>
Scripture says "*IN* everything give thanks", not "*FOR* everything".<br>
There's a difference.<br>
<p>
I can't claim a Job-like experience in my life, but I've had calamities in<br>
my life that I wondered how a loving God would allow.  In some of them, I've<br>
subsequently learned the answers, and in others I'm still waiting to be<br>
enlightened.  Many of them have boiled down to God removing "good" things<br>
from my life to make room for "better" things.<br>
<p>
These are principles that are best learned beforehand, because once you're<br>
faced with a seemingly "disaster", they tend to seem like pious platitudes.<br>
Romans 8:28 is the classic example of that.  I believe it's true, but it's<br>
not always tactful to quote that to a person in their hour of trouble and<br>
grief.  In the specific case you cited, one *COULD* speculate, but some<br>
things are better left unsaid.  There's a wonderful book writen by a<br>
Christian woman who was raped, became pregnant, gave the baby up for<br>
adoption, only to have the daughter search for her mother years later and be<br>
joyfully reunited.  That's an example of what God *CAN* do, but who's to say<br>
what He *WILL* do?  If the woman is dead in this case, then that's obviously<br>
not going to happen, of course.<br>
<p>
Consider the murder of Stephen.  Many believe that his death was one of the<br>
catalysts in the conversion of the apostle Paul.  The point being, sometimes<br>
the death of a single person has been used by God to set in action a chain<br>
of events that can benefit thousands or even millions of people.  That<br>
doesn't condone the criminal actions, of course, any more than the betrayal<br>
of Jesus which led to His death and our salvation justifies Judas' actions.<br>
<p>
 /--------------+------------------------------------\<br>
<i> |              |  Internet: davesparks@delphi.com   |</i><br>
