<title>Aug2_1994: Re: RE: Abortion</title>
<h1>Re: RE: Abortion</h1>
Joseph Miceli (<i>miceli@reason.win.net</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Aug 1994 08:16:36</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#53">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#53">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#53">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#53">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0054.html">Rolaant Loyd McKenzie: "Re: Fact of life/potential for life"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Joseph Miceli: "Re: Babies Update"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0023.html">Woody Baker: "RE: Abortion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Woody,<br>
<p>
Ignorance is a terrible thing when taken into the public arena<br>
and used to make policies which decide the fate of millions of<br>
unborn people.  Upon what do you base you opinion that the<br>
acquisition of knowledge is the critical criteria for<br>
personhood?  And where have you been hiding that you don't know<br>
that a baby in the womb is indeed acquiring knowledge<br>
appropriate to its stage of development?  My wife's baby is now<br>
coming up on 17 weeks, and that baby can just now hear and<br>
begin recognizing his mother's voice.  Does this not qualify as<br>
the acquisition of knowledge, or do you mean to imply that until<br>
a child can take information through its sensory organs,<br>
assimilate and classify that information in its brain, and then<br>
use selective cognition to further organize that info into<br>
rational thought and decisions it's not a human being?  If so,<br>
you'd better extend the line of demarcation between potential<br>
and actual humanity from birth to 1, 2, or even 4 or 5 years old.<br>
<p>
The argument that a fetus becomes a person when he takes "the<br>
breath of life" is a laugher.  Not only is the Genesis account<br>
unique to Adam and Eve, as they were formed directly by the hand<br>
of God from the dust of the earth, and thus needed life to be<br>
passed to them in a way humans ever since have not, but further<br>
it is God who breaths the breath of life into them, not they who<br>
of their own volition take that first breath.  Using your<br>
literal criteria in applying the Genesis account to all<br>
subsequent births, no one is ever a human being, since God has<br>
never once after Adam and Eve breathed into anyone's nostrils<br>
the breath of life.  All babies take that breath on their own,<br>
and for your information, Woody, they breath much earlier than<br>
their emergence from the birth canal.  They breath oxygen into<br>
their lungs via the amniotic solution they live in while in the<br>
womb.  Pre-born babies breathe every day; my baby is breathing<br>
right now.  Tell me, Woody, if something were to happen to the<br>
baby my wife is carrying right now, would I be amiss to grieve<br>
the loss of a human, or merely a potential human?<br>
<p>
Joseph <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
