<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Fact of life/potential for life</title>
<h1>Re: Fact of life/potential for life</h1>
Rolaant Loyd McKenzie (<i>rlm@sils.umich.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Aug 1994 08:46:06 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Dan Drazen: "Re: Skunks in EDEN?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Joseph Miceli: "Re: RE: Abortion"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0031.html">SDA Net: "Fact of life/potential for life"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0062.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Fact of life/potential for life"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In-Reply-&gt;To: &lt;9408142146.AA29806@edmund&gt;<br>
<p>
On Sun, 14 Aug 1994, SDA Net wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Too often the debate "abortion is murder" turns into a definition contest</i><br>
<i>&gt; with various people disputing when life begins. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; One thing that is not in dispute, however, is that once a sperm and ovum</i><br>
<i>&gt; unite, a unique combination of genes is created which has the potential to grow</i><br>
<i>&gt; into a living human being.  I think the debate could sometimes be carried</i><br>
<i>&gt; farther if we were to say:  "all right, the fetus may not be alive, but</i><br>
<i>&gt; it has a unique potential for life.  How shall we protect that potential life?"</i><br>
<p>
I think it could be carried even further. Having intercourse may not result <br>
in a new life, but the potential exists. Should we discourage contraception to <br>
protect this potential for life?<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
