<title>Aug2_1994: Punishment vs consequences</title>
<h1>Punishment vs consequences</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHAJD@wombat.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Aug 1994 10:11:40 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#40">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#40">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#40">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#40">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0041.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: How do we offer PRAISE?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Tony Dyson: "RE: Abortion and all that"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0070.html">Joseph Miceli: "Re: Punishment vs consequences"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On a completely different topic, Dave wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Would you like</i><br>
<i>&gt; to see accused rapists turned lose on the theory that "my father was</i><br>
<i>&gt; a rapist, so I was genetically pre-disposed to be one, too"?</i><br>
<p>
No, as a matter of fact if a criminal argued that they were genetically<br>
predisposed to commit crime, then to me that is all the more reason to <br>
lock them away rather than turn them loose.<br>
<p>
This brings up an interesting point, though - the idea of crime and<br>
punishment vs the idea of actions and consequences. "The wages of sin<br>
is death" - is this crime &amp; punishment, or cause &amp; effect? Is there<br>
any difference? Was Jesus' death on the cross a punishment for the<br>
sins of mankind? A consequence? Both, or neither?<br>
<p>
To preempt things a little, I am personally more comfortable with the<br>
picture of God saving humanity from the consequences of their actions,<br>
rather than Him punishing humanity for their depravity.<br>
<p>
	Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
