In-Reply-&gt;To: &lt;9408132335.AA02618@orion&gt; from "Bill Sands Jr." at Aug 13, 94 07:35:49 pm<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; With some of the theological beliefs about life in Eden changing</i><br>
<i>&gt; after the "fall", I wonder if God created skunks in Eden. And</i><br>
<i>&gt; if there were skunks in Eden, why were they equipped with such</i><br>
<i>&gt; a stink...</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Just wondering...were there skunks in Eden?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Bill Sands, Jr.</i><br>
<i>&gt; sands@andrews.edu</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; P.S. Will there be skunks in heaven?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Funny you should mention it, Bill.  I once wrote an (unpublished) story<br>
about some skunks on the Ark.  Any opinions that follow are purely<br>
speculative:<br>
<p>
As the fear of Man was not put into animals until after the Flood (Gen<br>
9:2), it's possible that skunks were "pre-equipped" with their trademark<br>
scent but didn't have occasion to use it up to a point.  Though when all<br>
the animals were on the Ark<br>
<p>
*Midrashic storytelling mode on*<br>
<p>
they must have compared notes as to their treatment at the hands of Man.<br>
So they resolved, if they couldn't kill the one placed in a position of<br>
superiority over them by the Creator, that the would have nothing to do<br>
with him and that self-defense was justified.  The skunks must have been<br>
nervous and fearful for their future until they realized their<br>
potential.<br>
<p>
*Midrashic mode off*<br>
<p>
Daniel J. Drazen<br>
Editor, SDA Periodical Index<br>
