<title>Aug2_1994: laypeople</title>
<h1>laypeople</h1>
Karin Thoresen (<i>kcthores@southern.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Aug 1994 11:49:49 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#60">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#60">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#60">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#60">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: APA Statement on L/G/B Youths in Schools"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: #2 response to Internet Replies/ASDAL"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
C. Edwards wrote: <br>
"... the conference offices would also be greatly improved <br>
if more of the ordained ministers were willing to move back into the <br>
field as pastors (the primary occupation for which they were trained and <br>
called) and allow more dedicated laymen and laywomen with expertise in <br>
the various areas, communications, law, accounting, business management, <br>
operations, administration, etc. to work and lead out in those areas."<br>
<p>
I agree with you wholeheartedly!  Who's to say that retired <br>
professionals, those wanting to stay home and raise a family, or even <br>
someone who's business is up and running "on auto-pilot" wouldn't be <br>
willing to work 1/4- to 1/2-time to do the work that a PASTOR is <br>
expected to do?!  Considering the re-training it would take to teach the <br>
ropes of a multi-million dollar "business" (i.e., the SDA church) to <br>
folks that have gone through schooling for preaching and evangelizing, <br>
etc. <br>
<p>
I think some of the mega $$ boo-boos in the history of our church would <br>
be motivation enough to look for godly men and women *professionals* in our <br>
congregations to fill these positions in the church hierarchy.  And get <br>
some of these preachers back in the field!!!<br>
<p>
Karin<br>
kcthores@southern.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
