<!-- inreplyto="Fact of life/potential for life" -->
<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Fact of life/potential for life</title>
<h1>Re: Fact of life/potential for life</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Aug 1994 12:04:13 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">AMY HACK: "a little of everything"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: APA Statement on L/G/B Youths in Schools"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0031.html">SDA Net: "Fact of life/potential for life"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0104.html">CONNELLE@vaxine.swac.edu: "Re: Fact of life/potential for life"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In-Reply-&gt;To: &lt;9408142146.AA29806@edmund&gt; from "SDA Net" at Aug 14, 94 05:46:57 pm<br>
<p>
Steve wrote,<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Too often the debate "abortion is murder" turns into a definition contest</i><br>
<i>&gt; with various people disputing when life begins. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; One thing that is not in dispute, however, is that once a sperm and ovum</i><br>
<i>&gt; unite, a unique combination of genes is created which has the potential to grow</i><br>
<i>&gt; into a living human being.  I think the debate could sometimes be carried</i><br>
<i>&gt; farther if we were to say:  "all right, the fetus may not be alive, but</i><br>
<i>&gt; it has a unique potential for life.  How shall we protect that potential life?"</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Now that this topic is no longer forbidden on this list, I'd like to<br>
make a few comments.  I think Steve has correctly stated where the real<br>
problem lies--the problem of definition of life.  In Western society we<br>
often fall into the trap of trying to categorize everything--in fact,<br>
much of science is based on this idea.  Even in computing we want the<br>
"switch" to be either on or off.  However, nature is not that simple.<br>
There are many ambiguities, and this is certainly one of them.  Both the<br>
beginning and end of life are processes rather than a precise point in<br>
time.  Even if one accepts a definition that life begins when a fetus is<br>
viable outside the womb, this would imply that the definition of life<br>
depends on the ability of scientific medicine to keep moving that date<br>
back earlier.<br>
<p>
Steve, I don't see any biblical or moral imperative to protect<br>
"potential life."  Removing the potential for life is not the same as<br>
murder.  After all, there's potential for life even before the sperm and<br>
the ovum unite.  I remain pro-choice.<br>
<p>
So far (as so often in this debate) I believe only males have discussed<br>
this.  I would like to hear more of a female perspective, as it is often<br>
quite different on this topic.  I found the cover article in _Time_ this<br>
week on genes and infidelity to be quite fascinating.  Is it possible<br>
that we males have a different perspective because we are concerned<br>
(probably unconsciously) that _our_ offspring might be threatened?  Just<br>
a thought.<br>
<p>
I appreciate the fact that so far this discussion has been happening<br>
without flames.  I hope we can keep it that way.<br>
<p>
Harvey<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
