<!-- body="start" -->
My grandfather died suddenly and unexpectedly last Sabbath morning.  I<br>
left town in such a hurry that I didn't suspend my mail on any of my<br>
discussion lists - I had over 200 postings this AM :( --didn't even<br>
thinkof dealing with any of it while I was out of town.<br>
<p>
I gave the invocation at the funeral and thought I'd share it with you<br>
as I note several letters reporting losses during the past week or so.<br>
In fact, while I was in Collegedale I saw the news reports about<br>
Olivia's death, and saw her parents reacting with dignity.  Recognized<br>
her father as a former acquaintance of mine.  My sympathy to Pam Harris<br>
and the Maizes.<br>
<p>
Lord,<br>
Remember your word to us, your servants, for you have given us hope.<br>
(deleted)<br>
May your unfailing love be our comfort.<br>
Let your compassion come to us that we may live.<br>
Amen<br>
<p>
I have found these verses (paraphrased) and others like them in<br>
Psalm 119 to be very comforting in the past week.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Amy Hack, Ph.D.<br>
Counseling Center Psychologist<br>
University of Tennessee - Martin<br>
AJ01@UTMARTN.Bitnet<br>
<p>
....the greatest of these is love...<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
