<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Close of probation (fwd)</title>
<h1>Re: Close of probation (fwd)</h1>
SDA Net (<i>sdanet@andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Aug 1994 18:39:56 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#44">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#44">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#44">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#44">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0045.html">KevJames@aol.com: "Abortion response"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Close of probation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Forwarded message:<br>
[My response to Fred]<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; [SDA Net writes:]</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; I heard the close of probation best explained in a sermon by </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Smuts Van Rooyen.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; [..]</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; He points to the legal system and notes that in the legal sense, when </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; your probation is up, the court has no more claims against you and </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; you are free to go. The heavenly probation works the same way,</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Once it has been shown that you have been justified by Christ,</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; there is no need to keep you on probation. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Once justified, then no more on probation?!  Sounds like "once saved, always</i><br>
<i>&gt; saved".  Sounds like "evangelical Adventism".  I submit that the parable</i><br>
<i>&gt; of Mat 18:23-35 teaches us that probation continues even after forgiveness,</i><br>
<i>&gt; that our sins can come back upon our heads and we can lose that justification.</i><br>
<i>&gt; BTW, our sins are not blotted out (Acts 3:19; cf Jer 17:1) until the times</i><br>
<i>&gt; of refreshing, which occur at the end of the anti-typical Day of Atonement.</i><br>
<i>&gt; -- </i><br>
<p>
Though Smuts van Rooyen was and is one of the leading proponents of <br>
evangelical Adventism, I did not do his sermon justice with the above <br>
reconstruction of a sermon that I heard in 1977 or thereabouts...<br>
He did not specifically tie "no further claims" to justification in that<br>
sermon.  But he did say that there is a time, before the 2nd Advent,<br>
that corresponds to the close of probation, where it will be clear that <br>
people are safe to save (and again I am paraphrasing his words.)<br>
<p>
I have heard the idea that your sins come back on you if you fall or something,<br>
but I don't believe it and don't think it can be classified as SDA theology.<br>
Can God cast our sins so deep into the sea that He can't retrieve them?<br>
I think so.  Rather, any falling away is a new sin with corresponding new <br>
penalty, but what is forgiven is forgotten.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
