<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;On a completely different topic, Dave wrote:</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; Would you like</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; to see accused rapists turned lose on the theory that "my father was</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; a rapist, so I was genetically pre-disposed to be one, too"?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;No, as a matter of fact if a criminal argued that they were genetically</i><br>
<i>&gt;predisposed to commit crime, then to me that is all the more reason to </i><br>
<i>&gt;lock them away rather than turn them loose.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;This brings up an interesting point, though - the idea of crime and</i><br>
<i>&gt;punishment vs the idea of actions and consequences. "The wages of sin</i><br>
<i>&gt;is death" - is this crime &amp; punishment, or cause &amp; effect? Is there</i><br>
<i>&gt;any difference? Was Jesus' death on the cross a punishment for the</i><br>
<i>&gt;sins of mankind? A consequence? Both, or neither?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;To preempt things a little, I am personally more comfortable with the</i><br>
<i>&gt;picture of God saving humanity from the consequences of their actions,</i><br>
<i>&gt;rather than Him punishing humanity for their depravity.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;       Tony</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
I agree completely.<br>
<p>
Joseph<br>
