<!-- sent="Tue, 16 Aug 1994 01:24:11 -0400 (EDT)" -->
<!-- name="Dennis Murphy" -->
<!-- email="UN041345@wvnvaxa.wvnet.edu" -->
<!-- subject="re: abortion" -->
<!-- id="wwx<w" -->
<!-- inreplyto="abortion" -->
<title>Aug2_1994: re: abortion</title>
<h1>re: abortion</h1>
Dennis Murphy (<i>UN041345@wvnvaxa.wvnet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Aug 1994 01:24:11 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#73">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#73">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#73">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#73">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0074.html">Joseph Miceli: "Re: Is abortion sin?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0072.html">Tony Dyson: "Another hypothetical"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>    &gt; a pre-born has no way of aquireing any knowlege, therefore is &lt;</i><br>
<i>    &gt; not a human being ...  If a feotus is non-viable, then I have &lt;</i><br>
<i>    &gt; absolutly no problem with aborting it.                        &lt;</i><br>
<p>
    The topic of abortion is serious--  much more so, in my opinion, than <br>
    most of the doctrinal issues that are argued about in this SDAnet.  As<br>
    I have studied the issue (and changed my position in the last several<br>
    years), I have observed that the most frequent arguments in favor of<br>
    "abortion-on-demand" refer to the negative effects of an unplanned <br>
    and/or unwanted pregnancy on someone's career, standard of living, <br>
    embarassment, difficulty, and etc.  Usually there is also the concern<br>
    expressed for the poor "quality of life" that an unwanted, disadvantaged <br>
    child will surely experience.  The most frequent arguments against<br>
    "abortion-on-demand" refer to the principles of the sacredness of life,<br>
    of concern for the weakest ones among us, and of responsibility for the<br>
    consequences of our actions.<br>
<p>
    I have decided that the principles used to oppose abortion are much more<br>
    noble and worthy of support than those in favor of abortion.  Life must<br>
    be considered as sacred, and not to be casually disposed of for the sake<br>
    of convenience.  Careers, living standards, prestige, and even "quality<br>
    of life" are matters of convenience.  Others in this world survive amid<br>
    situations that are worse than anything a disadvantaged or unwanted child<br>
    will experience in this country.<br>
<p>
    The statements quoted at the beginning of this message are typical of<br>
    careless and arbitrary rationalization, and do not reflect serious <br>
    thinking about this life and death issue.  The statement that a "pre-<br>
    born" shouldn't be considered as human because it cannot acquire <br>
    knowledge has been very well answered by another.  I would like to <br>
    respond to the statement about viability.<br>
<p>
    When is a fetus viable?  Today's limit of viability, before which some<br>
    believe that abortions are of no consequence, is tomorrow's successful<br>
    innovation when physicians manage to save one more baby that struggled<br>
    into the world a bit too early.  In the hospital where I work, there are<br>
    "pre-borns" that are newborns.  They struggle to stay alive in our neo-<br>
    natal intensive care unit.  Many of them are smaller than a lot of aborted<br>
    babies, so small that their skin has not even fully formed.  Many of <br>
    them survive and the bulletin boards in the hallway are filled with <br>
    their photographs years later.<br>
<p>
    Twenty five years ago none of these babies would have been "viable".<br>
    Is it really credible that a moral judgement, such as whether it is<br>
    wrong to kill a growing fetus, is dependent on the level of health<br>
    care technology?  We spend millions of dollars to save babies that<br>
    often are worse off than those who are aborted.  Sometimes the ones we<br>
    save are the ones who SURVIVE abortion attempts.  Why do we go to such<br>
    expense and effort, if not because these babies are human beings?<br>
<p>
    The parallels between the Holocaust, in which Jews and others were<br>
    progressively labelled as less than fully human, and today's abortion<br>
    industry are frightening.  Life must be considered as sacred, or else<br>
    your own life is in danger.<br>
<p>
    That's not all that could be said, but it's time to stop.<br>
<p>
    May God help us to defend those most helpless among us.<br>
<p>
    --Dennis.                   E-mail: un041345@wvnvms.wvnet.edu<br>
      Morgantown, WV<br>
<p>
    <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
