<title>Aug2_1994: Re[2]: Pastors</title>
<h1>Re[2]: Pastors</h1>
AMY HACK (<i>AJ01%UTMARTN.BITNET@uga.cc.uga.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Aug 94 10:31:18 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#79">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#79">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#79">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#79">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0080.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Breath or Blood"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Ted Barker: "Abortion &amp; Contraception"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0125.html">Dennis Hidalgo: "Re: Re[2]: Pastors"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In-Reply-&gt;To: In reply to your message of FRI 05 AUG 1994 12:37:07 EDT<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Amy:</i><br>
<i>&gt;	Seems that you are great advicing pastors. Could you help me with</i><br>
<i>&gt;this one. I am going to a new district this weekend. Seems that there</i><br>
<i>&gt;have been problems that I do not understand well yet and neither have</i><br>
<i>&gt;enough information of them.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Churcha and the place have a wonderful potential. I am relatively new in</i><br>
<i>&gt;the ministry and coming new to a church is always a difficult thing to do.</i><br>
<i>&gt;	As a church memeber, what would you expect from your new pastor?</i><br>
<i>&gt;What things would you like him not to do? How and how fast changes most</i><br>
<i>&gt;be brought?</i><br>
Sorry it has taken me so long to answer - my grandfather died and I was<br>
out of town all last week.  Off the top of my head:<br>
Transitions occur in stages - predictable phases which are experienced<br>
in different intensities and length of time by different people.<br>
<p>
1. Honeymoon phase :)  in which the transitioner is fascinated by the<br>
new place/role, feels eager to explore and make new friends, views life<br>
and the surroundings/people positively, and generally feels high<br>
energy.Toward the end of this stage however new thoughts/feelings creep<br>
in and the person/group says to self "I/we don't know who I/we am<br>
anymore".  "a mistake was made with this choice - must be the wrong<br>
choice."<br>
<p>
2.Hostility phase :(  in which the transitioners feel hostile toward the<br>
environment/other people, may act agressively, actively finds<br>
faults/shortcomings, criticizes, remembers/talks about how much better<br>
the former place/friends/environment was, feels and may talk about not<br>
really fitting inthis new place, etc.  This phase includes generalized,<br>
negative statements like "this church/school/whatever doesn't really<br>
care about its preacher/teacher/whatever". "Tennesseans are rude" etc.<br>
This is the phase where most people change jobs, bail out of marriage,<br>
call the conference, etc., drop out of school.<br>
<p>
3.  Humor phase  - if transitioners hang on during #2, they eventually<br>
begin to see some humor in their adjustment, begin to see some<br>
misunderstandings they had about the new environment/people, etc, find<br>
they can laugh at their mistakes, don't blame others for their problems.<br>
They are much more in tune with the social cues in the new environment<br>
and find they can have what feels like friendly contact rather than just<br>
business-like contact.<br>
<p>
4. At home - in which the new environment is accepted, new customs<br>
embraced, accepts new expectations, enjoys the differences from the<br>
past, and knows how to get along.  Feels secure and at-home, and if left<br>
this place would now miss it and feel a little homesick or lonesome for<br>
it.<br>
<p>
I would like my new minister to be aware of these phases that he will<br>
experience and to recognize that the corporate body will experience the<br>
same phases.  I would like  him to go gently...adjustment is a process<br>
that takes time and usually can't be hurried.  I appreciate ministers<br>
who invite suggestions, group involvement, make suggestions rather than<br>
commands, and ingeneral show respect for the decision-making ability of<br>
the church which functioned before he got there and will have to live<br>
with the decisions and changes after he's gone.<br>
<p>
"What we call the beginning is often the end.  And to make an end is to<br>
make a beginning.  The end is where we start from." T.S. Elliot<br>
<p>
Dennis, if you want more specific answers, just ask and I'll try to<br>
answer more specifically :)  I wish you the very best,  amy<br>
<p>
<p>
Amy Hack, Ph.D.<br>
Counseling Center Psychologist<br>
University of Tennessee - Martin<br>
AJ01@UTMARTN.Bitnet<br>
<p>
....the greatest of these is love...<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
