<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Abortion and all that</title>
<h1>Re: Abortion and all that</h1>
Gary Case (<i>gary@andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Aug 1994 15:25:44 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#86">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#86">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#86">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#86">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0087.html">Cori Bradford: "Good news"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Abortion and all that"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In-Reply-&gt;To: &lt;47@reason.win.net&gt; from "Joseph Miceli" at Aug 15, 94 07:49:47 am<br>
<p>
Much discussion has been going on regarding whether abortion is right or<br>
wrong and when life begins, but it seems to me the most important issue<br>
of the big abortion question in this country is the issue of choice.  I<br>
do not believe that abortions are a good thing.  I don't see how any<br>
Christian can support abortions (there are always exceptions and<br>
hypothetical situations that can be raised, of course).  However, I am <br>
pro-choice.  I belive that a woman should have the right to choose to<br>
have an abortion.  I don't think the government should be able to<br>
regulate such a personal decision.  Perhaps there should be some sort of<br>
mandatory counseling both before and after the procedure, but the right<br>
to choose must be maintained.  A woman (and hopefully the father, too)<br>
can alway s choose not to have an abortion.<br>
<p>
Gary Case            gary@andrews.edu, case@ucrph0.ucr.edu<br>
Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics<br>
UC Riverside<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
