<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Another hypothetical</title>
<h1>Re: Another hypothetical</h1>
Cori Bradford (<i>cbradfor@ida.org</i>)<br>
<i>16 Aug 1994 17:54:02 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#93">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#93">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#93">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#93">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0094.html">Jesse Lambeth: "RE: Auditing SDA Education..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0092.html">Cori Bradford: "Re: Are you ready...?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0072.html">Tony Dyson: "Another hypothetical"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0096.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Another hypothetical"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
        Reply to:   RE&gt;Another hypothetical<br>
<p>
Tony writes:<br>
<p>
&lt;DELETED&gt;<br>
<p>
Adventist girl and adventist boy in long-standing relationship<br>
have a nasty breakup. Later, girl meets another boy, they become<br>
friends, they date, and then become engaged. A few months before<br>
the wedding date, girl is visited by ex-boyfriend at night. <br>
After a confrontation she is raped by ex-boyfriend, and <br>
consequently falls pregnant. There is no question over the<br>
identity of the father, as this has been the only opportunity<br>
for conception. Ex-boyfriend, upon finding out that girl is<br>
pregnant, makes it clear that he will expect to have a part<br>
in the upbringing of the child.<br>
<p>
&lt;DELETED&gt;<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Hypothetically, the ex-boyfriend is a criminal, should not have<br>
ANY say-so in the upbringing of the child, and should be thrown<br>
in jail for his heinous behavior.<br>
<p>
Incidentally, I believe in turning the other cheek (and sometimes<br>
this is one of the hardest things Christians are called upon to do),<br>
but the ex-boyfriend would be truly blessed to escape a beating<br>
from the husband-to-be, the girl's father, and/or her brother(s).<br>
<p>
I'll share an incident from my childhood.  My Dad and I were<br>
walking home one afternoon, and my father stopped to chat with<br>
one of the teenage boys from the high school across the street.<br>
This boy's name was Jerome, and he was 17.  I was 12 at the time.<br>
Jerome was "friend of the family."<br>
<p>
While my Dad was talking with Jerome, I saw one of my friends,<br>
another girl who was 12.  When I heard my Dad tell Jerome that<br>
he'd see him later, I ended my conversation with my friend, and<br>
hurried to catch up with my Dad.  I was about 10 feet away from<br>
Dad, when Jerome caught my arm and tried to pull me toward him,<br>
whispering something vulgar.  I immediately called out, "Dad,<br>
help me!"  My father took one look, saw me struggling to pull<br>
away from Jerome, and quickly walked over to where we were.<br>
I won't tell you the specifics, but my father was steaming!<br>
He let Jerome know in no uncertain terms what would happen<br>
to him if he ever dared to try to touch me again.  From that point,<br>
whenever Jerome saw me, he would cross the street to avoid<br>
passing me, and I made it a point to always have one of my<br>
friends with me when I went anywhere.<br>
<p>
We lived across the street from DuSable High School, and one<br>
block from the Robert Taylor Homes in Chicago.  I used to hear<br>
about incidents of rape, but it didn't really sink in about how<br>
defenseless a girl or woman could be until the situation with<br>
Jerome.  At that point in my life, I really began paying close<br>
attention to my parents' instructions, and it has served me well.<br>
<p>
Have a pleasant evening!<br>
<p>
Cori Bradford<br>
cbradfor@ida.org<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
