<i>&gt; Much discussion has been going on regarding whether abortion is right or</i><br>
<i>&gt; wrong and when life begins, but it seems to me the most important issue</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the big abortion question in this country is the issue of choice.  I</i><br>
<i>&gt; do not believe that abortions are a good thing.  I don't see how any</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christian can support abortions (there are always exceptions and</i><br>
<i>&gt; hypothetical situations that can be raised, of course).  However, I am </i><br>
<i>&gt; pro-choice.  I belive that a woman should have the right to choose to</i><br>
<i>&gt; have an abortion.  I don't think the government should be able to</i><br>
<i>&gt; regulate such a personal decision.  Perhaps there should be some sort of</i><br>
<i>&gt; mandatory counseling both before and after the procedure, but the right</i><br>
<i>&gt; to choose must be maintained.  A woman (and hopefully the father, too)</i><br>
<i>&gt; can alway s choose not to have an abortion.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Gary Case            gary@andrews.edu, case@ucrph0.ucr.edu</i><br>
<i>&gt; Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics</i><br>
<i>&gt; UC Riverside</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; ===============</i><br>
What about the baby (foetus), does it not have a choice? The right to <br>
choose is practical as long as one person's choice does not overlook <br>
the other person's choice. Think on this. <br>
 <br>
<p>
    arap-Ng'apng'ap<br>
    serem@agreng.lan.mcgill.ca<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ <br>
What a joy to rest in His perfect redemption. <br>
