<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Another hypothetical</title>
<h1>Re: Another hypothetical</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 17 Aug 1994 07:07:13 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#96">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#96">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#96">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#96">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0097.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Abortion &amp; Contraception"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0095.html">Carlyle B. Edwards: "Re: Babies Update"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0072.html">Tony Dyson: "Another hypothetical"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tony wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Adventist girl and adventist boy in long-standing relationship</i><br>
<i>&gt; have a nasty breakup. Later, girl meets another boy, they become</i><br>
<i>&gt; friends, they date, and then become engaged. A few months before</i><br>
<i>&gt; the wedding date, girl is visited by ex-boyfriend at night. </i><br>
<i>&gt; After a confrontation she is raped by ex-boyfriend, and </i><br>
<i>&gt; consequently falls pregnant. There is no question over the</i><br>
<i>&gt; identity of the father, as this has been the only opportunity</i><br>
<i>&gt; for conception. Ex-boyfriend, upon finding out that girl is</i><br>
<i>&gt; pregnant, makes it clear that he will expect to have a part</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the upbringing of the child.</i><br>
<p>
Ex-boyfriend, aka RAPIST, belongs in a jail cell, not demanding his "rights"<br>
with regards to his biological offspring. (Under God's Law [Deut. 22:25],<br>
he'd reside under a pile of rocks.) Since when does a rapist have legal<br>
standing to get custody and/or visitation rights?  Since, as you've stated,<br>
it's a hypothetical case, put him in jail for a while, and if you parole<br>
him, make one of the conditions that he avoid contact with his victim and<br>
the child completely.<br>
<p>
Also, if the boy is supposedly an "Adventist", doesn't some sort of church<br>
discipline fit in there somewhere?  Surely no one is suggesting that what he<br>
"chose to do with his body" is a valid choice that he rest of us aren't free<br>
to question or judge.  Any sin might, ultimately, be a "choice", but not one<br>
devoid of consequences and penalties.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It's ridiculous using such hypotheticals as this in these </i><br>
<i>&gt; discussions, isn't it. All I can say is, if hypothetically</i><br>
<i>&gt; you happen to find yourself praying one of these days, perhaps</i><br>
<i>&gt; you could spare a thought for this hypothetical girl and her</i><br>
<i>&gt; fiance - pray that they can now live with whatever hypothetical</i><br>
<i>&gt; decision they may have made in this case.</i><br>
<p>
Has such a case ever occurred?  If so, how was it eventually decided? What's<br>
the alternative?  Kill the child to "protect" it from its criminal father?<br>
<p>
I'd pooh-pooh the idea if Dr. Kevorkian hadn't popularized and<br>
commercialized the notion of death as a "solution" to one's problems.<br>
<p>
