<title>Aug2_1994: Sabbath School</title>
<h1>Sabbath School</h1>
AMY HACK (<i>AJ01%UTMARTN.BITNET@uga.cc.uga.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Aug 94 08:46:38 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#98">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#98">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#98">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#98">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Craig Kinzer: "Re: 1844  (*^&amp;$%^$&amp;$^)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0097.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Abortion &amp; Contraception"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0119.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Sabbath School"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I would like any and all suggestions for the following:<br>
<p>
My church tried to have 2 Sabbath School classes but the one was so<br>
small that the few of us who decide these things felt we'd benefit most<br>
by all meeting together.  The class roll consists of the following<br>
people - our entire church, except for 3 adults who work with the kids:<br>
1 bachelor - 50's, hi school ed<br>
3 widows - 70's, hi school ed<br>
1 bachelor - 40's, college student<br>
2 single mom's - 30's (neither baptized SDA), college students<br>
1 married couple - 60's (parents of other 2 couples)<br>
1 married couple - 40's (professionals)<br>
1 married couple - 30's with new 1st baby, (professionals, 1 nonSDA)<br>
1 married man - 50's, plumber<br>
1 married woman - 60's housewife, elem school ed<br>
me, single - 30's, professional<br>
<p>
Several of the above attend sporadically and I counted how many of the<br>
above speak in class - 8 of them talk at least once in awhile, lessstudy<br>
the lesson or have much knowledge of the Bible, etc.  One of the<br>
quietestmembers told me she wished we could have 2 classes again and<br>
that one of them would be for younger people, more in tune with where<br>
she is (non-SDA, single mom, little knowledge).  I see that we aren't<br>
really helping her feel a part of us, she says she doesn't get anything<br>
from the study, etc. and I see that certainly her social needs aren't<br>
met.  She's not the only one, others have talked about not feeling<br>
revived/renewed/uplifted/whatever word fits for them.  I know part of<br>
the answer lies with them but what can the church do with limited<br>
people, time, energy, resources?  Only about 4-5 of us attend the board<br>
meetings, prayer meetings, plan the socials, invite people into our<br>
homes, etc. and now the school year is starting and some of us won't<br>
have the time we did in the summer.<br>
<p>
Suggestions for Sabbath School in particular?  or anything else?<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Amy Hack, Ph.D.<br>
Counseling Center Psychologist<br>
University of Tennessee - Martin<br>
AJ01@UTMARTN.Bitnet<br>
<p>
....the greatest of these is love...<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
