<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;On Aug 11, Bill Sands, Jr. wrote a number of things, including:</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;Something marvellous did happen in 1844 . Exactly what did</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;happen is still open to study. The major thing which happened</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;as far as I am concerned is that the opening of the spiritual</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;eyes to see that Earth is not the center of the universe,</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;and that there is a heavenly sanctuary in which God is,</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;and Jesus is there as my intermediary. This is a major</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;shift in focus, and opens the eyes to eternal verities.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Craig replied with this question...</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;This leaves me with a big question.  An intermediary is one who settles</i><br>
<i>&gt;disputes, reconciles disagreements.  If this is Jesus' job, He is working</i><br>
<i>&gt;for at least two parties.  Who are these two (or more) parties?</i><br>
<p>
The way I was raised on this was that there is a trial going on...<br>
<p>
The universe (the perfect portion) is the jury, God is the accused,<br>
Jesus is the defense attorney, Satan is the prosecuting attorney,<br>
and we are the evidence, and in this case, there is no judge.<br>
<p>
God already knows the outcome, but the jury is to be convinced so that<br>
when this is all over, there will be no question in anyone's mind that<br>
sin "just ain't worth it".<br>
<p>
God is the accused because He created us, giving us free will, allowing<br>
us to choose Him or another.<br>
<p>
Jesus is the defense attorney (I wouldn't want any other) who has been<br>
through what the evidence has been through, and much more.<br>
<p>
Satan is the prosecuting attorney because he want's to prove that God's<br>
way isn't the right choice.<br>
<p>
We are the evidence, because it is our free will to select God or Satan<br>
as our role model and leader.<br>
<p>
<p>
