<!-- body="start" -->
In-Reply-&gt;To: &lt;01HFX125IN04LKMNN4@WVNVMS.WVNET.EDU&gt;<br>
<p>
On Sun, 14 Aug 1994, Dennis Murphy wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; How do others of you understand the scriptures in 2 Cor 5:6-9 and Phil 1:23-24</i><br>
<i>&gt; in which the apostle Paul mentions his preference to be "absent from the body"</i><br>
<i>&gt; or to "depart", and thus in both cases to be with the Lord?  I don't believe</i><br>
<i>&gt; the Scripture contradicts itself, therefore I wonder how those words harmonize</i><br>
<i>&gt; with many other scriptures which describe a person's condition in death as</i><br>
<i>&gt; similar to sleep.</i><br>
<p>
Since death is similar to sleep, the next thing someone knows after death<br>
is the resurrection.  Therefore, as far as the person who died is<br>
concerned, he was alive in a sinful environment, and the next waking<br>
moment he is alive in a sinless environment.  With this understanding,<br>
there is no contradiction.<br>
<p>
Hope this helps.<br>
<p>
Daniel Crowe<br>
Assistant Professor of Physics<br>
Pacific Union College<br>
dcrowe@puc.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
