<p>
Fred Christiansen wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt; I submit that the parable of Mat 18:23-35 teaches us that probation</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; continues even after forgiveness, that our sins can come back upon our</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; heads and we can lose that justification.  BTW, our sins are not blotted</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; out (Acts 3:19; cf Jer 17:1) until the times of refreshing, which occur</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; at the end of the anti-typical Day of Atonement.</i><br>
<p>
To which Steve Timm responded:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I have heard the idea that your sins come back on you if you fall or</i><br>
<i>&gt; something, but I don't believe it and don't think it can be classified as</i><br>
<i>&gt; SDA theology.  Can God cast our sins so deep into the sea that He can't</i><br>
<i>&gt; retrieve them?  I think so.  Rather, any falling away is a new sin with</i><br>
<i>&gt; corresponding new penalty, but what is forgiven is forgotten.</i><br>
<p>
Steve,<br>
<p>
It might be useful if you supply Bible references.  I remember some of the<br>
passages, but it might be useful to inspect some of them more closely.<br>
<p>
Fred,<br>
<p>
Do you have any other Bible references besides the parable in Matthew 18? <br>
We all know that parables can be pushed too far, as in the case of the<br>
rich man and Lazarus (Luke 16:19-31).  Also, what supporting evidence can<br>
you supply for your assertion that the times of refreshing occur at the<br>
end of the anti-typical Day of Atonement?<br>
<p>
Daniel Crowe<br>
Assistant Professor of Physics<br>
