<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Fact of life/potential for life</title>
<h1>Re: Fact of life/potential for life</h1>
<i>CONNELLE@vaxine.swac.edu</i><br>
<i>Wed, 17 Aug 1994 17:53:17 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#104">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#104">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#104">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#104">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0105.html">Dan Crowe: "Re: Close of probation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0103.html">Harry Salvini: "Re: 1844  (*^&amp;$%^$&amp;$^)"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0031.html">SDA Net: "Fact of life/potential for life"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
-&gt;&gt; One thing that is not in dispute, however, is that once a sperm and ovum<br>
-&gt;&gt; unite, a unique combination of genes is created which has the potential to grow<br>
-&gt;&gt; into a living human being.  I think the debate could sometimes be carried<br>
-&gt;&gt; farther if we were to say:  "all right, the fetus may not be alive, but<br>
-&gt;&gt; it has a unique potential for life.  How shall we protect that potential life?"<br>
-&gt;<br>
-&gt;I think it could be carried even further. Having intercourse may not result <br>
-&gt;in a new life, but the potential exists. Should we discourage contraception to <br>
-&gt;protect this potential for life?<br>
-&gt;<br>
<p>
 An obvious difference is that in the case of the fetus, there is an <br>
 object to be protected, but in the latter example, one is merely <br>
 protecting and abstraction.<br>
 <br>
 Ed Connell                              connelle@swac.edu<br>
 <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
