<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Breath or Blood</title>
<h1>Re: Breath or Blood</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Aug 94 1:41:59 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#112">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#112">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#112">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#112">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0113.html">zerwekh@pellet.if.usp.br: "Heb 6:19"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0111.html">Tony Dyson: "RE: Another hypothetical"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0033.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "Breath or Blood"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0133.html">HectorP2@aol.com: "Re: Breath or Blood"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In-Reply-&gt;To: &lt;2e50d6b8.knapper@knapper.cactus.org&gt;; from "Woody Baker" at Aug 16, 94 10:09 am<br>
<p>
Here I go, running in where angels fear to tread.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Believe it or not, there are now synthetic blood subsitutes.</i><br>
<p>
So what?  There are synthetic lungs as well.  What does that prove?<br>
We can keep you alive (?) while your lungs are being replaced.  You<br>
certainly are not breathing during that multi-hour procedure.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Life is in the Blood, only in the sense that the blood provides</i><br>
<i>&gt; nutrients, and gasses to the cells, and removes waste products.</i><br>
<p>
Here's a news flash for you: the blood that circulates within the<br>
blood vessels of a developing fetus does what you just defined to be<br>
life.  Would you care to draw a consistent conclusion?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I think the way the bible puts it, is once again a cultural artifact</i><br>
<i>&gt; in this sense:  Back then science was an empirical thing.  You let</i><br>
<i>&gt; the blood out of an animal, and it dies.  Therefore the life is in</i><br>
<i>&gt; the blood.  I think that the Lord had to put it that way, so the</i><br>
<i>&gt; people could understand.</i><br>
<p>
Oh, please!  What kind of hermeneutics is this?  You think that God<br>
could not have gotten the point across that life is in the breathing?<br>
You think no one ever drowned back then?  When a drowning victim was<br>
recovered, even with all his blood intact, I am sure those ignorant<br>
people understood that he was dead, and that he died for lack of<br>
breathing.<br>
<p>
Regards,<br>
Dan Blake<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
