<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Sabbath School</title>
<h1>Re: Sabbath School</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Aug 94 10:53:17 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#119">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#119">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#119">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#119">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Carlyle B. Edwards: "Re: Re[2]: requirements for a new pastor"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0118.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: 1844  (*^&amp;$%^$&amp;$^)"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0098.html">AMY HACK: "Sabbath School"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I will share observations from our small church...(not as small as what your's<br>
sounds like though).  First, we ended the pre-lesson study time.  It was poorly<br>
attended and frustrating for those who put the effort in to make it<br>
interesting.  Now we have lesson study time from 9:30 - 10:30.  It seems to be<br>
received ok from all (more or less).<br>
<p>
As for lesson study, we had 4 adult classes, 1 for young adults, 1 for new<br>
believers ("Pastor's class"), and 2 for the older members (we have few middle<br>
aged adults...when their kids reach teen years, they move to other metro area<br>
churches that are the "IN" spots for teens).  The teacher for the young adults<br>
class was unreliable in his arrival time or attendence.  Although he was a very<br>
knowledgeable teacher and an interesting class, his poor attendence led to a<br>
dwindling class attendence and finally it died.  Those who were in the yound<br>
adults class switched to the "pastor's class", which in turn went back to<br>
studying the lesson instead of SDA 27 Fund. Beliefs book.  We had a young<br>
pastor for a year and during that time this class grew to be large and popular.<br>
 He did an excellent job in lesson study time.  After he left, this spring, we<br>
have now tried to split this "pastors class" into a "pastors class" and a<br>
"contemporary issues" class.<br>
<p>
I believe the key to a good SS lesson study class is in the teacher.<br>
 Unfortunately, there are precious few who are skilled in being teachers and<br>
who put the time in to prepare.  Ideally, no SS adult class should ever be more<br>
than about 12 people, ideally 8-10.  Otherwise discussion is stiffled and the<br>
shy people won't speak up.  You'll hear plenty from the vocal people.  But how<br>
do we get more qualified teachers?<br>
<p>
Our successful pastor's class was largely due to his excited enthusiasm that he<br>
brought to the class each week.  Enthusiasm is KEY I believe.  He smiled alot,<br>
asked questions that got you thinking, pushed boundries of our thinking,<br>
bordering on the controversial, yet making a point out of it before the time<br>
was up.<br>
<p>
Being prepared is important, and knowledgeable on teaching techniques.  I'd<br>
like to see more people willing to learn how to teach.  I'd like to see<br>
training classes offered to teach and then good attendence by church members.<br>
 There are many who could learn to teach.  It adds to your self esteem and<br>
benefits all aspects of your life (work, social gatherings, phone<br>
conversations, etc).  Gives the self confidence to project your image more<br>
boldly.<br>
<p>
Meeting the needs of the class members is also KEY.  If topics aren't discussed<br>
in a relavent way, the members at some point may ask why they are coming to SS.<br>
 The topics of our "contemporary issues" class were highly rated as wanting to<br>
discuss them.  So you might try to find a teacher willing to tackle this kind<br>
of class.  He doesn't need to know the answers, let the class dig for<br>
that...but find someone who exudes enthusiasm, intelligence, and a willingness<br>
to lead it.<br>
<p>
Anyway, hopefully this has helped a little bit in what you are trying to<br>
accomplish, no real specific answers but experience from our situation.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
