<title>Aug2_1994: More thoughts on abortion</title>
<h1>More thoughts on abortion</h1>
GEORGE TASKER (<i>taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Aug 1994 11:03:31 +1000 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#110">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#110">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#110">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#110">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0111.html">Tony Dyson: "RE: Another hypothetical"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0109.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "A Peculiar People?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0132.html">CONNELLE@vaxine.swac.edu: "Re: More thoughts on abortion"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I sometimes wonder about the arguments running back and forth pro and anti<br>
abortion.  One point of interest is the one with regard to the viability of <br>
an infant once it has left the mothers womb.  It is assumed by some that <br>
once an infant becomes viable that it can then be regarded as a human being.  <br>
My problem is where do we define the point of viability.<br>
<p>
Strictly speaking a newborn infant is non-viable.  Leave one lying on its <br>
own for a few days and see how long it lives for.  Even ones that are looked <br>
after can die.  I recall hearing about a certain orphanage in England that <br>
had many babies that were cared for very well but they died at very high <br>
percentage rates.  It turned out that apart from being fed and cleaned the <br>
babies were handled very little and died from emotional starvation.<br>
<p>
I would have thought that the point of viability comes when the child is <br>
able to fend for itself which technically means they would be a minimum of <br>
ten years old.  On this basis I view the argument of viability of an infant <br>
as a case for abortion with suspicion.  My twin boys could not even breath <br>
properly without oxygen enrichment for the first few days after they were <br>
born.  They even had to be in humidicribs so be sure of surviving.  We were <br>
told that they had a 95% chance of surviving.  That theoretically meant that <br>
they had a 5% chance of being "non-viable".<br>
<p>
As it was they were non-viable outside the hospital.  So when I stood there <br>
and looked at my babies lying there in their cribs should I have looked at <br>
them as human beings or should I have seen them as packages of flesh and <br>
blood that one day would hopefully become human beings.  I don't believe the <br>
argument of viability will give me a correct answer on this one.<br>
<pre>
-- 
George Tasker                                 taskerg@topaz.cqu.edu.au
                                              taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au
<p>
Blessed is the man that hath nothing to say and cannot be persuaded to say it.
Hezekiah 5:9
</pre>
