<title>Aug2_1994: RE: Another hypothetical</title>
<h1>RE: Another hypothetical</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHAJD@wombat.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Aug 1994 11:24:57 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#111">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#111">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#111">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#111">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0112.html">Dan Blake: "Re: Breath or Blood"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0110.html">GEORGE TASKER: "More thoughts on abortion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Of course the father is a criminal, and should be jailed. Cases like this,<br>
though, are rarely that simple. Even victims of aggravated rape are sometimes<br>
put through hell by the police and the courts - how about someone who not<br>
only had a previous relationship with the alleged attacker, but who <br>
voluntarily granted him entry to her home? And as for church discipline,<br>
all you have to do to escape that is come from the right family and have<br>
the right friends.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Has such a case ever occurred?  If so, how was it eventually decided? What's</i><br>
<i>&gt; the alternative?  Kill the child to "protect" it from its criminal father?</i><br>
<p>
I'm not about to trot out people's personal decisions for others to hash<br>
over, especially those who have never had to deal with anything like this.<br>
It seems that, especially in a debate, people are all too ready to point<br>
fingers and ignore the fact that others are suffering through very real<br>
traumas. "She never should have let him into the house" "It's the fault<br>
of the Australian court system that rape victims are treated that way" <br>
"She didn't scream loud enough" "Maybe it wasn't _really_ rape" "Surely<br>
she could have stopped him if she really wanted to" or whatever.<br>
<p>
What if I was the fiance in this story? Could I expect any more sensitivity<br>
then? Or are we the kind of Christians who stick our upstanding, never-<br>
really-tested morals in people's faces regardless of their personal hurts?<br>
Let's not forget that of all the faceless subscribers to SDAnet, we<br>
know very little about many of their backgrounds or experiences. <br>
<p>
One thing's for sure, if I _was_ the fiance in this story, Cori has<br>
correctly identified the outcome. I doubt whether my Christianity is <br>
sufficient to hold me back. (Of course, assault is much more easy to<br>
prove in court than rape, so then it would be _me_ behind bars.)<br>
<p>
	Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
