In-Reply-&gt;To: &lt;16AUG94.11363620.0095.MUSIC@UTMARTN&gt;<br>
<p>
Amy:<br>
	I am sorry about the loss in your family. And thanks for spelling <br>
out so clearly and short the stages that we go through when arriving to a <br>
new church.<br>
	Now, I have seen in my life how many new happy starts have become <br>
a mess afterward. I now that we are not supouse to make every body happy <br>
because that will be avoiding being stable, direct and honest. But, I <br>
care about the happyness of everybody in my church. I also care about the <br>
spiritual life of each member. And many times, when addressing those <br>
issues, relationships becomes sticky and rough. How can we extend the <br>
honeymoon phase longer. Or how can we move to a more realistic but glad <br>
phases?<br>
	Something else. I know that in counseling we are not supouse to <br>
give to much advise. Because that will be de direct counseling and indirect <br>
counseling will develop more independence and stronger will in the <br>
client. But pastors are expected to say something, to act, to take <br>
control of the situation and lead. How can we better look for a middle road?<br>
<p>
Amy, is good to have somebody to discuss this issues with.<br>
<p>
Dennis Hidalgo<br>
Pastor-<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
