<title>Aug2_1994: Re: A Peculiar People?</title>
<h1>Re: A Peculiar People?</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 19 Aug 1994 07:05:03 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#129">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#129">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#129">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#129">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0130.html">AMY HACK: "Re[2]: Sabbath School"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0128.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Is abortion sin?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0109.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "A Peculiar People?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0153.html">John Watkins: "Re: A Peculiar People?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Bill Sands wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; IF Ellen White is merely an anachronism of the 19th century,</i><br>
<i>&gt; and IF the 2300 days did not end in 1844,</i><br>
<i>&gt; what reason is there for a denomination called the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Seventh-day Adventist Church?</i><br>
<p>
One might say that the Roman Catholic Church brought us Martin Luther,<br>
having been one of its priests, and thus, indirectly, the Protestant<br>
reformation.  Does that fact argue for the validity of Roman Catholicism?<br>
<p>
I'd suspect that the Jehovah's Witnesses prediction of the Second Coming of<br>
Christ in 1914 caused a number of Christians (and maybe a few<br>
non-Christians) to read their Bibles, but that beneficial side effect does<br>
not vindicate the false prophecy.  One could ask, rhetorically, "what<br>
happened in 1914".  A lot of things happened, obviously.  But what's<br>
important is that what was PREDICTED to occur that year didn't.  Yes, they<br>
promptly came up with what "really happened", including a re-interpretation<br>
that Jesus' "return to earth" in 1914 was not PHYSICAL after all, but merely<br>
"spiritual".  IOW, rather than admitting their error, they attempted to<br>
explain their way out of it.  Would you be so charitable with them as you<br>
seem to be with Miller?<br>
<p>
First of all, the SDA church has distinctive doctrines other than a belief<br>
in 1844.  If it was a movement that God chose to bring about, then He was<br>
not limited to using a man who misled his followers into giving away their<br>
possessions, quitting their jobs, etc. in the vain hope of a literal Second<br>
Coming in 1844.  EGW could presumably have had her visions without having<br>
associated with Miller.  The fact that God managed to use him is no more a<br>
vindication of him than Judas' instrumental role in bringing about Jesus'<br>
arrest and  crucifixion, and thus our salvation, somehow absolves him of his<br>
guilt for betraying Christ.<br>
<p>
 /--------------+------------------------------------\<br>
<i> |              |  Internet: davesparks@delphi.com   |</i><br>
<i> | Dave Sparks  |  Fidonet:  Dave Sparks @ 1:207/212 |</i><br>
<i> |              |  BBS:      (909) 353-9821 - 14.4K  |</i><br>
 \--------------+------------------------------------/<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
