<title>Aug2_1994: Re: More thoughts on abortion</title>
<h1>Re: More thoughts on abortion</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Sat, 20 Aug 1994 07:03:44 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#148">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#148">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#148">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#148">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0149.html">GEORGE TASKER: "Nature of Christ?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0147.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Re[2]: Sabbath School"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0110.html">GEORGE TASKER: "More thoughts on abortion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;  I believe that it is considered a crime to destroy a fertilized egg </i><br>
<i>&gt;  of a California Condor or other endangered species.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<i>&gt;  No, human's are not on the endangered species list, but... :-)</i><br>
<p>
And I'll bet that if there was an organization that got PAID to destroy<br>
condor eggs, the political left and even the "religious left" would picket,<br>
march, protest, hand out leaflets on the sidewalk, block access, and engage<br>
in various other acts of civil disobedience in response.  Those who have<br>
done so to save spotted owls, whales, and harp seals have not been nearly as<br>
vilified as pro-life activists have been, even those whose "crime" was<br>
praying on a public sidewalk in violation of an injunction.<br>
<p>
As for man not being an endangered species, it depends on how you look at<br>
it.  With declining birth rates, many countries are wondering how a<br>
declining number of younger, working people can support a growing number of<br>
older, retiring people.  As for this country, I understand that the only<br>
reason the population continues to grow is due to immigration and longer<br>
lifespans.<br>
