<title>Aug2_1994: Re: A Peculiar People?</title>
<h1>Re: A Peculiar People?</h1>
John Watkins (<i>jwatkins@scndprsn.firstperson.com</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 20 Aug 1994 19:03:59 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#153">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#153">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#153">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#153">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0154.html">Joseph Miceli: "Re: Breath of Life/Living Being"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0152.html">Benjamin Siyowi Mapani: "re: missionary questionaire"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0109.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "A Peculiar People?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Re: A Peculiar People?<br>
<p>
A while back (August 17) Bill Sands asked:<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>	&gt; IF Ellen White is merely an anachronism of the 19th century,</i><br>
<i>	&gt; and IF the 2300 days did not end in 1844,</i><br>
<i>	&gt; what reason is there for a denomination called the</i><br>
<i>	&gt; Seventh-day Adventist Church?</i><br>
<p>
<i>	&gt; IF there is no special significance to the heavenly sanctuary</i><br>
<i>	&gt; with regard to Daniel 8:14, why do we bother to perpetuate</i><br>
<i>	&gt; our church?</i><br>
<p>
<i>	&gt; If there are no special or unique messages or beliefs</i><br>
<i>	&gt; why should we continue? Why not disband and drop it all</i><br>
<i>	&gt; as a GREAT DISAPPOINTMENT?</i><br>
<p>
<i>	&gt; Bill Sands, Jr.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
First, I don't believe EGW was merely an anachronism.  Next topic....<br>
<p>
The reason I am an SDA today is definitely not because of what may or may <br>
not have happened in Oct. 1844.   The composite picture that the SDA package<br>
of beliefs portray of God is what keeps me a member of this church despite<br>
the fact I have definite reservations about the traditional Adventist teaching<br>
on the sanctuary.  <br>
<p>
Adventist doctrines show me a God who: <br>
- ultimately believes in freedom of choice for His creatures <br>
- cares about the multi-dimensional aspects of His creatures <br>
- insightfully provided a special time for us to strengthen our relationships <br>
  with Him and each other <br>
- shows incredible wisdom, patience, love and the ultimate in self-sacrifice <br>
  for the universe in His dealing with the sin problem <br>
- hates the notion of losing any one and will *not* inflict an eternity of <br>
  pain on those who choose against accepting His gracious overtures to us<br>
- wants to reason with us and draw us towards Him because He has earned our<br>
  trust, respect and our desire to emulate Him<br>
<p>
I find no other church that presents such a package and is Biblically based<br>
to the extent that I find the SDA church.  Thus, I remain a member here.<br>
<p>
To tell you the truth, Bill, I've never personally met anyone who became an<br>
Adventist because s/he was attracted by the sanctuary doctrine.  Most SDAs<br>
I know joined for other reasons, don't really understand or can rationally<br>
explain this doctrine to a non-SDA, and don't believe it affects the way we<br>
live our lives if Christ moved into the most holy place of the sanctuary in<br>
1844 vs. went directly into it at His ascension.  I count myself among them<br>
and I am constantly baffled when I hear it stated that without the sanctuary<br>
doctrine, Adventism makes no contribution to theology.  (I don't know if you <br>
are saying this.)  Personally, I don't really care if we have no unique <br>
doctrines to contribute.  In fact I would think since we claim to be <br>
theologically in synch. with Adam and Eve, Moses, Christ, Paul, and John the <br>
Revelator, we should have very little new theology to add.  Our contribution <br>
should be an emphasis on the message the Bible shows God trying to communicate <br>
to the human race since the creation.  We should continue as a denomination <br>
because new or old, unique or ubiquitous, our goal is to present the gospel <br>
as we see it expressed in the Bible.  If there happens to be someone else with <br>
the same message we have, fantastic!  (If there is another group with our same<br>
teachings except for the sanctuary, I'd like to know who they are.)  Our focus <br>
is a continual search for truth and a desire to be inwardly changed to live it.<br>
<p>
<p>
jw<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
