<title>Aug2_1994: Re: Abortion &amp; Contraception</title>
<h1>Re: Abortion &amp; Contraception</h1>
Raylene Dyson (<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 23 Aug 1994 12:58:12 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#195">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#195">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#195">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#195">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0196.html">Carlyle B. Edwards: "Dupage County/Kane County"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0194.html">Benjamin Siyowi Mapani: "does the flesh and blood have an effect..."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0078.html">Ted Barker: "Abortion &amp; Contraception"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
More from abortion....<br>
<p>
Considering firstly - if you don't want children, avoid sex. Well, I did read<br>
before I got married that a couple getting married should be prepared for<br>
children even if not planning them. I can't say I would have been pleased to<br>
have fallen pregnant in any of the time we've been married so far. And I<br>
get the impression that taking such drastic action to avoid children while<br>
married would not be beneficial, and is certainly not biblical.<br>
<p>
But lets take it further. Not a lot has been said about contraception<br>
really.<br>
<p>
It seems we as SDAs are happy to use contraception to better plan our<br>
families. Is this true? We generally don't like to consider abortion because <br>
we value life. This value of life extends to other arenas.<br>
<p>
Do you think it is OK for an SDA to use contraception to avoid having<br>
children altogether?<br>
<p>
What _kind_ of contraception? <br>
<p>
IUDs act to expell fertilized eggs from the<br>
body. A fertilized egg is the beginning of somebody. Is this like abortion?<br>
Is it OK for an SDA to use this method of contraception? _Do_ SDAs use this<br>
method of contraception?<br>
<p>
The IUD can't be too different from this new "abortion drug" RU235 (?) being<br>
trialled can it?<br>
<p>
The "morning after" pill is taken after the egg is fertilized. Could this be<br>
an unfavourable thing for an SDA?<br>
<p>
Do SDAs consider carefully the _kinds_ of contraceptives - not just their<br>
effectiveness but also their "humanitarian" aspects?<br>
<p>
Comments?<br>
Raylene<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
