<title>Aug1_1994: RE: All scripture...</title>
<h1>RE: All scripture...</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHAJD@wombat.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 10 Aug 1994 10:34:02 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#216">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#216">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#216">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#216">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0217.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Requirements for a new pastor"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0215.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Question about "SDA Reform Movement"?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; That depends on whether one chooses to consider the New Testament as</i><br>
<i>&gt; "scripture", or not.  One could also apply the same logic to many references</i><br>
<i>&gt; in Psalms to the "word of God".  Back then, even the Old Testament was</i><br>
<i>&gt; incomplete.  I interpret Paul's words to mean that whatever "ALL SCRIPTURE"</i><br>
<i>&gt; consists of, in any given generation, is what Paul ultimately had reference</i><br>
<i>&gt; to.  The question is, has God added to "scripture" since the first century</i><br>
<i>&gt; AD?  My opinion is "NO".</i><br>
<p>
But at least you do recognize the fact that "scripture" is not used by Paul<br>
to refer to a static body of written revelation. Sure, you can take the<br>
stance that it is God, rather than Paul, who wrote the letter to Timothy,<br>
and that God himself _was_ referring to what we know as the Bible. But I think <br>
this method of exegesis runs against what the New Testament writers had to say <br>
on the matter. (Holy Spirit breathed, clay pots, etc. etc.)<br>
<p>
As for applying the same logic to the Psalms, indeed I do just that. Time and <br>
time again in the Bible we see writers referring to what they know as the<br>
scriptures. What David was thinking of and what Paul was thinking of were two<br>
different literal collections of work, although as you say they were both<br>
referring to the same general concept, that being whatever ALL SCRIPTURE<br>
consists of in any given generation.<br>
<p>
The question is, would either David or Paul have been happy with the notion <br>
that what they were writing would _become_ scripture? This question probably <br>
cannot be answered satisfactorily. But I would hazard a guess that neither of<br>
them would have expected their work to be included the way it was.<br>
<p>
What I find interesting is that when Paul said what he said to Timothy, he<br>
made the statement that _what_he_knew_as_scripture_ was both necessary  _and_<br>
_sufficient_ for the Christian. (Well, that's how you interpreted the passage,<br>
right?) Nowadays we say the same thing, except that we have added a whole lot<br>
more to the scripture of Paul's time. Considering the fact that Peter and Paul<br>
tended to disagree on certain things, I wonder how each would have felt about<br>
them both being included in scripture?<br>
<p>
Do I advocate adding any modern prophets' work to the scripture?<br>
By no means! :-)  However there are more similarities here than some would<br>
care to admit. <br>
<p>
In conclusion, the bottom line to me is that if the Law, the Writings and<br>
the Prophets were enough for Paul, and to that we have already added the<br>
gospels, apostolic writings and so on, then why alienate ourselves from the<br>
rest of the Christian world by acting as if we have an expanded canon.<br>
<p>
	Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
