<title>Aug1_1994: Re: Requirements for a new pastor</title>
<h1>Re: Requirements for a new pastor</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Aug 1994 17:35:10 -0700 (MST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#217">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#217">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#217">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#217">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0218.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "Who is Eating What?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0216.html">Tony Dyson: "RE: All scripture..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
{With apologies to T.J. Mostert, pres, Pacific Union Conf, for "stealing" some<br>
of his ideas; but, hey!, he admits he "stole" ideas from R.A. Clifton.}<br>
<p>
The First Jerusalem SDA Church needed a new pastor and so they formed a<br>
search committee.  After much investigation and not a little expense,<br>
they presented their report to the church board.<br>
<p>
1)  Re: Pastor Elijah:<br>
    Pro: Zealous for God; revivalist.<br>
    Con: Confrontational with non-SDAs; over zealous; his revivals focus too<br>
	much on "reform"; it is alleged he suffered from depression at one<br>
	time; we suspect the praise from his members is overdone, meaning<br>
	that they'd like to get rid of him.<br>
    Conclusion:  Not recommended.<br>
<p>
2)  Re: Pastor Elisha:<br>
    Pro: Has helped set up church schools; travels to visit members.<br>
    Con: Seems he had the nerve to rebuke a group of children over some<br>
	perceived problem; parents are concerned that self-image of children<br>
	has been bruised and that they'll turn away from the church.<br>
    Conclusion:  Not recommended.<br>
<p>
3)  Re: Pastor Paul:<br>
    Pro: Good rapport with ethnic groups; evangelism-oriented, Seminary PhD.<br>
    Con: Away from the pulpit too much .. evidently does not understand that<br>
	a pastor's place is in the pulpit; has had a brush or two with gov't<br>
	authorities and ended up in jail .. this could seriously damage<br>
	our image in the community.<br>
    Conclusion:  Not recommended.<br>
<p>
4)  Re: Pastor Peter:<br>
    Pro: 3,000 baptized after one series of meetings.<br>
    Con: Some members say he never got around to visiting them; lots of<br>
	baptisms will mean an expensive church building program, which our<br>
	members are not prepared to support; sometimes hasty of speech and<br>
	decision making.<br>
    Conclusion:  Not recommended.<br>
<p>
5)  Re: Pastor Nehemiah:<br>
    Pro: Successfully organized major church rebuilding program.<br>
    Con: Far too confrontational with members over alleged Sabbath breaking,<br>
	marrying out of the church, etc.<br>
    Conclusion:  Not recommended.<br>
<p>
6)  Re: Pastor Nathan:<br>
    Pro: Friends with national, political leaders.<br>
    Con: Rebuked a church member for alleged morals problem; too "down home".<br>
    Conclusion:  Not recommended.<br>
<p>
7)  Re: Pastor Moses:<br>
    Pro: Degrees in several disciplines, good leadership skills both before<br>
	and after he became a pastor; can preach w/o notes.<br>
    Con: At 80+, far too old; not eloquent, hard to listen to when speaking.<br>
    Conclusion:  Not recommended.<br>
<p>
8)  Re: Pastor Jean Baptiste:<br>
    Pro: Revivalist, gets baptisms.<br>
    Con: His messages focus too much on repentance of Jesus soon coming;<br>
	needs to focus on love, grace, and relationships.<br>
    Conclusion:  Not recommended.<br>
<p>
8)  Re: Pastor Tinkling Cymbal:<br>
    Pro: Eloquent, young; members feel real comfortable with his sermons.<br>
    Con: None that we can think of.<br>
    Conclusion:  Ask the conference to extend an urgent call to him ASAP.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen ("Canajun, eh?" from Ontario)  Email: fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com
Disclaimer: I do not speak for Motorola Computer Group       Fax: 602-438-3836
"For the transgression of a land many are the princes thereof: but by a man of
 understanding and knowledge the state thereof shall be prolonged." Prov 28:2
</pre>
