<title>Aug1_1994: Requirements for a new pastor</title>
<h1>Requirements for a new pastor</h1>
Harvey Steck (<i>stech@eskimo.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Aug 1994 17:28:07 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#199">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#199">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#199">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#199">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0200.html">Harvey Steck: "(no subject)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0198.html">Harvey Steck: "Re: Pastors &amp; Purgatory"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0213.html">94POLLOK@cua.edu: "Re: Requirements for a new pastor"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tonight the church board of Elmhurst meets to determine the qualities<br>
we would like to have in our next pastor.  This is the list that I'm <br>
taking to the meeting, I will post a summary of what we decide after the meeting.<br>
<p>
<p>
Qualities desirable in a new pastor:                                       <br>
                                                                           <br>
Good people skills--&gt; ability to listen to people and convey               <br>
to them that he is concerned about their problems.  Training in            <br>
conflict resolution preferred.                                             <br>
                                                                           <br>
Good administrator--&gt; facilitates meetings well, sees problems and         <br>
helps them get fixed.                                                      <br>
                                                                           <br>
Gets along good with young people OR knows how to equip other people       <br>
in the church with that skill.                                             <br>
                                                                           <br>
Ability to recognize and continue the role of Elmhurst as a safe place     <br>
for those in relationship problems.                                        <br>
                                                                           <br>
Not afraid to try new techniques as part of overall vision for the future. <br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
