<title>Aug1_1994: Re: Who is Eating What?</title>
<h1>Re: Who is Eating What?</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 10 Aug 1994 22:42:55 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#242">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#242">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#242">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#242">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0243.html">JAYNE ROP: "Re[2]: requirements for a new pastor"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0241.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0218.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "Who is Eating What?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Bill Sands, Jr. wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The ongoing discussion about who is eating what could benefit by asking:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Who ever said that mushrooms were okay to eat?</i><br>
<p>
Or manufactured soy bean products, for that matter. &lt;g&gt; The bottom line is<br>
a question about the "default case" in scripture.  Are things NOT explicitly<br>
mentioned in Scripture acceptable or unacceptable, by default?  One side<br>
might ask, "Where does the Bible AUTHORIZE that?" while the other side<br>
could ask "Where does the Bible FORBID it"?<br>
<p>
A good example of that line of reasoning is the spectrum of opinion over<br>
music in the church.  The Church of Christ avoids instrumental music in<br>
church because there is no EXPLICIT New Testament "precedent" for it.  On the<br>
other extreme, some churches allow and even encourage the performance of<br>
"heavy metal music" in the church, ostensibly for purposes of evangelism<br>
and/or entertainment.<br>
<p>
To that could be added just about every technological innovation since the<br>
first century, including electric lights, public address systems, and<br>
clothing made from synthetic fibers.  In the continuum from liberty to<br>
legalism, absent any clear scriptural mandate, I tend to prefer the<br>
"liberty" side, applied with God-given common sense.<br>
<p>
On what basis would/should mushrooms be banned?  Or should they?  One might<br>
consider the origins of penicillin before answering, since it was derived<br>
from a FUNGUS as well.  You sure do ask some thought-provoking questions,<br>
Bill!<br>
<p>
 /--------------+------------------------------------\<br>
<i> |              |  Internet: davesparks@delphi.com   |</i><br>
<i> | Dave Sparks  |  Fidonet:  Dave Sparks @ 1:207/212 |</i><br>
<i> |              |  BBS:      (909) 353-9821 - 14.4K  |</i><br>
 \--------------+------------------------------------/<br>
