<title>Aug1_1994: Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori</title>
<h1>Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 10 Aug 1994 21:11:13 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#241">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#241">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#241">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#241">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0242.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Who is Eating What?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0240.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: The Bible and (Which) Bible Only???"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
George Tasker wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; However even with today's knowledge we still get a large amount of micro-</i><br>
<i>&gt; biological contamination if a recent TV program I saw is to be believed.</i><br>
<p>
This is a case of the "exception proving the rule", though.  If it's high<br>
today, DESPITE modern techniques, think what the "contamination" was back in<br>
the relative primitive conditions right after the flood when God first<br>
gave man meat to eat.  God obviously knew what the conditions were then, and<br>
what they would be today, and took them into account before saying what He<br>
did.  IOW, we at least KNOW HOW to make food safer today, regardless of how<br>
consistently those concepts are applied.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It seems that many preparers of such food hold the attitude, out of sight </i><br>
<i>&gt; out of mind.  Of course to make things more interesting they stored their </i><br>
<i>&gt; food items in places that made the environment for bacterial growth highly</i><br>
<i>&gt; favorable.  Warm, moist and behind glass.</i><br>
<p>
This is, of course, an argument for proper preparation and storage.  It's<br>
like showing pictures of fatal car wrecks.  One can either respond to them<br>
by learning how to drive more safely, or else give up his/her automobile<br>
altogether. I'll opt for the former.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; We still take our chances every bit as much now as back in those days.</i><br>
<p>
That being the case, then the "grounds" for God's decision in Genesis 9 are<br>
every bit as valid (or invalid) as they were when He first communicated it<br>
to Noah and his descendants.  You're right -- modern technology is not a<br>
substitute for common sense.  Hopefully no one is suggesting it is.  But to<br>
a person who HAS and USES his common sense, technology can be a useful tool.<br>
<p>
My point being, when God gives me a gift, I'll gladly "take my chances" on<br>
His wisdom. <br>
<p>
