<title>Aug1_1994: Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori</title>
<h1>Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 09 Aug 1994 10:41:58 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#210">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#210">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#210">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#210">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0211.html">Woody Baker: "Re: WE NEED YOUR VOICE (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0209.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: Networking stuff"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave brings up an interesting question, that we of course can't know<br>
the answer to.  Was there a need for plants to have chemical defenses in<br>
Eden?  Presumably the entire creation was vegetarian.  Death had not<br>
happened before the fall, so it is likely that animals did not kill<br>
other animals. (open can of worms here..).  Did insects kill plants like<br>
they do now?  Once again I think the answer would be no.  If so, then<br>
why would a plant need a chemical defense as powerful as nicotine?  More<br>
to the point, would the production of nicotine be a micro evolutionary<br>
trait, or a created trait?  (worms starting to crawl out of can).  Why<br>
would cats have the carnivorous dentation that the have?<br>
<p>
Now these questions are not essential to salvation, they are more on<br>
the order of "how many angels can dance on the head of a pin", but<br>
they are interesting never the less.<br>
<p>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
