<title>Aug1_1994: Re: Networking stuff</title>
<h1>Re: Networking stuff</h1>
Malcolm Butler (<i>malb@boojum.ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Aug 94 16:45:26 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#209">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#209">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#209">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#209">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0210.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0208.html">MELDOUGLASS@delphi.com: "ASI Convention in Dallas"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; After a while on the Compuserve Internet forum, I have come to the conclusion</i><br>
<i>&gt; that it is more likely that the Compuserve management will deliver on enough </i><br>
<i>&gt; of their Internet access promises than it is that we will change Ralph</i><br>
<i>&gt; Blodgett's mind about anything.  The vast majority of the SDA's Online </i><br>
<i>&gt; people who don't have Internet access now will be able to access the </i><br>
<i>&gt; Usenet News on Compuserve within a month or so, it appears.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; Not clear yet whether this will be a premium service or not. I will investigate</i><br>
<i>&gt; that and other details.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Such as will they be getting all the alt.* groups or only the big<br>
seven?  It would be unfortunate if we created an alt group and they<br>
didn't carry it.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I will be presenting a proposal to the SDAnet board for the relationship </i><br>
<i>&gt; of sdanet and the new proposed newsgroup alt.religion.sda.  We want to </i><br>
<i>&gt; build a consensus within this community before proposing the group in</i><br>
<i>&gt; the alt.config section.  If there is anyone out there in SDAnet-land who </i><br>
<i>&gt; has news administration privileges on a node that carries the alt groups,</i><br>
<i>&gt; and knows how to gateway a mailing list to a newsgroup and vice versa,</i><br>
<i>&gt; please let me know.  In none of my existing accounts do I have any </i><br>
<i>&gt; privilege to create such a group.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
I may be able to help here.  My home machine, bellman.apana.org.au, is<br>
Usenet-connected.  It isn't Internet connected, as it uses a dial-up<br>
UUCP link, but that shouldn't be the main barrier.  The biggest likely<br>
problem is that it is connected via a public access network that is<br>
run on a fairly amateur basis, so the propagation of a newgroup<br>
message from my site may not be very good.<br>
<p>
Actually, the way I read the various FAQs, anyone with posting<br>
privileges should be able to create a newsgroup.  You just post an<br>
appropriate message to the 'control' newsgroup.  Of course, being a<br>
news admin yourself probably helps.  Failing that, if your local news<br>
admin doesn't want to carry the group, it won't get very far.<br>
<p>
Have the various SDA institutions connected to the net refused to<br>
create such a group, or are you just assuming they wouldn't want to<br>
because they are supporting compuserve, or do they not get alt.*<br>
groups?  You've managed to get a domain name (sdanet.org), I would<br>
have thought it was _easier_ to create a newsgroup.<br>
<p>
Regarding the naming of the group.  I grepped my .newsrc for<br>
alt.religion and this is what turned up:<br>
<p>
alt.religion.buddhism.tibetan<br>
alt.religion.gnostic<br>
alt.religion.mormon <br>
alt.religion.zoroastrianism<br>
alt.religion.christian<br>
alt.religion.eckankar <br>
alt.religion.islam<br>
alt.religion.monica<br>
alt.religion.sabaean<br>
alt.religion.santaism<br>
alt.religion.sexuality<br>
alt.religion.computers<br>
alt.religion.adm3a<br>
alt.religion.kibology<br>
alt.religion.all-worlds<br>
alt.religion.emacs<br>
alt.religion.scientology<br>
<p>
There seems to be nearly as many 'joke' groups in here as serious<br>
ones.  Have you considered positioning the group under<br>
alt.religion.christian, or are you happy having it on the same<br>
hierarchical level as this and all the others?<br>
<p>
It is technically possible for me to do this, as my home machine,<br>
<p>
<p>
Finally, mail-news gateways.  I've done this on bellman for a mailing<br>
list which I wanted to read locally using my newsreading software and<br>
it worked fine.  I did it by setting up a mail alias which mungs the<br>
headers a bit and calls inews, which posts the article.  As far as I<br>
know, this is basically how it is normally done, though perhaps the<br>
munging script is usually more foolproof.  <br>
<p>
I made it work the other way by making the group moderated and setting<br>
the forwarding address for the moderator to the list address, which is<br>
a fairly cheap and nasty way to do it, but since the group only<br>
existed at one site, it worked OK.<br>
<p>
My impression is it should be possible to operate a gateway without<br>
root privileges, it just makes it easier if you have them.  <br>
<p>
While in theory I could operate a gateway for you, this wouldn't be a<br>
good idea because bellman has a very slow turn-around time due to the<br>
UUCP link, and my provider probably wouldn't be too happy with all<br>
that traffic going twice across our part of the Net.  I'm more than<br>
happy to help find out technical details for you, though.<br>
<p>
<p>
best regards,<br>
<p>
Malcolm  (malb@bellman.apana.org.au)<br>
<pre>
--
Switched Networks Research Centre,               malb@ee.uts.edu.au
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia            +61 2 330 2344
</pre>
