<title>Aug1_1994: Abortion and all that</title>
<h1>Abortion and all that</h1>
GEORGE TASKER (<i>taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Aug 1994 10:38:34 +1000 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#270">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#270">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#270">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#270">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0271.html">Tony Dyson: "Where the Spirit leads"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0269.html">Dan Crowe: "Re: 1844 Error? Not in my Bible!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Now that abortion has come up as a topic I wish to talk about the following<br>
hypothetical and get your thoughts on it.<br>
<p>
It has been stated that about 50% of a childs behavioural characteristics<br>
are gained genetically through the parents.  It also appears that these <br>
characteristics stay with them throughout their life.  This suggests then <br>
that if a child comes from a home where the father/mother is alcoholic the <br>
chances are high that the child will also have a weakness towards alcohol <br>
even if they never touch the stuff their whole life.<br>
<p>
Let us now consider the case of the poor lady who falls pregnant to a <br>
rapist.  On the basis of the above if the baby is a boy then that boy will <br>
possibly have the same tendency as the father.  So this boy reaches teen <br>
years or more and rapes another girl himself.  Which then is the greater <br>
sin?  Is it to have an abortion in the first place thereby preventing this <br>
problem or should the pregnancy be allowed to go ahead in the full knowledge <br>
that coming from a rapist that this is going to significantly increase the <br>
chances that the person will grow up and commit the same crime as his sire?<br>
<p>
My belief is that abortion is worth while in the case of rape or the <br>
mother's health is in danger.<br>
<p>
My own boys were brought out six weeks early because of the problem with my <br>
wife's health so in a sense it was an abortion if you please but at least I <br>
have two boys now who turn one year old on August nineteen.  We were <br>
fortunate enough to have the best of both worlds, an abortion(ceasarian) and <br>
two wonderful boys.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
George Tasker                                 taskerg@topaz.cqu.edu.au
                                              taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au
<p>
Blessed is the man that hath nothing to say and cannot be persuaded to say it.
Hezekiah 5:9
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
