<title>Aug1_1994: RE: The Bible and (Which) Bible Only???</title>
<h1>RE: The Bible and (Which) Bible Only???</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Aug 94 15:41:57 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#268">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#268">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#268">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#268">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0269.html">Dan Crowe: "Re: 1844 Error? Not in my Bible!"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0267.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "The Wheeled Throne of God"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It most definitely does qualify Dan.<br>
<p>
This is the question being discussed, how much and at<br>
what time is "all scripture" ALL scripture?  Especially if<br>
some manuscripts say something and others say<br>
another.<br>
<p>
Further, the knowledge we know now was not there<br>
when the writer(s) of 2 Sam/1 Corinthians disagreed<br>
on the "who done it" and the other disagreeing points<br>
in that story (ie. how many = 800,000/1,100,000;<br>
500,000/400,000) to name one.  Is every single word<br>
inspired?  What's going on?  Is "God breathing" differing<br>
things out of opposite sides of His mouth?<br>
<p>
Furthermore, *who* is the SDA commentary if we're a<br>
"The Bible and the Bible only" people?  Get with it folks.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
