<title>Aug1_1994: Where the Spirit leads</title>
<h1>Where the Spirit leads</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHAJD@wombat.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Aug 1994 11:35:20 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#271">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#271">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#271">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#271">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0272.html">Tony Dyson: "RE: Abortion"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0270.html">GEORGE TASKER: "Abortion and all that"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Has it reached the point where each church gets to</i><br>
<i>&gt; choose who they want as a pastor???</i><br>
<i>&gt; I don't understand, but I thought pastors serve where</i><br>
<i>&gt; the Spirit leads them, not where they are wanted. Please,</i><br>
<i>&gt; somebody, enlighten me!</i><br>
<p>
We _hope_ that the Spirit will lead a pastor to somewhere they<br>
are wanted, or at least to somewhere where they can be <br>
effective. The idea of a local church based "search committee"<br>
is no less an opportunity for the Spirit to lead than any other<br>
kind of God-fearing committee.<br>
<p>
If the Spirit can only lead through mystic means or through<br>
institutions, than perhaps your requests for enlightenment<br>
would be better saved for prayer meetings?? :-)<br>
<p>
	Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
