<title>Aug1_1994: The Wheeled Throne of God</title>
<h1>The Wheeled Throne of God</h1>
Bill Sands Jr. (<i>sands@andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Aug 1994 18:14:11 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#267">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#267">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#267">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#267">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0268.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: The Bible and (Which) Bible Only???"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0266.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "The Angels' Gold Card!!!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Clay was unaware that there are some opinions around that say that<br>
God's throne is mobile and moves from Holy Place to Most Holy Place.<br>
The idea originates in Daniel, and Ellen White describes this I belieive<br>
in Early Writings in the chapter on the 2300 days.<br>
<p>
It is obviously a metaphor because we are discussing a spiritual<br>
concept in a material or physical 3 dimensional way.<br>
<p>
We know so little about the earthly or heavenly sanctuaries<br>
that we must be careful when we express the idea that it is<br>
simply not possible. Spiritual things are spiritually understood.<br>
<p>
Yes, Clay, I believe that the throne of God is mobile. I do find<br>
a bit of a problem with the Bible texts which speak of God as<br>
a being which doesnot cast a shadow...a shadow of turning<br>
as one text says.<br>
<p>
Bill Sands, Jr.<br>
sands@andrews.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0268.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: The Bible and (Which) Bible Only???"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0266.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "The Angels' Gold Card!!!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
