On Thu, 11 Aug 1994, Clay Spinuzzi wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt; &gt; I have been wondering at what stage of fetal development is abortion sin?</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; &gt; Do we have a theological basis for our stand?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The question is when the fetus becomes a human being. If you check</i><br>
<i>&gt; out discussions on newsgroups such as talk.abortion, most abortion</i><br>
<i>&gt; proponents believe that the fetus does not become a person until it</i><br>
<i>&gt; has brainwaves approaching the complexity of (born) human brainwaves.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The problem with this approach is that we as Christians realize that</i><br>
<i>&gt; a person is not merely a mind. We also have a spirit. We can assume</i><br>
<i>&gt; that when the spirit enters the body, the fetus becomes a person,</i><br>
<i>&gt; theologically speaking.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; When does the spirit enter the body? Or is it there at the moment the</i><br>
<i>&gt; egg is fertilized? I don't think there's any way to tell. In the</i><br>
<i>&gt; absence of any evidence one way or the other, I choose to err on the</i><br>
<i>&gt; side of caution and oppose abortion in all instances.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; However, I can't condemn others as evil for thinking that the fetus </i><br>
<i>&gt; becomes a person at a much later date. Actually, I hope they're right.</i><br>
<p>
Clay, I have a question. Would the "spirit" you refer to be a "soul?" Or <br>
is it breath?<br>
