<title>Aug1_1994: Re: The Reformed SDA church.</title>
<h1>Re: The Reformed SDA church.</h1>
Joilo Barbosa (<i>U08837@uicvm.uic.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Aug 94 21:04:08 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#273">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#273">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#273">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#273">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0274.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: Re:"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0272.html">Tony Dyson: "RE: Abortion"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0249.html">Benjamin Siyowi Mapani: "The Reformed SDA church."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Thu, 11 Aug 1994 14:58:12 +1000 Benjamin Siyowi Mapani said:<br>
<i>&gt;Fred asked whether the people I termed "The SDA reform" are the</i><br>
<i>&gt;same as the "Reformed Seventh-Day Adventist Church".</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;The answer is yes, may be I should have written it as it is</i><br>
<i>&gt;commonly written. Sorry for misleading you!</i><br>
<i>&gt;Have a good day.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Ben</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
That is not true.  I grew up in the SDA Reform Movement.  I was impressed by th<br>
e accurate description Ben gave of what the Reform Movement represents, but I n<br>
ever heard Reformed SDA Church as a descriptive term for the SDA Reform Movemen<br>
t.<br>
<p>
Just in case there is still some interest in finding out about the Reform Movem<br>
ent, I can share some of what I know abou them.<br>
<p>
It started in Europe in 1914, during WWI, when the GC lost communication with t<br>
he European Division.  The president of the Division, in a miscalculated decisi<br>
on, ordered the brethren to bear arms.  A small group, unhappy about the decisi<br>
on separated from the church and hence the Reform Movement was born.  When the<br>
communication channels were open again, there were some efforts made to concili<br>
ate the differences, but by then, apparently it was too late.  Other issues wer<br>
e introduced such as diet, dress codes, 1888, and a justification of the existe<br>
nce of the SDA Reform Movement by saying that it represented the fourth angel o<br>
f Revelation.<br>
<p>
Over the years the movement grew considerably in certain parts of the world, pa<br>
rticularly in South America, where most of the members of the church are locate<br>
d today.  In 1951, there was a schism in the movement, due to a power struggle<br>
for the presidency.  Since then there were two main SDA Reform Movement churche<br>
s, both claiming to be the original 1914 movement and accusing the other of bei<br>
ng the 1951 "apostate" offshoot.  One group, kept most of the members in Europe<br>
, particularly Germany, while the other kept mainly the members from South Amer<br>
ica, especially Brazil.<br>
<p>
The main leaders of each were Kozel (leading the predominantly german members)<br>
and the other was Nicolici.  Through the years they constantly fought and bicke<br>
red over properties, accused each other of the most heinous things, and for a w<br>
hile in the last few years, seemed to be overcoming their differences and were<br>
about to reunite.  I do not know, at the present time, what the status of that<br>
is.<br>
<p>
Anyway, many other offshoots from these appeared over the years.  Their main so<br>
urce of members, as was pointed out by someone, are unhappy SDA members.  For m<br>
any years they were aggressive attackers of the SDA church and active recruiter<br>
s.  In Brazil (where I am from) I witnessed many long debates between reformers<br>
 and members of the Big Church, also known for a long time as Babylon (the SDA<br>
church).<br>
<p>
Circa 1970, there was a tremendous shake up in the Reform Church.  Initially a<br>
small group (among them my family members), tired of bickering, accusations, an<br>
d a controlling environment, left the Reform church.  It was not easy.  Leaving<br>
 a family like society where everyone is known by name, to join what for years<br>
was the apostate church (SDA), the Big Church, where we became just unknown mem<br>
bers.  We lost all our friends.  It took us many years to recover from the trau<br>
ma.  Many more left afterwards.  Today, I still know many people there.  Their<br>
world headquarters of the '51 group I belonged is now in Roanoke, VA.  I know m<br>
any of their leaders.  Unfortunately, the adverse attitude towards the SDA Chur<br>
ch has never changed.  I believe it never will.  Many are sympathetic towards t<br>
he good things it does, but for them, it is better that a family member goes to<br>
 the "world" than to join the Big Church.<br>
<p>
Some people have made attempts to overcome their aversion to rejoining the Chur<br>
ch.  The late Elder Pierson, to his death, worked quietly with the reformers, p<br>
articularly because of the geographic proximity to their biggest church in Amer<br>
ica - Sacramento, CA.  He was an appreciated person by their leadership.<br>
<p>
There are many things I could still share, but I feel this has gone long enough<br>
..  If there are any questions you could answer about that, please contact me by<br>
 E-mail.<br>
<p>
 Greetings,<br>
<p>
Joilo Barbosa  U08837@uicvm.uic.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
