<title>Aug1_1994: Re: Re:</title>
<h1>Re: Re:</h1>
<i>DAVESPARKS@delphi.com</i><br>
<i>Thu, 11 Aug 1994 22:46:05 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#274">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#274">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#274">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#274">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0275.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "A Sad Day for Adventism..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0273.html">Joilo Barbosa: "Re: The Reformed SDA church."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Nic Vermaak - Interne &lt;GNINNV@pulmo1.uovs.ac.za&gt; wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; "What we eat - we are"</i><br>
<i>&gt; At least the apple worm is wriggling apple, while the fish worm is </i><br>
<i>&gt; wriggling fish.</i><br>
<i>&gt; I have an aversion to fish - even before I became vegetarian, </i><br>
<i>&gt; therefore I would prefer the apple worm.</i><br>
<p>
I'd prefer NEITHER kind of worm, as a matter of fact.  Your logic is a<br>
little hard to follow.  You say you'd prefer to eat an "apple worm" because<br>
you like apples.  Do you like corn, too?  Would you therefore eat the beef<br>
from a corn-fed cow?<br>
<p>
The fact is, a cow is a Biblically "clean" animal and a worm, either in a<br>
fish or in an apple, isn't.  I'm told that lipstick is, or at used to be,<br>
made from worms.  I wonder which kind of worms are used?  Personally, I don't<br>
wear lipstick, so I don't worry about it too much. &lt;g&gt;<br>
<p>
As for your "aversion to fish", just be glad you weren't around when Jesus<br>
fed fish to over 5,000 hungry people.  It might be a tad bit embarrasing to<br>
refuse something that God Himself had prepared for you.  Nevertheless,<br>
that's your prerogative.<br>
<p>
