<title>Aug1_1994: Choosing pastors</title>
<h1>Choosing pastors</h1>
Cori Bradford (<i>cbradfor@ida.org</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Aug 1994 18:08:12 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#258">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#258">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#258">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#258">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0259.html">Cori Bradford: "Re: Is abortion sin?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0257.html">Cori Bradford: "Update on Reds"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0282.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Choosing pastors"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Jayne Rop asked if it has come to the point where every church can choose<br>
their own pastor.  Well, no, not quite.  Obviously in multi-church districts<br>
which are still the majority in many North American conferences the conference<br>
has to play a more active role.  But for the larger churches, particularly<br>
those which like Elmhurst have been faithful in returning their tithes,<br>
the conferences are becoming increasingly cooperative.  In fact I think <br>
we probably have more freedom than we really need.  <br>
<p>
The conference has invited us to submit any names we may think of for<br>
consideration in the process.  So far the search committee has not <br>
come up with any.  There is a reason we have our men in the conference <br>
office, and part of that is that they know much more than we do what <br>
and who is available in the way of ministers.  In particular, Ken Denslow<br>
who is the ministerial director and church growth specialist in Illinois,<br>
was formerly the assistant director of the North American Division <br>
Evangelism Institute and so has seen many of the best young pastors in <br>
the denomination go through his supervision.  I would not be surprised<br>
if we end up settling on one of the names recommended by the conference.<br>
<p>
But before we do, past experiences of this congregation have left <br>
us with a desire to make sure that we don't repeat the same mistakes<br>
that we have made before.  No doubt with this selection there will be <br>
new and different mistakes, but that is the price to pay.<br>
<p>
I don't think that this is denying the role of the Spirit.  It's an <br>
important consensus-building exercise between the local congregation<br>
and the conference officers, one of the few contacts that we have with them.<br>
The Spirit came upon the apostles when they were all of one accord,<br>
and any opportunity we have to come into accord should be taken.<br>
Furthermore, in this mode, our church has no one to blame except ourselves<br>
if we get a pastor we don't like.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
