<title>Aug1_1994: Dare To Care camporee</title>
<h1>Dare To Care camporee</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Aug 1994 17:12:07 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#177">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#177">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#177">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#177">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0178.html">Harvey Steck: "1844 a mistake?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0176.html">Woody Baker: "Fax Back service"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This comes from Owen Troy, courtesy of <br>
<p>
<p>
         "From the SDAs On-line CompuServe Forum"        <br>
           (Call [800] 260-7171 to learn how to join)    <br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
The Dare to Care Camporee officially opened Tuesday evening, but Pathfinders<br>
and staff members, some traveling for days by autos, vans, busses, trains and<br>
airplanes, arrived at least a day before and turned the Bandimere Drag Strip<br>
into a temporary city.	<br>
The hastily erected Pathfinder city is located just southwest of Denver, and<br>
stretches more than a mile and among the foothills of the massive Rocky<br>
Mountains.  <br>
A huge amount of planning over a long period of time by a large staff of<br>
workers lead by Ron Whitehead, made this possible.  <br>
The awesome task of providing for 10,000 campers required an enormous staff of<br>
volunteers, who were not only willing to work without compensation, but to also<br>
pay the full fee of $95 for the Camporee.<br>
The result of their strenuous work made it possible to offer just about every<br>
type of wholesome activity for youth between the ages of ten and fifteen, has<br>
been provided at the camporee. <br>
Registration for the large influx of personnel and vehicles required special<br>
traffic control, provided by camp security, over a two-mile area.  The<br>
registration tent was flooded with Pathfinder directors receiving their official<br>
papers and the wrist bands that everyone is required to wear.  <br>
Each North American Union has an assigned location for its Pathfinder clubs.<br>
It is remarkable the way a flat piece of ground can be transformed into home for<br>
the next week. Sleeping dinning, and cooking tents are erected. Of course the<br>
club sign is raised for all to see that the "Arkansas Travelers," the "Madison<br>
Mustangs," "Pontiac Chiefs," or the "Denver Mountaineers" are present.<br>
It took 137 golf carts, 191 walkie-talkie radios,  and the help of 125 who had<br>
worked as summer staff in camps around the country to keep the operation running<br>
smoothly.  A camp radio station operates during the waking hours by qualified<br>
professionals.<br>
Eighteen 2,000 gallon water tanks supplied the 25,000 gallons of drinking water<br>
each day. Portable showers, and rest rooms are strategically located throughout<br>
the camp. Hot water is supplied from plastic bags heated by the sun.<br>
Pathfinders are showing their willingness to "Care."  A number of institutions<br>
and organizations have benefited by the volunteer service provided by<br>
Pathfinders throughout the Denver metropolitan area. They have participated in<br>
feeding the homeless programs, painting houses, removing graffiti, some office<br>
work, and packaging food in food banks. <br>
On the campground, sixteen large tents have been erected and are filled with<br>
activities that provide entertainment, instruction, and materials for the<br>
campers. Additional activities are available on the grounds, and even  more are<br>
available at locations away from the camp but available by shuttle bus.<br>
<p>
Pathfinders are interested in their health.  The Health and Lifestyle tent runs<br>
well attended programs through the day.<br>
In the handicap tent, Pathfinders are blind folded and then run an obstacle<br>
course pushing a wheel chair with an occupant directing the blinded one through<br>
the course.<br>
Thousands are getting honors in the honor tent, which provides the necessary<br>
information for honors that range from amphibians to ukelele.<br>
Each evening nearly ten thousand assemble in the Red Rock Amphitheater. The<br>
Amphitheater is beyond walking distance from the camp, so a sixty bus convoy<br>
makes two trips each way each evening.  While this massive transportation system<br>
operates, talented Pathfinders and special guest provide additional<br>
entertainment before and after the main evening program. The first night<br>
demonstrated that there is more than enough good talent among our Pathfinders.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
