<!-- body="start" -->
Steve wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Some of our board members have suggested that the idea of </i><br>
<i>&gt; alt.religion.sda as a newsgroup name conveys that we are an alternative </i><br>
<i>&gt; religion.  Another possibility might be alt.religion.christian.sda since there</i><br>
<i>&gt; already is an alt.religion.christian.  What do you folks think of this?</i><br>
<p>
I would prefer it.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I am not sure if distribution under the bit.listserv hiearchy</i><br>
<i>&gt; might also suit our purposes.  I have set it up as internet.listserv.sdanet</i><br>
<i>&gt; at Carnegie Mellon, but if it takes a request at every news site to do that </i><br>
<i>&gt; it would not suit our purposes well.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
You shouldn't need to do it at every site, but unless it's in a widely<br>
carried hierarchy, even if you did it wouldn't help.  If your control<br>
message doesn't propagate, your articles certainly won't.  A group<br>
named internet.* isn't likely to get far as it is a non-standard hierarchy.<br>
<p>
A bit.* group is a good idea, and I think it has a better chance of<br>
being taken seriously than an alt group.  In the newsgroup bit.admin,<br>
the article titled "NetNews/Listserv Gateway Policy" explains how to<br>
get a gateway set up.  (If you can't find it, ask me and I'll send you<br>
a copy.)  Or email to news-admin@american.edu for information.  As far<br>
as I can tell, you don't need to create the newsgroup yourself, the<br>
people who provide the gateway will do it for you.  You then just<br>
place the gateway on your mailing list.<br>
<p>
Hope this helps,<br>
<p>
<p>
Malcolm<br>
<pre>
--
Switched Networks Research Centre,               malb@ee.uts.edu.au
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia            +61 2 330 2344
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
