<title>Aug1_1994: Re: Requirements for a new pastor</title>
<h1>Re: Requirements for a new pastor</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 10 Aug 94 16:21:35 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#239">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#239">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#239">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#239">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0240.html">DAVESPARKS@delphi.com: "Re: The Bible and (Which) Bible Only???"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0238.html">GEORGE TASKER: "reformed church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Qualities desirable in a new pastor:                                       </i><br>
<i>&gt;                                                                            </i><br>
<i>&gt; Good people skills</i><br>
<i>&gt;                                                                            </i><br>
<i>&gt; Good administrator</i><br>
<i>&gt;                                                                            </i><br>
<i>&gt; Gets along good with young people OR knows how to equip other people       </i><br>
<i>&gt; in the church with that skill.                                             </i><br>
<i>&gt;                                                                            </i><br>
<i>&gt; Ability to recognize and continue the role of Elmhurst as a safe place     </i><br>
<i>&gt; for those in relationship problems.                                        </i><br>
<i>&gt;                                                                            </i><br>
<i>&gt; Not afraid to try new techniques as part of overall vision for the future. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<p>
I would give my manager here at Hewlett Packard high marks in all<br>
these areas; maybe I should forward you his resume.  There is only one<br>
drawback I can think of: he has no known relationship with God.  Is<br>
that a problem?<br>
<p>
Seriously, I suspect that Steve has done what we all do, i.e., we<br>
don't waste time speaking about items that are an absolute given.  For<br>
example, at a mechanical design meeting to rank priorities, someone<br>
input ruggedness as a priority.  When it came to the vote, only one<br>
person wanted to prioritize ruggedness and was shocked that no one else<br>
shared his concern.  On the contrary, everyone replied, ruggedness is<br>
not negotiable; we don't make products that are not rugged.<br>
<p>
How could we say that?  Because we have written qualification<br>
standards that our products have to pass.  I see this as one of the<br>
major benefits of belonging to a denomination.  One should expect an<br>
ordained minister to satisfy the mandatory requirements and that the<br>
examination effort could concentrate on the optional requirements.<br>
<p>
Cheers,<br>
Dan Blake<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
