<title>Aug1_1994: Re: SDA Reform &amp; fetters in SDA?</title>
<h1>Re: SDA Reform &amp; fetters in SDA?</h1>
GEORGE TASKER (<i>taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Aug 1994 08:56:12 +1000 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#237">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#237">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#237">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#237">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0238.html">GEORGE TASKER: "reformed church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0236.html">SEREM VINCENT: "Taboo topics"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; 	I'm reminded of Paul's missionary journeys to the Gentiles. He </i><br>
<i>&gt; went to them and told them of Jesus. Many were saved and small communities </i><br>
<i>&gt; of believers were established to live among their towns &amp; demonstrate the</i><br>
<i>&gt; love of Christ to those around them.</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	A few concerned people did their own missionary journey behind Paul </i><br>
<i>&gt; and told those communities that they should be circumcized and keep the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Jewish days/feasts etc.</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	Paul was not pleased. He told the Gentile believers that if they</i><br>
<i>&gt; were circumcized they would no longer be saved. He told the Jews to stop</i><br>
<i>&gt; making it difficult for the Gentiles to accept Christ.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 	I wonder if I see comparison with such groups as those mentioned</i><br>
<i>&gt; by Ben above and their specific laws and codes.</i><br>
<p>
You may but I see one important difference.  The above mentioned groups<br>
claimed to be part of the mainstream church of the day.  The Reformed SDA's<br>
on the other hand have essentially left our church and do not worship with<br>
the mainstreamers.  The way I see it they are not interfering with the <br>
mainstream of our church and keep pretty much to themselves.  If we spend a<br>
lot of time and energy talking about them aren't we guilty of the very thing<br>
that we appear to be accusing them of.  If they leave us alone then it is <br>
only fair that we leave them alone.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 	In fact I even wonder if the mainstream SDA church is guilty of</i><br>
<i>&gt; some of this - and I'd appreciate your thoughts on this issue.</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	When we take a non-Christian and make him/her a SDA, are we not</i><br>
<i>&gt; fettering them with the Sabbath/vegetarianism/other culturally based</i><br>
<i>&gt; behaviours? </i><br>
<p>
You bet we are!  Of course I don't have a problem with that.  When we join <br>
any human organisation we do so for two reasons.  The first is that the <br>
organisation has a set of interests or beliefs  that matches our own.  The <br>
second following on from that is that the organisation will expect us to <br>
conform to a code of behaviour.  The organisation can be anything you like - <br>
clubs, pubs, choirs, religions, politics - the list goes on.<br>
<p>
Let's take work as an organisation.  It is expect that when one is at work <br>
that one will behave in a manner pleasing to the boss and fellow workers.  <br>
Last year I was in the local city choir.  I enjoyed it but a change in <br>
circumstances made it impossible for me to perform in a manner pleasing to <br>
the producer of the show that was being organised and I had to drop out.<br>
<p>
It so happens that if one moves onto churches one sees exactly the same kind <br>
of thing.  A church is a human organisation.  It has become like this <br>
because a number of people got together that had something in common that <br>
noone else would accept.  As such it is only natural that they decide on who <br>
becomes a member of their organisation and who doesn't.  This means that I <br>
belong to this church because it suits my way of life.<br>
<p>
The real problem comes as a result of too many people pushing the idea that <br>
to be a member of this church == being saved.  The implication here is that <br>
if for some reason the church decides to disfellowship someone that they <br>
have been dammed to rot in hell.  That, I have a real problem with.  It <br>
tars us with the same brush that we have been trying to tar the catholics <br>
with for so long.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
George Tasker                                 taskerg@topaz.cqu.edu.au
                                              taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au
<p>
Blessed is the man that hath nothing to say and cannot be persuaded to say it.
Hezekiah 5:9
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
