<title>Aug1_1994: Taboo topics</title>
<h1>Taboo topics</h1>
SEREM VINCENT (<i>SEREM@agreng.lan.mcgill.ca</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Aug 1994 17:25:06 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#236">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#236">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#236">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#236">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0237.html">GEORGE TASKER: "Re: SDA Reform &amp; fetters in SDA?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0235.html">SEREM VINCENT: "Re: Is abortion sin?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Several people were surprised to find that SDAnet has taboo topics.<br>
Since this is the first time abortion has come up on SDAnet in almost 2 <br>
years, it's not surprising that many don't remember it.  There are <br>
only two "taboo topics", namely abortion and creation/evolution.<br>
Both of those got to be that way because the discussion on them rapidly<br>
degenerated to the level that one would find on the Usenet groups<br>
talk.abortion or talk.origins.  I didn't start SDAnet to duplicate the <br>
same rhetoric on both sides that happens in the world at large.  If you <br>
want to recite canned rhetoric on either side of the abortion debate,<br>
you can take your discussion elsewhere.<br>
<p>
Having said that, I recognize that SDAnet also includes many people who <br>
have something to say about this from time to time, and they should be <br>
allowed to have their say.  So when discussion on these topics comes up,<br>
we allow it to happen, but try to keep it focused to the Adventist angle<br>
of things.  Really unanswerable questions like how many abortions are<br>
going on in SDA hospitals, what should be SDA's attitude to birth control,<br>
etc.<br>
<p>
The SDA statement on abortion has been posted here before,.  I will try<br>
to dig it out of the archives, also it is available on SDA's Online.<br>
As I recall there were quite a few "motherhood" statements in there, if <br>
you'll pardon the expression.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
