<title>Aug1_1994: Re: Question about "SDA Reform Movement"?</title>
<h1>Re: Question about "SDA Reform Movement"?</h1>
GEORGE TASKER (<i>taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Aug 1994 10:30:52 +1000 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#184">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#184">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#184">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#184">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0185.html">adam@veda.is: "Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0183.html">Bill Sands Jr.: "The Close of Probation..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The SDA reform movement that I am aware of may or may not be related to the<br>
one being asked about as they are in two different countries.  The one I<br>
know here in Oz considers itself a step above the mainstream SDA church.<br>
It gets its members in by cannibalising the main SDA church rather than <br>
trying to win new members from the world.<br>
<p>
I don't know enough about it to know whether or not it can be considered a <br>
cult but it is very strong on EGW and at one stage the expected behaviour <br>
of men and women were very well defined.  I can recall that women did not <br>
cut their hair.<br>
<p>
I hope that adds to the body of knowledge about the reform movement.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
George Tasker                                 taskerg@topaz.cqu.edu.au
                                              taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au
