<title>Aug1_1994: Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori</title>
<h1>Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori</h1>
GEORGE TASKER (<i>taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Aug 1994 10:51:01 +1000 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#186">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#186">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#186">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#186">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0187.html">adam@veda.is: "Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0185.html">adam@veda.is: "Re: Herbivorism vs Omnivori"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Maybe so, but then what item of food or drink (even "plain water") isn't</i><br>
<i>&gt; "less safe" now than it was then?  Of course, that's counter-balanced by</i><br>
<i>&gt; modern technology concerning proper preparation of food, bacteriological</i><br>
<i>&gt; sampling, etc.  Back before you had microscopes, or even a knowledge of the</i><br>
<i>&gt; existence of bacteria, you had to take BROAD measures to be safe.  It was</i><br>
<i>&gt; obviously easier for God to give some simple, blanket rules than a</i><br>
<i>&gt; dissertation on microbiology.</i><br>
<p>
However even with today's knowledge we still get a large amount of micro-<br>
biological contamination if a recent TV program I saw is to be believed.  In <br>
it the journalist doing the story got hold of a number of items bought over<br>
the shelf from various sandwich shops and other fast food outlets and took <br>
them to a microbiol lab for testing.  The results were that each of these<br>
food items had at least 300,000 microbes.  So if one bought a food item<br>
from one of these stores then one could rest assured that there would be <br>
about 300,000 microbes in there about to be digested in their stomach.<br>
<p>
Amongst the bacteria found included E.Coli, S.Cocci and various other <br>
nasties.  When my wife looked at the program she was almost sick as she <br>
often has enjoyed a sandwich or to from such places in the past.  I suspect <br>
she will be less inclined towards that kind of thing in the future.  It <br>
seems to me that knowledge of such nasties is no safety net against them.  <br>
It seems that many preparers of such food hold the attitude, out of sight <br>
out of mind.  Of course to make things more interesting they stored their <br>
food items in places that made the environment for bacterial growth highly<br>
favorable.  Warm, moist and behind glass.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; To put it another way, the very purest water "back then" was probably purer</i><br>
<i>&gt; than what we have available to us today.  OTOH, when a water source was</i><br>
<i>&gt; contaminated back then, it was often only discovered after the fact when</i><br>
<i>&gt; people who drank from it started getting sick or dying.  The same is true</i><br>
<i>&gt; with the meat that people ate.  While it may have been, IN GENERAL, "more</i><br>
<i>&gt; healthy, less diseased", without microscopes and modern inspection methods,</i><br>
<i>&gt; you pretty much took your chances.  While the "best" may have been better</i><br>
<i>&gt; than it is today, undoubtedly the "worst" was worse, too.</i><br>
<p>
Of course it is still much the same today with salmonella lying around.  In<br>
my experience with working in the abattoir(sp) the meat that was processed<br>
did not all go past the labs for testing.  And even if it did they have to <br>
know what they are looking for.  From what I have seen of the food <br>
processing industry any faith placed in modern inspection methods is badly <br>
misplaced.  We still take our chances every bit as much now as back in those <br>
days.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
George Tasker                                 taskerg@topaz.cqu.edu.au
                                              taskerg@jasper.cqu.edu.au
<p>
Blessed is the man that hath nothing to say and cannot be persuaded to say it.
Hezekiah 5:9
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
