<HEAD>
<title>Dick Armey's Flat Tax -- ATR</title>
</HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><H2><IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="atr!2.gif" ALT="Americans for Tax Reform"><Center><FONT SIZE=+4><B>T<FONT SIZE=+3>ax</FONT>  R<FONT SIZE=+3>eform</FONT> N<FONT SIZE=+3>ews</FONT></B></FONT>
<P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>F</FONT></B>lat <FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>ax Will Make the Tax Code Family-Friendly Again</B><P></H2><IMG SRC="blueline.gif"><CENTER><EM>by Rep. Dick Armey (R-texas)</EM><P></CENTER></CENTER>

   Many families today say they need two incomes to make ends meet, and they're right but
not for the reason most people think.  They need two incomes because of the high cost of
government:  one to support themselves, and a second to pay their taxes and support the politicians.<P>  
In recent decades, the government has grown so large so fast that over 40 percent of an average family's earnings is soaked up by taxes.  A typical family now pays more in taxes than it spends on food, clothing, and shelter combined.<P>
     In addition, Americans today spend 5.4 billion man-hours a year calculating how much they
owe Uncle Sam in taxes.   The overall size of government itself is undermining families'abilities to live the American dream.  That's why I introduced a bill, the Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act, designed to cut the size and influence of Washington.  It will revolutionize everything the government does-taxing, spending, and regulating-and allow us to keep more of our money and live the way we believe is right. <P>
     The bill starts by replacing our entire current income tax code with a flat tax.  After seven
decades of abuse by corporate lobbyists and self-righteous income redistributors, our tax code is a mess.  Rates are high, loop-holes abound, and families are burdened as never before.<P>  
My bill would scrap the entire code and start over with a simple, low, flat tax.  Modeled after a
plan that Robert Hall and Alvin Rabushka proposed in 1981, it would work like this: You would
add up your earned income, subtract a large personal allowance ($13,100 for a single person,
$26,000 for a married couple filing jointly), take away $5,300 for each child (which is double the
current amount), and then pay a flat 17 percent rate on the remainder.  That's it.  There would be
no special interest deductions or loop-holes of any kind.  You could figure your taxes on a form
as small as a post-card.  In fact, while it takes the average taxpayer 11 hours to do his taxes today, you could this figuring in ll minutes-with no fear that you made a mistake that'll bring out the IRS auditors or missed some clever loopholes that everyone knows about but you.<P>
     Why a 17 percent rate?  That's low enough to give virtually all Americans a major tax cut, but
high enough to meet the government's revenue needs (which will, of course, be reduced under this plan).  With a doubled child deduction, families with children will do especially well.<P>
     Now, the soak-the-rich crowd reflexively claims that a flat tax is by definition unfair.  That's
flat wrong.  Fairness is in fact the flat tax's great virtue.  It's based on the idea of fairness we
learned in grade school : Everyone should be treated the same.  Rather than have fallible
politicians decide which groups should surrender more or less of their earnings to the government, the flat tax sets a single objective standard.<P>
     Indeed, this system will be as progressive as the income tax system we had when John
Kennedy was president.  How so?  The plan's high personal allowance mean that the middle class income folks will pay a far lower portion of their total income to the government than the
wealthy, even if their tax rate is the same.<P>
     A typical family of four, for instance, will pay no income taxes at all on their first $36,800 of
income-the 17 percent rate will only apply to income above that.  As many as 10 million poor
people will be removed from the tax roles entirely.  If you want progressive, this gets the job done without a complicate tax code as long as the Encyclopedia Britanninca.<P>
     Of course, there will be the predictable objections.  Vested interests will fear the loss of such
breaks as the home mortgage deduction.  But by removing the tax code's current punishment for
saving, the plan will swell the capital pool, causing interest rates to drop and demand for housing
to rise.  As housing values hold or increase under the plan-and economic growth soars-only
Washington tax lobbyists will be nostalgic for the old way.  With the flat tax, there will be a single
readily grasped objective standard.  The only thing that matters is whether you have children. 
Otherwise you are treated the same as everyone else.  <P>
     All Americans will benefit mightly form the higher wages and new jobs that such a rational tax
system would be sure to create.  Our twisted tax system today treats investing in new jobs the
same way it treats cigarette smoking-by discouraging it with especially high taxes.    If you want
to put some of your earnings in a stock or mutual fund, that money is hit with double-taxation: it's
taxedwhen you invest it.  No wonder wages have been flat and job growth low.<P>
     The flat tax would end this craziness.  There would, in effect, be no capital gains tax, no tax on dividends or interest, nor would there be a tax on whatever inheritance we try to leave for our
children (why work a lifetime so the government can take half of what you leave behind?).  This
would unleash American talent, work and creativity as never before.  Economic growth would
soar.<P>
     We would still have a tax on business income, of course, but it would be the same flat 17
percent rate that we'd pay on personal income, and a far simpler system for small businesses to
manage than today's ridiculously complicated code.  They would not need to wrestle with
depreciation schedules or other arcania.  They would simply subtract all their expenses from their revenues and pay 17 percent.<P>
     Make no mistake, though, the flat tax is more than just a good government reform to make our tax system simple, fair and pro-growth.  It's a way of telling politicians that we're tired
of being toyed with.   Congress didn't design our tax system to raise revenue for the government
efficiently.  It doesn't do that.  They use it the same they use spending programs-to direct our
money at whatever causes or inerest groups they think are important. 
     Government does not have the competence or the right to make those decisions.  We should
have a tax system that is neutral and let 250 million free Americans decide where their money
should go. <P>
     Oh, and one last thing.  This 17 percent flat tax rate with these personal deductions means a
big tax cut for everyone-especially families who would see their child deduction double. The best
way to keep politicians form spending more and more of other people's money is to reduce their
supply.  Let them cut spending instead. <P>
<center><IMG SRC="blueline.gif"></center><br>
<B>Source: Tax Foundation</B>
