<HTML>
<HEAD><title>GrassRoots News -- ATR</title></HEAD>
<BODY Bgcolor=#FFFFFF><CENTER><a href="/atr/bar4.map"><img src="/atr/bar4.gif" ismap border="0"></a>  </CENTER>
<BOLD><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>
GrassRoots America
</FONT></CENTER><ADDRESS><HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=30%>
<img align=left src="outline.gif">
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD><CENTER>Initiatives and Referenda</FONT></BOLD></CENTER><P>

	When Congress refuses to deal with an issue, activists often go to state legislatures to fight for change.  Welfare reform is an example of an issue ignored by Washington, D.C., and championed by state leaders like Gov. John Engler (R-Mich.), Gov. Tommy Thompson (R-Wisc.), and others.<P>
	But when Washington, D.C., and state capitals hide their heads in the sand or man the barricades in defense of the status quo, citizens in 24 states can turn to the initiative process.  Initiatives allow citizens to gather a specified number of signatures of voters on a petition to place a law or constitutional amendment on the state ballot.<P>
	This was the case when Howard Jarvis and Paul Gann placed Proposition 13 on the California ballot in June of 1978.  Proposition 13 cut property taxes in half and just as importantly required a two-thirds majority vote of the legislature to approve any state tax increase.  Other states followed with similar initiatives on the November 1978 ballot.  The subsequent success of taxpayer groups in using the initiative process helped to convince President Ronald Reagan to support the Kemp-Roth tax cut that eventually passed in 1981.  Thus local and state taxpayer groups started a tidal wave using the initiative process at the state level which also influenced federal legislation.<P>
	In 1990, the term limits movement began the long march through the states using the initiative process.  In spite of opinion polls which showed overwhelming public support for limits of six years for U.S. Representatives and 12 years for U.S. Senators, congressional leaders such as former House Speaker Tom Foley (D-Wash.) and former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell (D-Maine) refused to allow a vote on term limits in either the House or Senate.  Worse, they used tax money to pay for attorneys who filed lawsuits against state term limit ballot questions.<P>
	Most members of state legislatures were usually no more enthusiastic than most members of Congress were about the move to limit their own terms of office.  But fortunately, the voters had one more option: the initiative process.<P>
	Success came in recent years when 21 states passed term limits with an average approval majority of 65 percent.  This groundswell created the right climate to persuade U.S. House Republican leaders that a promise to vote on a constitutional amendment to limit terms of lawmakers should be included in the "Contract with America."<P>
  	This spring, the first vote ever held on the floor of the U.S. House of Representatives to limit terms received support from a solid majority of House members, but less than the two-thirds majority needed to amend the Constitution.  None of this could have happened unless the national organization called U.S. Term Limits had prepared the ground by leading fights at the state level using the initiative process.<P>
	Most recently, the drive to abolish affirmative action including racial quotas and set-asides in government contracts has been energized by backers of the California Civil Rights Initiative (CCRI).  CCRI supporters plan to place that initiative on the California ballot in 1996.  Supporters believe the CCRI is needed to strike down all government racial quotas and reintroduce employment and business opportunities where men and women may be judged by the merit of their qualifications and content of their character rather than the color of their skin.  Activists in Colorado and other states are exploring ways to copy the CCRI in their states.  For a copy of CCRI, call Kolt Jones in the ATR Washington, D.C., office at 202-785-0266.<P>
<p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD>Super  Majority States
</CENTER></FONT></BOLD><P>
	Another major reform that is sweeping the nation through the initiative process is a requirement that legislatures may only approve tax increases by a super majority, not just a simple majority.  For example, in 1992 Arizona passed a requirement that any tax increase must receive the approval of two-thirds of both the state house and state senate.  In 1994, Nevada passed a similar two-thirds requirement with 79 percent of the vote.  That state will vote again on the measure since two separate votes of approval by the people are required in that state.<P>	
	Initiative supporters in Ohio, Florida, Montana, and other states are planning to sponsor ballot questions in November 1996 that would approve constitutional amendments to make it more difficult to raise taxes.  California may vote in March of 1996 on a measure to require either a two-thirds vote of the legislature or a two-thirds vote of the people for any tax increase to pass.<P>
	Americans for Tax Reform hosts a monthly conference call on the initiative process which includes leaders of state initiative measures.  The telephone discussion usually lasts for one hour and covers the progress of various state efforts.  If you know of an initiative or plan to sponsor one in your state, please call Kolt Jones at 202-785-0266 to learn more about how to participate in the conference call.<P>
<p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD>
Term Limits</CENTER></FONT></BOLD><P>


	Until the U.S. Supreme Court handed down its May 22 decision which banned state legislation imposing congressional term limits, many states had used the initiative process to place term limit questions on the ballot.<P>
	Before the decision, 21 states had passed congressional term limits by popular vote of the people, usually by overwhelming majorities.  One state that allows initiatives, Utah, passed the provision in the state legislature.  In early May, the New Hampshire legislature became the first assembly in a non-initiative state to pass congressional term limits.  The governor of New Hampshire signed the bill on May 15.<P>
	Almost before the ink was dry on the New Hampshire statute, the U.S. Supreme Court struck down the laws of all 23 states which had acted to impose congressional term limits.  Before the decision, more than 90 percent of states which allow some kind of initiative or referendum process had adopted congressional term limits.<P>
	Currently, 20 states have passed measures which impose term limits on state legislators.  Limits on the terms of state officials will remain in force since they were not overturned by the Supreme Court decision which affects only congressional term limits.  This November, citizens of Mississippi will vote on an initiative that will place term limits on all state legislators and local elected officials.  For more information on term limits efforts in your state, call U.S. Term Limits in Washington, D.C., at 202-393-6440.<P>
<P>
<p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD>
Buckeye State Super Majority</CENTER></FONT></BOLD><P>


	There are several different initiatives that have "responsibility" as their main message.  In the state of Ohio, Lee Donaho, Executive Director of the National Taxpayers Union of Ohio, has been working on an initiative that would force the legislature to require a three-fifths super majority to enact any new taxes or new tax increases.  For more information, write to Lee Donoho at NTU of Ohio, 2029 Riverside Drive, Suite 101, Columbus, Ohio 43221 or call 614-486-0315.<P>
<p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD>
Sunshine State Tax Cap</FONT></BOLD></CENTER><P>


	David Biddulph, President of the Florida Tax Cap Committee, has a similar initiative that requires two-thirds of the vote of the people to raise taxes.  Voting on your own tax increases?  Yes, 10 states now have the ability to say whether or not they will receive a tax increase.  People in these states can feel the difference too, the tax burden rose nearly 20 percent faster in states without a super majority to raise taxes.<P>
 	 Last year, the need for tax restraint was recognized, discussed, and fought for by the people.  The American people were given the chance to limit government, and they did.  Realizing the impact the I&R process could have, bureaucrats are making the initiative process more time-consuming, bureaucratic, expensive, and out of reach to many American citizens looking for the justice that the initiative process preserves elsewhere. <P>
	 For more information, write to David Biddulph at Florida Tax Cap Committee, P.O. Box 193, New Smyrna Beach, Fla., 32170-0193 or call 904-423-4744.<P>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD>
   National Pause for the Pledge of Allegiance
</FONT></BOLD></CENTER><P>

	Flag Day, June 14 this year, will include the 16th annual "Pause for the Pledge of Allegiance," organized by the National Flag Day Foundation.  Sites around the nation will include a major event at Fort McHenry, in Baltimore, Md., where participants will lead  simultaneous recitations of the pledge at 7 P.M. EDT.  For more information contact Pat Perluke at 410-563-3524.<P>
<p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD>
Let Freedom Ring</FONT></BOLD></CENTER><P>

	On July 4, the Philadelphia Society of the Sons of the American Revolution will be sponsoring a bell ringing to honor the patriots of the 13 colonies who fought, and lost their lives for the freedoms that we celebrate today.  The ringing will take place at 2:00 P.M. (EDT) across the United States.  The bells are to be rung one time for each of the 13 original colonies.  For more information or to volunteer to be a bell ringer in your community, please call "Let Freedom Ring" at 1-800-336-1776.<P>
<P>
<p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD>
"Contract with Passaic"</FONT></BOLD></CENTER><P>


	On May 9,  four incumbents on the Passaic, New Jersey, city council lost their seats to members of the Passaic Homeowners and Taxpayers Association.  The challengers signed a contract with the citizens of Passaic pledging a 20 percent reduction in taxes.<P>
	The contract contains 10 "common sense points" that will lessen the tax burden of the residents as well as improve the use of their tax money.  Included among these points are provisions to reduce taxes over a three year period (10 percent for FY 1996 and 5 percent for FY 1997 and 1998), reduce city spending to mirror tax decreases, and a freeze on unnecessary municipal hiring and pay increases without council review. <P>
 	The winners, Ellen Magnus, Gary Schaer, Chaim M. Munk, and Benni Jakubovic, vowed to pull the city together and focus on its economy.<P>
<p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD>
Rush Dinners</FONT></BOLD></CENTER><P>


	Walter Abbott of Ruston, La., has started a national trend in conservative eating known as the "Rush Limbaugh Supper Club."  The clubs are basically social dinner clubs comprised of "right-minded" people who get together and listen to Rush, discuss the issues, and eat dinner.  ATR is hoping that this trend will spread very fast, as it is a great way to activate the grassroots.<P>
	 To receive information on how to start a "Rush Supper Club," please call Kolt Jones at (202) 785-0266.<P>
	Contributors to this section include Kolt Zimmerman Jones, ATR State Projects Coordinator, and Tricia Penkert, State Projects Manager.<P>
<P>
