<HEAD><title>AGENDA -- ATR</title></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><IMG SRC="bar4.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><BOLD><FONT SIZE=+3>
Dozens of Freshmen Take the Pledge
</CENTER></BOLD></FONT>

<FONT SIZE=+2>J</FONT>ackie Gleason loved to tell a story about an old priest from a poor village in Ireland who had never before stayed in a hotel.  Invited to visit New York City for the first time in 1959 as the guest of a foundation, the priest checked in to the Waldorf Astoria.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT> bell boy carried the clergyman's luggage to his room, opened the drapes, set out glasses and linen, hung clothes in the closet, and performed all manner of service.  Expecting a tip, as the young man started to leave he placed his hand palm up in front of the priest.  Unfamiliar with the gesture, the priest shook the bell boy's hand and thanked him heartily.<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>"F</FONT>ather, you don't understand," the bell boy explained  "In this country, it's customary for guests to give us a tip."   The priest was embarrassed since he had no money, but he had an idea.<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="capblue.gif"><br>
<A HREF="etaxho.html"> House List    </A>|<A HREF="etxsena.html">   Senate List</a>	<p>In a thick Irish brogue he asked,  "Tell me young man, do you ever drink?"<P></CENTER>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>"</FONT>Sure!," said the bell boy brightening with enthusiasm, as the joyful vision of an imported bottle of Irish whiskey popped into his imagination,  "I do indeed, Father."<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>"W</FONT>ell then," replied the priest, hoping to be of service,  "kneel down and bow your head while I give you the pledge."<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>hen that priest was young, many men "took the pledge" to shun the excesses of alcohol.  Some took it often and just as often fell short of full compliance.  But the act itself was a sincere promise to try to do better, which is all anyone could ask.<P>
  <FONT SIZE=+2>S</FONT>ince 1986,<BOLD> Americans for Tax Reform (ATR)</BOLD> has encouraged candidates for Congress to take a different pledge.  This pledge requires lawmakers to promise they will shun another addiction common to government  -- that of overspending and excess taxation.  A similar pledge has been offered  to candidates for state legislatures since 1987.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>H</FONT>undreds of legislators have signed the ATR Pledge promising constituents to:<P><ADDRESS><CENTER> "Oppose any and all efforts to increase the marginal income tax rates for individuals or businesses;" <P><FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD><IMG SRC="ball_blu.gif">AND<IMG SRC="ball_blu.gif"></BOLD></FONT><P>
  "Oppose any further reduction or elimination of deductions and credits, unless matched dollar for dollar by further reducing tax rates."<CENTER></ADDRESS><P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he pledge plays an important part in many  campaigns.  Currently, 31  U.S. Senators and 196 House members have signed up.   Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole (R-Kan.) and Sen. Phil Gramm (R-Texas) have joined other presidential candidates who have also signed, including Pat Buchanan, Alan Keyes, Robert Dornan, Lamar Alexander, and Arlen Specter.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><a href="/atr/bar.map"><img src="/atr/bar.gif" ismap border="0"></a> </CENTER>
