<HR>
<a name="8">
<B>Pro Bono Legal Services for the Poor</B>
<BR>
Lawyers have a long and distinguished history of providing free or 
<I>pro bono</I> (from the Latin &quot;Pro bono publico,&quot; meaning &quot;for public good&quot;) legal services 
to the poora history that predates the nation's founding. 
 Accounts of the young lawyer Abe Lincoln 
representing poor clients for little or no compensation have 
always been part of the lore of the young Republic.  The 
history of formal pro bono legal service organizations is 
almost as long and equally distinguished.
<P>Organized delivery of free legal services began 
in 1876 with the founding in New York City of what 
became the Legal Aid Society (LAS).  Created to help 
poor German immigrants, by 1901 it was serving 16,000 
clients of all nationalities.  (Today, the LAS civil office 
has a $20-million budget, all of which comes from 
sources other than the LSC.)  Another venerable provider of legal services, the Chicago Bureau of 
Justice, was created in 1888 and was the first organization 
to provide civil legal help to the poor regardless of 
nationality or race.  By 1923, at least 33 legal aid societies 
in over 40 cities were providing basic legal services.
<P>According to the LSC, the number of private 
attorneys in the United States today who perform pro bono 
civil legal work for the poor is roughly 130,000.  This, 
however, was the figure cited by an ABA spokesman 
seven years ago when there were less than 500 organized 
pro bono programs.  Whatever the figure's accuracy then, 
it is totally unreliable today since the number of pro 
bono programs has increased to 950.  Moreover, ABA 
official Laurie Zelon recently conceded that the 130,000 
figure does not count the many lawyers who perform 
valuable pro bono service outside of organized 
legal-services programs.
<P>By conservative estimates, at least 400,000 and 
possibly as many as 600,000or between 44 and 67 
percent of all private attorneysdo pro bono work.  
These numbers are derived from surveys conducted in 
states with lawyer populations totalling half the lawyers in 
the U.S.
<P>Assuming that the remaining number of lawyers 
per forms an equal amount of pro bono work, the total number of lawyers rendering pro bono service in 
1991 was approximately 473,000.  Since the total lawyer 
population grew from 805,872 in 1991 to 896,172 in 1995, 
the number of lawyers currently providing at least some 
pro bono work is probably close to 525,000.  Thus, the 
range of 400,000 to 600,000 is realistic.  Whatever the 
exact number, it is far greater than the 130,000 
commonly cited.
<P>Information on the amount and value of pro bono 
work lawyers perform is available for six 
statesCalifornia, Florida, Maryland, New York, Oregon, and Texas.  
Together, these states contain 40 percent of all lawyers. 
 Assuming that these states and the value placed on their 
lawyers' time by their state bar leaders are representative 
of the total lawyer population, an estimated $3.3-billion worth of pro bono work is 
performed annually in the U.S.  That is over 8 times the LSC's 
1995 budget.
<P>Critics may dismiss this figure by arguing that 
most LSC-funded lawyers are full-time and compensated on 
a salary basis; their much lower hourly rate cannot 
be compared to this estimated value of pro bono hours.  
A more accurate analysis, they say, would compare 
the number of hours LSC-funded lawyers work to the 
number of pro bono hours.
<P>If we extrapolate the number of pro bono hours 
contributed in the six states surveyed (9,659,709) to 
all lawyers, this suggests that lawyers contribute 
over 24,000,000 pro bono hours per year.  In other words, 
pro bono attorneys contribute over five times the number 
of hours worked annually by the 4,749 staff attorneys of 
the approximately 281 providers in the LSC's network.
<P>
<HR WIDTH="33%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B><CENTER>Pro bono attorneys contribute over five times the number of hours worked 
annually by the 4,749 staff attorneys of the 
approximately 281 providers in the LSC's network.</CENTER></B>
<HR WIDTH="33%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-1>
(This article is adapted from the October 1995 issue 
of <I>Alternatives in Philanthropy</I>, entitled &quot;Private 
Alternatives to the Legal Services Corporation,&quot; by 
David Wilkinson.  Several figures have been lowered 
slightly because the number of pro bono hours reported by 
the state of Florida has since been revised downward.  For 
the complete article, contact the editor.)
</FONT>





