<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Organizational Trends -- CRC</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar"
 border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/crc/images/hdr-ot.gif">
</center>
<p>
<i>January, 1997</i>
<P>
<h2>Pennsylvania Legislative Report: Restricting Foundation Influence Over State Government</h2>
<p>
<i>Editor's Note:  Last month we reported in "Briefly Noted" that the Pennsylvania General Assembly was considering a measure to curtail nonprofit foundation grantmaking to state agencies.  In this issue, Genevieve Young, a lawyer specializing in health law issues, provides a thorough review and analysis of the proposal, explores the events that led to its consideration, and explains why this has become an important issue for all state governments.</i>
<p>Imagine this scenario:  An organization obtains the names of every Medicaid-eligible student under the age of 21 in a state's public school system, and provides those names to the local school district.  It explains that it has figured out how to get Medicaid to make payments to the district every time a school encourages one of its eligible kids to go to the school guidance counselor.  Now imagine that every time one of those students visits a guidance counselor, the Medicaid program is billed for "mental health services."  Does this sound far-fetched?  It does.  Is it happening?  It is.  Does it sound like Medicaid fraud?  Yes.  So why haven't we heard of any investigations by the U. S. Department of Health and Human Services Office of Inspector General (OIG)?  
<p>The reason the public is unlikely to hear Washington officials express outrage about this development is that the fraud has not been perpetrated by a fly-by-night health care company or a cabal of doctors.  It's being carried out by state officials in Pennsylvania, Kentucky, and other states that have established public school health clinics.
<p>But this idea did not originate with the "educrats"; they're only implementing the programs, defending the benefits they derive from the program, and hiding the costs.  The real impetus for the creative exploitation of school health clinics and related programs comes from certain prominent private foundations.  They have discovered a new way to affect public policy -- just pay for what you want to have happen.  Foundations have found that it's possible to get the government to initiate unpopular programs by simply giving grants of money to state agencies to set up pilot projects.  
<p>The money comes with conditions, but cash-hungry agencies don't mind.  Agency heads are happy to do the foundations' bidding because they are always in search of new missions that they can use to justify their budgets.  The idea is to use foundation "seed money" to launch new government social programs or expand existing ones.  Soon various clients and interest groups will see the benefits for them; agency officials will argue that that there is an evident need for the programs; and the taxpayers -- not the foundations -- will be stuck with the bill.
<p>The problem with this cozy partnership of public agency and private foundation is that it's undemocratic.  If they wanted to provide services to people who want them, the foundations could spend their ample funds creating charitable institutions to accomplish a mission they think needs doing.  They could even practice the kind of public interest advocacy that unfortunately has become the commonplace way to generate support for programs that nonprofits think the government should provide.  But the foundations prefer to skip the process of public persuasion.  They would rather simply pay state agencies to buy their programs off the shelf.  
<p>This novel approach to public policy has gone unnoticed until recently.  But state legislators, protective of their own prerogatives, are taking notice.
<p>
<center>* * * * *</center>
<p>
<p><b>Pennsylvania Targets the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation</b>
<p>
<p>On November 19, 1996, the Subcommittee on House Resolution 37, a body reporting to the Pennsylvania House of Representatives' Committee on Education, adopted certain Findings of Fact and issued a Report.  It concerned abuses of a state program intended to allow public schools to tap into Medicaid funds.  House Resolution 37 directed Pennsylvania legislators to scrutinize the program, which it said lacked adequate statutory authority and which state agencies had initiated without affording to the legislature the opportunity to consider its consequences.  
<p>The Report's recommendations were based on thousands of documents, seven hearings, and testimony from nearly 75 persons.  While investigating how the legislature's authority had been circumvented, the Subcommittee discovered that state agencies had entered into relationships with certain private foundations in exchange for grant money to support the establishment of school-based health clinics.
<p>The Subcommittee Report expressed the concern that these relationships were usually carried out without notice to the general public.  It also became clear during the inquiry that certain employees of state agencies were having their salaries paid, in whole or in part, by private foundation money.  Moreover, foundation documents indicated that although money was distributed as a "grant," it had strings attached.  In the case of grants made by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation (RWJF), Pennsylvania had executed contracts with the foundation giving RWJF exclusive and perpetual rights to data collected in connection with the state program, even if the data would otherwise be considered confidential and private under federal and state law.
<P>The Report is a historic step -- and it is likely the first of its kind -- that a state's legislators have taken to curtail encroachments on their constitutional authority by unelected officials serving in the state's executive and administrative agencies.  The language of the Report is unambiguous:
<p>
<blockquote>The Select Subcommittee's inquiry has... found that the Executive Branch's school based mental health and rehabilitative programs have been created and implemented in ways that cavalierly disregard the proper role of the General Assembly as the elected representatives of the people in formulating public policy.  In this regard, the Executive Branch has implemented this massive program... through a patchwork of bureaucratic initiatives rather than the legislative process where these difficult social and fiscal issues are more properly decided.  For instance, comprehensive mental health services are being provided throughout the public school system despite the absence of clear and specific statutory authority....  While there may be funding authorization for these initiatives within the state budget, this is a woefully inadequate substitute for the solid statutory framework that forms the only legitimate foundation for exercise of power in a representative democracy.</blockquote>
<p>The Report specifically focuses on the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation (RWJF).  It finds that besides bypassing the General Assembly, the Executive Branch "tailored its discretionary authority to meet the specifications of a grant from the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, a private entity, in order to obtain funding from this private source."
<p>The Report further establishes that the Executive Branch relied upon a RWJF "pilot project" to develop techniques for implementing Pennsylvania's statewide program to provide comprehensive mental health and related services to students, a program that is heavily dependent on Medicaid and other state monies.  In fact, a Department of Public Welfare memorandum that the Select Subcommittee obtained identified RWJF as a primary source for all of Pennsylvania's school-based mental and other health initiatives.
<p>The authors of the Report say that its findings will be the basis for legislation on the use of medical and educational records by the public school system to protect the privacy rights of parents and children, and that the legislation should require parents' prior written and informed consent for their children to participate in activities and services provided in the schools.  The proposed legislation will also protect the fiscal integrity of Pennsylvania's Medicaid program, particularly as it is used by the public schools.  Finally, there are several specific recommendations about how private foundations may interact with state agencies.  Says Rep. Samuel E. Rohrer, Chairman of the Subcommittee on House Resolution 37, "It's going to have a tremendous ripple effect on all the policy coming out of this administration."
<p>The Report calls for laws that would require authorization before the state can receive grant funds.  It calls for prior notice to the public and the General Assembly before state officials can apply for private grant monies.  Without express statutory authorization, it says agencies cannot participate in pilot projects or other foundation initiatives that come with strings attached.
<p>The Report also recommends that any foundation-funded project narrative, its costs, and proposed terms and conditions should be reported in the Pennsylvania Bulletin, the official administrative register, along with 30 days' notice, and that the Majority and Minority Chairmen of the House and Senate Appropriations Committees and other committees should be notified before a state agency makes a commitment to participate in a project.  It would prohibit agencies from accepting private funds to pay the compensation of any state employee without providing similar detailed notice.
<p>Finally, the Report urges the Pennsylvania General Assembly to consider legislation to restrict the types of agreements that state agencies can enter into in exchange for grant money.  Adequate privacy safeguards should be instituted before agencies extend contractual rights to private organizations for any data collected in connection with their participation in or funding of state programs. 
<p>
<p>
<b>What's Going On in the Public Schools?</b>
<p>House Resolution 37 directed the Select Subcommittee to examine four major issues relating to Pennsylvania's public school system:
<p>1.	the use of the public schools to deliver mental health services;
<p>2.	whether existing safeguards and procedures for protecting student and family privacy were adequate, as well as whether there were proper procedures for obtaining the written, informed consent of parents on a full range of school activities, including participation in special education programs;
<p>3.	in the Report's words:  "fiscal, regulatory, privacy, informed consent, and other issues relating to a program enabling school districts to tap into Medicaid funding for certain health services (known as "ACCESS");"
<p>4.	the impact of recent changes in federal law, regulation, and policy as they related to education curriculum, learning outcomes, and other educational standards and goals for students.
<p>The Report's findings on those four issues included discussion of the results of the Subcommittee's investigation of the activities of the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, other private foundations, and certain officials in the years 1988 through 1994 during the administration of Pennsylvania Governor Robert Casey.  On the issue of school-based clinics and school mental health programs, the Subcommittee found that "Private foundations have been utilizing their private funds in order to shape state programs for the delivery of mental health services in public schools without any oversight or regulation by the General Assembly."  It also stated that this policy had been driven by an agenda "which appear[s] to be indifferent to the privacy interests of students and families."
<p>The Subcommittee obtained documents from state agencies which showed how RWJF projects and activities in those agencies strongly influenced their programs.  For example, the state's director of the Office of Mental Health ("OMH") wrote that the RWJF's Mental Health Services for Youth project "was the prototype for our expanded mental health services under OBRA 89/EPSDT...a major OMH initiative."  "OBRA 89" stands for the Omnibus Reconciliation Act of 1989 and "EPSDT" means the federal Medicaid benefits known as "Early and Periodic Screening, Diagnosis, and Treatment."  This program is discussed in greater detail in the March 1996 issue of Organization Trends.  The state Mental Health Office began its ambitious project to deliver EPSDT services to children in Pennsylvania public schools and to bill Medicaid.  The elaborate scheme promised to transform schools into Medicaid providers so that school districts could become claim recipients for Medicaid funds.
<p>The Report notes that Medicaid law does not require states to use their public school systems to implement the EPSDT program.  Indeed, critics warn that there are important public policy reasons why the education system should not be commingled with a health care delivery system that emphasizes mental health diagnosis and treatment.  Will children be referred to mental health treatment for pedagogical reasons rather than medically indicated ones?  According to the report "The mental health alternative will be very tempting to some educators and school administrators who are frustrated by their inability to improve their students' academic and/or behavioral performance."  Already huge numbers of children all across the country are given Ritalin, a drug presribed for a condition labelled Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD). Is this a real health concern, or is it just easier for teachers to control kids by putting them on drugs?  
<p>
<b>Robert Wood Johnson Foundation Shows State Health Agencies How To Shape Education Policy</b>
<p>The RWJF is funding other states besides Pennsylvania to implement its program to establish school-based health services that can be billed to Medicaid.  In 1995, nine states received RWJF grants from its "Making the Grade Program: State and Local Partnerships to Establish School-Based Health Centers."
<p><dd>	Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment     $1.242 million
<p><dd>	Connecticut Department of Public Health and Addiction Services     $1.543 million
<p><dd>	Health Research, Inc., Albany, New York     $913,799
<p><dd>	Louisiana Department of Health and Hospitals     $99,775
<p><dd>  Maryland Office for Children, Youth, and Families, Baltimore     $100,000
<p><dd>  North Carolina Department of Environment, Health and Natural Resources     $100,000
<p><dd>	Oregon Department of Human Resources     $100,000
<p><dd>   Rhode Island Department of Health     $99,629
<p><dd>	State of Vermont Agency of Human Services     $100,000
<p>
<b>Kentucky Follows Where Annie E. Casey Foundation Leads</b>
<p>
<p>The Johnson Foundation is not the only player in this Medicaid shuffle.  The Annie E. Casey Foundation has been a driving force behind a similar multi-million dollar initiative in Kentucky.  In December 1996, a small group of Kentucky state legislators who make up the state's Administrative Regulation Review Committee approved regulations funding a new $80 million dollar Medicaid program in the public schools.  Federal Medicaid monies would provide about $56 million and some $23 million would be from state education dollars.  Kentucky's Department of Medicaid Services provided the names of all Medicaid-eligible individuals under the age of 21 to the Kentucky Department of Education ("KDE").  This is the same procedure that was also followed by the Department of Public Welfare and the state's Department of Education.  The KDE then created a new Medicaid provider category -- local school districts.  Armed with their very own Medicaid billing numbers -- heretofore reserved only for health care institutions and practitioners licensed under state law -- school districts are now free to supplement what they consider their meager education budgets with "free" federal money from the Medicaid program.
<p>The KDE and the local school districts claim that children needing "special services" can now get them -- because Medicaid will pay for them.  These are services the schools are required to provide after all.  The regulations, however, allow the Medicaid program to be billed for all sorts of "physical and mental health services" provided not by licensed health care professionals, but by school personnel -- such as guidance counselors -- whose licensure or certification is assured by the "Kentucky Education Professionals Standards Board."
<p>Kentucky parents testified that they were concerned not only for the fiscal ramifications of this new program, but also, most importantly, for the welfare of the school children involved.  While state officials tout the program's potential for providing services to the state's most vulnerable children, the poor and disabled, they ignore the possibility that these children will be harmed, physically and emotionally, and that parents' rights to oversee and provide proper care for their children's needs will be infringed.  No Kentucky statutes provide standards for the administration of this program.  All of these concerns, however, apparently pale in comparison to the prospect that Kentucky's education bureaucracy will receive $80 million dollars in federal and state money.
<p>Pennsylvania's Committee on Education has aired its finding of facts before members of the state General Assembly.  It is hoped that hearings will be held soon in Kentucky, and that other states may follow suit.
<p>Two things are clear.  First, the giants of American philanthropy have directed their efforts again to the promotion of programs that intrude into areas that should remain the province of the family, not the state.  Second, they have done so in a manner that undermines the democratic process by excluding meaningful public discourse and flouting the authority of elected representatives.  
<p>Back room policymaking -- for that is what the "public-private partnership" is -- is being subjected to the glare of public scrutiny.  The Pennsylvania legislature has undertaken an important public service by exposing how private monies are used to initiate and implement state regulatory programs that ultimately are funded by the taxpayers.  How will Pennsylvania taxpayers respond?
<p>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=3 WIDTH="80%" BORDER=3 ALIGN="MIDDLE" V ALIGN="RIGHT">
<TR><TD>The Select Subcommittee's findings and recommendations are summarized in a report available from Rep. Samuel E. Rohrer, Chairman of the Select Subcommittee on House Resolution 37.  Room 423 South Office Building, Harrisburgh, PA  17120-2020
<p><b><center>EXCERPTS OF COMMITTEE REPORT:</center></b>
<p><blockquote>"When Executive Branch officials accept conditions in return for private funds, and without legislative oversight, this raises the disturbing question of whether the program was adopted because it best reflected legislative intent . . . or whether those objectives were compromised by the desirability of obtaining money from a private organization with its own notion of the common good.  It may be unclear, perhaps even in the bureaucracy's own collective mind, as to whether components of its program were adopted on the basis of money or merit."</blockquote>
<p><blockquote>"It is one thing to seek change, it is quite another when changes in public policy are influenced by the offering of private money to state governmental institutions, especially when those changes vitally affect individuals' privacy ... and dramatically affect the public treasury, all without ever approaching the General Assembly....  Rather, the changes sought are purchased from executive agencies, absent necessary statutory limits and protection, and then the agencies -- and these `purchasers of public policy' -- turn to the legislative branch with bloated budgets -- the consequences of their acts -- seeking continued funding of programs already administratively implemented under the inducement of private grant moneys."</blockquote>
<p><blockquote>"The availability of the mental health option for educators, together with the fact that federal and state taxpayers, rather than the school district, will pick up the cost, is likely to lead to a gross misutilization of Medicaid resources for reimbursing services that would not have been indicated as medically necessary if the child had accessed the Medicaid system through sources other than the public school system."</blockquote>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<br>
<br>
